<DIV1 N="1" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000034.tif">

<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="1">
<HEAD>I. Loue god, and drede.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[A.D. 1400]</P><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 98.]</P><P>[21 stanzas of 8, <I>abab bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Eche man be war, that bereth a state,</L>
<L>Of counseil of double entendement,</L>
<L>Of tyrauntrye, and preuey hate,</L>
<L N="4">And synguler profit by fals assent,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ong to &yogh;yue Iugement.</L>
<L>In Euenhede, Lawe &yogh;e lede.</L>
<L>Worche be good auisement.</L>
<L N="8">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Drede god, and knowe thy selue,</L>
<L>That ouer puple hast gouernaunce.</L>
<L>Noght for the loue of ten or twelue,</L>
<L N="12">Brynge not a Comone in greuaunce.</L>
<L>Make vnyte ther was distaunce.</L>
<L>Weye o lawe in euenhede,</L>
<L>Bytwen ffauour and vengeaunce.</L>
<L N="16">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche mannys gouernours</L>
<L>Of hous or lordshipe or cite,</L>
<L>The puple is godes, and not &yogh;oures,</L>
<L N="20">Thow they be soget to &yogh;oure degre.</L>
<L>Gouerne the puple in vnyte,</L>
<L>In the comaundements that god bede,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e wole lyue in charite.</L>
<L N="24">Knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="2"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche man wot, that hath wyt,</L>
<L>These worldes goodes beth not his.</L>
<L>Alle is godes; he oweth hit,</L>
<L N="28">And land and see, and pyne and blis.</L>
<L>God wole haue rekenyng, ywys,</L>
<L>Of men and cloth, the leste shrede,</L>
<L>Thy getyng, thy holding, thy spendyng mys.</L>
<L N="32">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man of his owen hath no thyng;</L>
<L>Man is goddis, and al god sent.</L>
<L>God wole haue rekenyng</L>
<L N="36">Of ryht and wrong, how it is went.</L>
<L>Man, not nys thyn, alle god lent,</L>
<L>And borwed thyng mot home ful nede;</L>
<L>And &yogh;ut thy soule is goddis rent:</L>
<L N="40">Quyte that wele in loue and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Serue god for helle drede,</L>
<L>ffle fro synne and al vys.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e loue god for heuen mede,</L>
<L N="44">&YOGH;yue hym thyn hert fro fleschly delys.</L>
<L>ffor worldly wys is gostly nys,</L>
<L>And fooles erande may not spede.</L>
<L>In begynnyng to be wys</L>
<L N="48">Knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &yogh;e wole wyte, thus mowe &yogh;e lere:</L>
<L>What man pursueth his soule to saue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hym be lef of god to here,</L>
<L N="52">He ableth hym self mercy to haue.</L>
<L>Richesse<MILESTONE N="98b" UNIT="folio"> and hele maketh wylde men raue,</L>
<L>That to vertues take non hede.</L>
<L>Er thy soule be fendes knaue,</L>
<L N="56">Knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="3"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That man that wole be gouerned by wyt,</L>
<L>ffle fro foly, and worldis delys;</L>
<L>Loke his charge how it is knyt,</L>
<L N="60">And take counseil that is wys;</L>
<L>ffolwe mesure in euene syse;</L>
<L>Lete no falshed blome ne sede.</L>
<L>And lawe be kept, no folk nyl ryse.</L>
<L N="64">Than seruest god in loue and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whanne a fool stereth a barge,</L>
<L>Hym self and al the folke is shent.</L>
<L>There as conscience is large,</L>
<L N="68">By wrath or mede the doom is went.</L>
<L>The bowe of goddis wrath is bent</L>
<L>On hem that deth not that god bede.</L>
<L>War wordes of dowble entendement,</L>
<L N="72">Knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Gif a kyngdom falle a chaunce</L>
<L>That al the rewme myght greue,</L>
<L>A&yogh;en that make an ordinaunce,</L>
<L N="76">To kepe &yogh;ow euere fro suche myscheue;</L>
<L>And chastise hem that matere meue:</L>
<L>Make othere take ensaumple treuth to hede.</L>
<L>Who so is wys, his werkys preue.</L>
<L N="80">Loue god, and &yogh;e thar not drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Goddis bowe of wratthe on vs was bent;</L>
<L>There we thenke al to lyte.</L>
<L>His &yogh;erde of loue on summe is lent,</L>
<L N="84">With swerd of vengeaunce he summe doth smyte.</L>
<L>The brydell with teeth thay byte</L>
<L>That of god taken non hede.</L>
<L>Or fendys alle &yogh;oure werkys wryte,</L>
<L N="88">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="4"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Why pore men don riche reuerence,</L>
<L>Two skylles y fynde therfore:</L>
<L>To tyrauntes don hem greuaunce,</L>
<L N="92">To rewe and a&yogh;en restore.</L>
<L>Goode men for loue they worshipe more,</L>
<L>That don hem good, and help at nede;</L>
<L>ffor god seeth thurgh euery bore.</L>
<L N="96">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche man wot, that bereth estate,</L>
<L>Why they hit resceyue, and to what wyse.</L>
<L>Worship for drede is preue hate;</L>
<L N="100">Suche worship of frendes men schold refuyse.</L>
<L>In loue and drede worshipe the wyse.</L>
<L>Be suget to resoun in lengthe <MILESTONE N="99a" UNIT="folio">and brede,</L>
<L>ffor god seeth thurgh eche mysse.</L>
<L N="104">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; As long as man doth wrong,</L>
<L>He maketh god his ful foo;</L>
<L>The more he dwelleth theryn long,</L>
<L N="108">To his soule he encreseth woo.</L>
<L>Er he fele het, y rede say hoo,</L>
<L>Er his soule glowe as glede.</L>
<L>Haue heuene, or helle: chese of two.</L>
<L N="112">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The man withoute charitee</L>
<L>May neuere wynne heuen blisse.</L>
<L>As thou wolde men dede for the,</L>
<L N="116">Do thou so liche eche man haue hisse;</L>
<L>ffor all that euere is goten mysse,</L>
<L>Mot be rekened, a drope &yogh;e shede.</L>
<L>Thes worldis good and thou mon kysse.</L>
<L N="120">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="5"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffalse men bye helle ful dere.</L>
<L>That taken with wrong, are goddis theues;</L>
<L>They han here heuene in this world here;</L>
<L N="124">After in helle, huge myscheues.</L>
<L>What they byleue, here werkys preues</L>
<L>Arn heretikes, and out of the Crede.</L>
<L>Why god doth loue, why god doth greues,</L>
<L N="128">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, synne not in ouerhope;</L>
<L>Thou wynnest not goddis mercie with fight;</L>
<L>Hit wolde brynge the in wanhope,</L>
<L N="132">To wene no mercy thou hauen myght.</L>
<L>Alle thyng is nombred in goddis sight,</L>
<L>The leste tryp that euere &yogh;e trede.</L>
<L>His mercy is medled with his right.</L>
<L N="136">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Mannes conscience wil hym telle,</L>
<L>Riche and pore, fool and wyse,</L>
<L>Whether he be worthi heuene or helle</L>
<L N="140">To resceyue, after his seruyce.</L>
<L>Eche man auyse hym, that is wys,</L>
<L>Pore, and prynce styf on stede,</L>
<L>Or vyces ouer vertues rys.</L>
<L N="144">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who that take&thorn; fro pore to eke with his,</L>
<L>ffor that wrong is worthy wo;</L>
<L>A-nother, richer than he is,</L>
<L N="148">Of the same shal serue hym so.</L>
<L>That &yogh;eueth to that li&yogh;e or go,</L>
<L>Mete or drynke, herborwe or wede,</L>
<L>God sendes y-now to tho</L>
<L N="152">That louen god, and hym wolen drede.
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="6"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; He is a fool, that doth answere</L>
<L>To a man er tale be told;</L>
<L>But after the dede deme there;</L>
<L N="156">Lete not lawe be fauoured ne sold.</L>
<L>Suche maken fals men be bold,<MILESTONE N="99b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And false men myghte stroye a thede.</L>
<L>Er charitee in hert wexe cold,</L>
<L N="160">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if a man do a-nother mys,</L>
<L>Neighbores shuld hem auyse,</L>
<L>The trespasour amende and kys,</L>
<L N="164">Do bothe parties euene assise.</L>
<L>Old horded hate maketh wratthe to rise,</L>
<L>And ofte gilteles blod to blede.</L>
<L>ffle fro fooles, and folwe wise.</L>
<L N="168">Man, knowe thy self, loue god, and drede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>II. Mede and muche thank.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 99, <I>back</I>.]</P><P>[11 stanzas of 8, <I>abab bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>IN blossemed buske I bode boote,</L>
<L>In ryche array, with ryches rank,</L>
<L>ffaire floures vnder foote,</L>
<L N="4">Sauour to myn herte sank.</L>
<L>I sawe two buyrnes on a bank.</L>
<L>To here talkyng I tok hede.</L>
<L>That on preysede moche thank,</L>
<L N="8">That other held al with mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That on, a trauaylyng man had ben,</L>
<L>He was but in mene array;</L>
<L>That other clothed in gawdy gren,</L>
<L N="12">Blasande bri&yogh;t, embrowdid gay.
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>"Loo, felow, chese y may</L>
<L>To ryde on palfray or on stede.</L>
<L>Shewe forth moche thonk, y the pray;</L>
<L N="16">Loo, here y shewe sumwhat of mede."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'Syre, y see thou hast richesse;</L>
<L>How thou hit get, whiche is thy fame,</L>
<L>In corage and prowesse,</L>
<L N="20">After thy dede resceyue thy name,</L>
<L>Other in worshipe, or in shame.</L>
<L>Men wol the deme after thy dede,</L>
<L>Thy fer trauayle, or cochour at hame.</L>
<L N="24">How serued thou to haue that mede?'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "I plese my lord at bed and bord,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; y do but strype a stre,</L>
<L>And florische fayre my lordis word,</L>
<L N="28">And fede hem forth with nay and &yogh;ee.</L>
<L>Whan trauaylyng men fare euele on see,</L>
<L>In fight, in preson, in storme and drede,</L>
<L>With moche thonk than mery &yogh;e be,</L>
<L N="32">And y wole make me mery with mede."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'fflateryng is the fendis scoles.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure awen werkys preueth &yogh;ow nys.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e skorne lordes, and make hem &yogh;oure foles,</L>
<L N="36">To playe and lawhe at &yogh;oure delys.</L>
<L>Do for a lord; and he be wys,</L>
<L>Trewe trauayle shal not lese his dede.</L>
<L>To vertuous lord al worship lys.</L>
<L N="40">The trewe seruant is worthy hys mede.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Say, felowe, what doth the greue</L>
<L>My glosyng, flateryng, play, and daunce?</L>
<L>Shulde my souerayn aske the leue,</L>
<L N="44">Whom hym list to auaunce?
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>Thou getest the thonke with spere and launce,</L>
<L>Ther-with <MILESTONE N="100a" UNIT="folio">thou might the clothe and fede;</L>
<L>I gloser wil stonde to my chaunce,</L>
<L N="48">And mayntene my men al with mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "My flateryng, glosyng, not me harmes.</L>
<L>I gete loue, and moche richesse,</L>
<L>When wel-faryng men of armes</L>
<L N="52">In fight, in presoun, and distresse.</L>
<L>When thou art old and feble, y gesse,</L>
<L>Who wole the fynde fode or wede?</L>
<L>Lete moche thonk than thy mete dresse,</L>
<L N="56">And y wole make me mery with mede."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'I likne a gloser, in eche weder</L>
<L>To folwe the wynd, as doth the fane.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e begeten hony togedere;</L>
<L N="60">To stroy&yogh;e that cometh the drane.</L>
<L>Me thenke&thorn; &thorn;ere wit is wane</L>
<L>To stroi&yogh;e the hony, and foule hit shede;</L>
<L>Gloser hath brought faytour lane</L>
<L N="64">To halle and chambre, to lordes, for mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'Thy wikked speche come fro ferre.</L>
<L>Euel thou spekest, worse dost mene.</L>
<L>Thou woldest euere more were werre,</L>
<L N="68">(ffor profyt and pilage thou myght glene,)</L>
<L>Cristen blod destroyed clene,</L>
<L>And townes brent on a glede.</L>
<L>Thy conscience is ful lene;</L>
<L N="72">Thou noldest not come ther but for mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'In wikked lyuer no good counsayle,</L>
<L>Is coward of kynde ny&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L>Good lyuere dar fende and assayle,</L>
<L N="76">And hardy in dede brou&yogh;t to bay.
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>I wolue thou were brou&yogh;t to assay</L>
<L>At nede a wys counseil to rede.</L>
<L>Were thou as hardy as thou art gay,</L>
<L N="80">&YOGH;e were wel worthy to haue good mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'Thenketh the not it doth the good,</L>
<L>Whan thou out of thy bed dost swerue?</L>
<L>&YOGH;e clothe &yogh;ow, and do on &yogh;oure hod,</L>
<L N="84">At tyme of day thy mete dost kerue.</L>
<L>Why dost thou thy seluen serue?</L>
<L>I trowe thou do it for gret nede;</L>
<L>ffor hunger and cold elles myghtest thou sterue.</L>
<L N="88">This preueth thou seruest al for mede.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="3" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>III. Treuth, reste, and pes.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Early in 1401]</P><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 100.]</P><P>[21 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>FOr drede ofte my lippes y steke,</L>
<L>ffor false reportours, that trouhte mys-famed.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ut Charitee chargeth me to speke.</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;ou&yogh; trou&thorn;e be dred, he nys not ashamed.</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e seche&thorn; non hernes ther los is lamed;</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e is worschiped at euery des.</L>
<L>In that kyngdom ther trou&thorn;e is blamed,</L>
<L N="8">God sendes vengeaunce to make trou&thorn;e haue pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Trou&thorn;e is messager to ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t is counseille to Iustice;</L>
<L>Iustice in goddis stede is dy&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="12">Do euene lawe <MILESTONE N="100b" UNIT="folio">to fooll and wyse.</L>
<L>Set mesure in euene assise,</L>
<L>The ri&yogh;te weye as lawe ges.</L>
<L>And lawe be kept, folk nyl not ryse.</L>
<L N="16">That kyngdom shal haue reste and pes.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="10"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if suche a tale-tellere were,</L>
<L>To a kyng apayre a mannys name,</L>
<L>The kyng shulde bo&thorn;e partyes here,</L>
<L N="20">And punysche &thorn;e fals for defame.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fals men wolde ases for blame;</L>
<L>ffor falshed, body and soule it sles.</L>
<L>ffalshed endes ay in shame;</L>
<L N="24">And trou&thorn;e, in worschipe and in pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whanne lawe is put fro ri&yogh;t assise,</L>
<L>And domes man made by mede,</L>
<L>ffor fawte of lawe &yogh;if comouns rise,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;an is a kyngdom most in drede.</L>
<L>ffor whanne vengeaunce a comouns lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei do gret harm er &thorn;ey asses.</L>
<L>There no man o&thorn;er do&thorn; mysbede,</L>
<L N="32">That kyngdom shal haue reste and pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whan craft rise&thorn; a&yogh;ens craft,</L>
<L>In burgh, toun, or citee,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey go to lordes whan lawe is laft,</L>
<L N="36">Whoche party may strengere be.</L>
<L>But wyse men &thorn;e sonere se</L>
<L>By witles wille &thorn;ey gedre pres,</L>
<L>Or lordis medle in foly degre,</L>
<L N="40">Let lawe haue cours in reste and pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;it &thorn;ere is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde distaunce</L>
<L>Brynge&thorn; a kyngdom in moche noy&yogh;e:</L>
<L>Ofte chaunge of gouernaunce</L>
<L N="44">Of all degre, lowe and hy&yogh;e.</L>
<L>A kyng may not al aspie.</L>
<L>Summe telle hym so&thorn;, summe telle hym les.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whete fro &thorn;e chaf &yogh;e try&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="48">So mowe &yogh;e leue in reste and pes.
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="11"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I speke not in specyale</L>
<L>Of oo kyngdom the lawe to telle;</L>
<L>I speke hool in generale</L>
<L N="52">In eche kyngdom the lawe to telle.</L>
<L>Also is writen in &thorn;e gospelle</L>
<L>A word &thorn;at god hym-seluen ches:</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;ere &thorn;an fi&yogh;te, a man go selle</L>
<L N="56">On of his clo&thorn;es, and bi&yogh;e hym pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A wor&thorn;i kny&yogh;t wol worchip wynne;</L>
<L>He wil not &yogh;elde hym &thorn;ou&yogh; me &thorn;ret,</L>
<L>But ra&thorn;ere as Malice do&thorn; begynne,</L>
<L N="60">Quenche hit at &thorn;e firste het.</L>
<L>ffor, and &yogh;e lete it growe gret,</L>
<L>Hit brenne&thorn; breme as fyre in gres.</L>
<L>Laweles nouellerye loke &yogh;e lete,</L>
<L N="64">So mowe &yogh;e lyue in reste and pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Old speche is spoken &yogh;ore:</L>
<L>What is a kyngdom tresory?</L>
<L>Bestayle, corn stuffed in store,</L>
<L N="68">Riche comouns, and wyse clergy;</L>
<L>Marchaundes, squyers, chiualry</L>
<L>That wol be redy at a res,</L>
<L>And cheualrous kyng in wittes hy&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="72">To lede in were, and gouerne in pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Among philosofres wyse,</L>
<L>In here bokes, men writen fynde</L>
<L>&THORN;at synne is cause of cowardyse;<MILESTONE N="101a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="76">Wel lyuyng man, hardy of kynde;</L>
<L>Wikked lyuere, graceles blynde;</L>
<L>He drede&thorn; de&thorn;, &thorn;e laste mes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e good lyuere ha&thorn; god in mynde;</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at mannys counseil make&thorn; pes.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="12"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What kyng that wol haue good name,</L>
<L>He wol be lad by wys counsayle</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue worschip, and dreden shame,</L>
<L N="84">And boldely dar fende and assayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere wit is, corage may not fayle,</L>
<L>ffor wysdom neuere worschip les.</L>
<L>Corage in querell do&thorn; batayle,</L>
<L N="88">And ende of batayle bygynne&thorn; pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Defaute of wit make&thorn; long counsayle;</L>
<L>ffor witteles wordes in ydel spoken,</L>
<L>&THORN;e more cost, &thorn;e lesse auayle;</L>
<L N="92">ffor fawte of wyt, purpos broken.</L>
<L>In euyl soule no grace is stoken,</L>
<L>ffor wikked soule is graceles.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[nota]</NOTE></L>
<L>In good lyuere goddis wille is loken,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at mannys counsell make&thorn; pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To wete &yogh;if parlement be wys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e comoun profit wel it preues.</L>
<L>A kyngdom in comouns lys,</L>
<L N="100">Alle profytes, and alle myscheues.</L>
<L>Lordis wet neuere what comouns greues</L>
<L>Til here rentis bigynne to ses.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere lordis ere, pore comons releues,</L>
<L N="104">And mayntene hem in werre and pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Make god &yogh;oure ful frend;</L>
<L>Do &thorn;e comaundement &thorn;at he bede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; all &thorn;e world a&yogh;en &yogh;ow wend,</L>
<L N="108">Be god &yogh;oure frend, &yogh;e thar not drede:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ere as god his frendis lede,</L>
<L>He saue&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e on lond and sees.</L>
<L>Who so fi&yogh;te&thorn;, god do&thorn; &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L N="112">ffor god is victorie and pes.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="13"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What kyngdom werre&thorn; hym-self wi&thorn;-ynne,</L>
<L>Distroye&thorn; hym-self, and no mo.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute here enemys bygynne</L>
<L N="116">On eche a syde assayle hem so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e comouns, &thorn;ey wil robbe and slo,</L>
<L>Make fyere, and kyndel stres.</L>
<L>Whan ryches and manhode is wastede and go,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;an drede dryue&thorn; to trete pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The world is like a fals lemman,</L>
<L>ffayre semblaunt, and moche gyle.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen heire dye&thorn; no man:</L>
<L N="124">God is chief lord of toun and pyle.</L>
<L>God make&thorn; mony heire in a whyle,</L>
<L>ffor god ressayue&thorn; eche reles;</L>
<L>God kan breke hegge and style,</L>
<L N="128">And make an hey wey to pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God made lordis gouernoures</L>
<L>To gouerne puple in vnyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;e puple, ne ryches, nys not &yogh;oures:</L>
<L N="132">Al is goddis, and so be &yogh;e.</L>
<L>Eche day &yogh;e may &yogh;oure myrrour se.</L>
<L>Eche man after o&thorn;er deses;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure auncetres arn gon, after shal &yogh;e,</L>
<L N="136">To endeles werre, or endeless pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche kyng is sworn to gouernaunce</L>
<L>To gouerne goddis puple in ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Eche kyng bere&thorn; swerd<MILESTONE N="101b" UNIT="folio"> of goddis vengeaunce</L>
<L N="140">To felle goddis foon in fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And so do&thorn; euerons honest kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>That bere&thorn; &thorn;e ordre as it wes;</L>
<L>The plough, &thorn;e chirche, to mayntene ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="144">Are goddis champyons, to kepe &thorn;e pes.
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="14"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The world is like a chery fayre,</L>
<L>Ofte chaunge&thorn; all his &thorn;ynges.</L>
<L>Riche, pore, foul, and fayre,</L>
<L N="148">Popes, prelates and lordynges,</L>
<L>Alle are dedly, and so ben kynges;</L>
<L>Or de&thorn; lede &yogh;ow in his les,</L>
<L>Arraye by tyme &yogh;oure rekenynges,</L>
<L N="152">And trete wi&thorn; god to gete &yogh;ow pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What brynge&thorn; a kyngdom al aboue?</L>
<L>Wys counseil, and good gouernaunce;</L>
<L>Eche lord wil other loue,</L>
<L N="156">And rule wel labourrers sustynaunce.</L>
<L>God make&thorn; for his frendis no destaunce,</L>
<L>ffor god kan skatre &thorn;e grete pres.</L>
<L>God for his frendis ma&thorn; ordynaunce,</L>
<L N="160">And gouerne&thorn; hem in werre and pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Good lyf is cause of good name;</L>
<L>Good name is worthi to haue reueraunce.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="164">Synne is cause of greuaunce.</L>
<L>Eche kyngdom honge&thorn; in goddis balaunce;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hym &thorn;at holde&thorn;, wi&thorn; hym &thorn;at fles.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue fre wille; chese &yogh;oure chaunce,</L>
<L N="168">To haue wi&thorn; god, werre or pes.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="4" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>IV. Lerne say wele, say litel, or say no&yogh;t.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 101, <I>back</I>.]</P><P>[31 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>As &thorn;e see do&thorn; ebbe and flowe,</L>
<L>So fare&thorn; &thorn;e world hyder and &thorn;edere.</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;e wynd they sayle and rowe</L>
<L N="4">To gadre worldys gooddis to-gedere.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>At &thorn;e last it go&thorn;, y wot not whyder,</L>
<L>As ende of web out of slay.</L>
<L>And hem-self stoden so slydere,</L>
<L N="8">How it is wi&thorn; hym, y kan not say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sum man dar not be &thorn;ef for drede;</L>
<L>His trou&thorn;e is vice, and no vertue.</L>
<L>In heuene he nys not wor&thorn;i mede,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at clo&thorn;es trou&thorn;e in falsed hewe.</L>
<L>Maugre his tee&thorn; he is trewe;</L>
<L>Stoken in presoun as best fro stray,</L>
<L>Here wikked wille growe&thorn; newe;</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;ey thenke more &thorn;an &thorn;ey say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Men may not staunche a comoun noys,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er for loue ne for awe.</L>
<L>After men lyue is comoun voys,</L>
<L N="20">In wrongwys dede, or ry&yogh;t lawe.</L>
<L>Who do&thorn; hem pyne, who do&thorn; hem pawe,</L>
<L>Eche on telle o&thorn;er, child and may.</L>
<L>Tho that to vertues drawe,</L>
<L N="24">Hem thar not recche what [men] say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Tak fro &thorn;i foo, and &yogh;eue &thorn;i frende;</L>
<L>Tak not fro thy frend, to &yogh;eue &thorn;i foo:</L>
<L>&THORN;y frend wole holde &thorn;e vnhende;</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ow haddest on enemy, &thorn;an hast &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP>. As the MS. has "thou," 4/116, 8/46, above, I print &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> '&thorn;ou.' In my first-edited text of some Saints' Lives (Philolog. Soc. 1862) I printed i<SUP>c</SUP> as the Northern 'ic' instead of the Southern 'ich' as I ought to have done. Dr. R. Morris told me of the mistake.&mdash;F. J. F.</NOTE> two.</L>
<L>Man, be war er &thorn;ou do so;</L>
<L>To greue the he wol assay;<MILESTONE N="102a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>When &thorn;yn enemys wexen mo,</L>
<L N="32">Litil worchipe of &thorn;e say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Oo prouerbe loke &yogh;e preue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wole to resoun bende:</L>
<L>Look what ney&yogh;ebore most may greue;</L>
<L N="36">By al way make hym &thorn;i frende.
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>&THORN;an wole &thorn;yn enemys fro &thorn;e wende,</L>
<L>Here owen &thorn;ou&yogh;t wol hem afflay.</L>
<L>Be out of daunger of the fende,</L>
<L N="40">And recche neuere what men say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To synge or preche generale,</L>
<L>Werkys of vices for to blame,</L>
<L>Summe tak to hem speciale,</L>
<L N="44">And say, "felow, &thorn;ou dost vs blame."</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he accuse&thorn; his owen name;</L>
<L>All &thorn;at hym se, knowe it may,</L>
<L>He can not hele his owen shame;</L>
<L N="48">And so, all folk wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if men speke of goddis wille,</L>
<L>To preyse werkys of vertue,</L>
<L>A good man wole holde hym stille,</L>
<L N="52">And lete as he hem neuere knewe,</L>
<L>And no&thorn;er chaunge hyde ne hewe;</L>
<L>ffor vaynglory wolde hem betray.</L>
<L>Who is fals, and who is trewe,</L>
<L N="56">After &thorn;ey lyue, all folk wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou&yogh; a man holynes preche,</L>
<L>He shete&thorn; no&yogh;t, but bent his bowe;</L>
<L>But he lyue as he teche,</L>
<L N="60">He nys not trusty for to trowe;</L>
<L>ffor suche seed he do&thorn; sowe</L>
<L>In stones, in thornes, and in clay,</L>
<L>The same he schal repe and mowe;</L>
<L N="64">So he is worthy, folk wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A lord of hym-self ha&thorn; no wyt,</L>
<L>He knowe&thorn; wele, but no wo;</L>
<L>Of pore men he mot haue hit,</L>
<L N="68">Knowelechyng of frend and fo.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="17"></L>
<L>He is wys, that can do so,</L>
<L>And wel twynnen hem o tway.</L>
<L>In sykernes may he go,</L>
<L N="72">And recche neuere what men say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Gloseres maken mony lesynges&mdash;</L>
<L>Al to sone men hem leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. leues</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to lordys and to kynges,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at bo&thorn;e partye ofte greue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. greues</NOTE></L>
<L>Wolde lordis seche repreue,</L>
<L>Glosers shuld not go so gay,</L>
<L>Ne not so hardy for to meue</L>
<L N="80">Suche wordes as they say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou&yogh; prestes prechyng hem avyse,</L>
<L>Or mynstrallis synge in song now,</L>
<L>A glosere wole a lord askuse:</L>
<L N="84">Sire, &thorn;ey synge or preche of gow.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lord vnderstondes not how</L>
<L>&THORN;e fals[e] glosere hym bitray;</L>
<L>Wolde he make &thorn;o wordis avowe,</L>
<L N="88">He wolde auyse hym eft to say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Many can stomble at a stre;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey nyl not snapere at a style,</L>
<L>And graunte purpos nay and &yogh;ee,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;ou&yogh; his &thorn;ou&yogh;t be &thorn;ens a myle.</L>
<L>Whan falsed lawhe&thorn;, he forge&thorn; gyle;</L>
<L>Half in malice is his play.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wysdom who so voyde&thorn; that wyle,</L>
<L N="96">He is<MILESTONE N="102b" UNIT="folio"> wys, all folk wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou&yogh; men in er&thorn;e trou&thorn;e hyde,</L>
<L>On halle roof he wole be sayn.</L>
<L>In botme of see he nyl not byde,</L>
<L N="100">But shewe in market, on the playn.
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="18"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh; trou&thorn;e a while be slayn,</L>
<L>And doluen depe vnder clay,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ut he wole ryse to lyue agayn,</L>
<L N="104">And al the sothe he wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Many callen conscience fleschly willis,</L>
<L>And nelen non o&thorn;ere counseil craue.</L>
<L>But soule of reson is gostly skillis,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at conscience shal hem deme, or saue.</L>
<L>ffleschely wille is fendes knaue,</L>
<L>Out of reson, out of stray.</L>
<L>As they disserue, &thorn;ey shal haue,</L>
<L N="112">ffor so do&thorn; &thorn;e gospel say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffalshed wolde trou&thorn;es tunge tey&yogh;e</L>
<L>ffor trewe wordis &thorn;at he ha&thorn; spoken;</L>
<L>God bidde&thorn; vengeaunce hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="116">And helpe trou&thorn;e be wel wroken.</L>
<L>ffor trou&thorn;e lippes ar faste stoken,</L>
<L>And false mede ha&thorn; &thorn;e kay.</L>
<L>Whan vengeaunce ha&thorn; look broken,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;an trou&thorn;e shal al &thorn;e so&thorn; say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sumtyme men halwed the holyday;</L>
<L>Now holiday is turned to glotonye.</L>
<L>Sumtyme men vsed honest play;</L>
<L N="124">And now it is turned to vilonye;</L>
<L>And paramour is turned to lecherye,&mdash;</L>
<L>Sumtyme was loue of good fay,&mdash;</L>
<L>And shameles haunted so comounly,</L>
<L N="128">Vnne&thorn;e &thorn;ey recche what men say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Summe men sowe here seed in skornes,</L>
<L>Ofte on o&thorn;ere mennys londes;</L>
<L>Summe on stones, summe on thornes,</L>
<L N="132">Summe on hi&yogh;e way, summe on sondes.
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="19"></L>
<L>He &thorn;at wel vnderstondes,</L>
<L>Amende while he mende may,</L>
<L>Make hym clene, and wasche his hondes,</L>
<L N="136">And recche neuere what men say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou&yogh; holy chirche shulde fawtes mende,</L>
<L>Summe put hem of for mede;</L>
<L>And summe wi&thorn; maystri&yogh;e hem defende,</L>
<L N="140">That holy chirche stant of hem drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at recchelesly sowe here sede,</L>
<L>Here lond of vertues ligge ful lay.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy chirche &thorn;e corn shuld wede;</L>
<L N="144">ffor cowardis, &thorn;ey dar not say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Gloseres that wi&thorn; lordis bene,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey thryue faste &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey come late,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ey wole a lord to wene</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;at he is byloued ther men hym hate,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his frendis make debate,</L>
<L>Of pore puple pyke here pray.</L>
<L>Of all degre, of eche astate,</L>
<L N="152">After &thorn;ey lyue, all folk wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffro goddis sy&yogh;t, who may stele</L>
<L>Word or werk, &thorn;e lest &thorn;ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>&THORN;e comoun voys nyl not hele,</L>
<L N="156">But loue, or hate, as werk is wrou&yogh;t;<MILESTONE N="103a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor so&thorn;nes neuere hernes sou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Who seche&thorn; wel, he may assay.</L>
<L>The good[e] lyuere neuere rou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="160">Of his werkis what men say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Of all degre, of eche astate,</L>
<L>After desert &thorn;e name ha&thorn; prys.</L>
<L>&THORN;at lord his owen worship do&thorn; hate,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;at &yogh;eue&thorn; ano&thorn;er his offys&mdash;
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>ffor in astate grace lys&mdash;</L>
<L>And wilfully wast it a-way.</L>
<L>Who is fool, who is wys,</L>
<L N="168">After &thorn;ey lyue, alle folk wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A glosere is gredy ay to craue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue hym no thyng, &thorn;ou&yogh; he bede.</L>
<L>A lord &thorn;at wole his worschip saue,</L>
<L N="172">Lerne not at a glosere to don his dede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue to vertuous men &thorn;at haue nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to god wole for &thorn;e pray:</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore mannys erande, god do&thorn; spede.</L>
<L N="176">God wil not here what glosere wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;tes ben but wast<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;oute contemplacioun.</L>
<L>ffro heritage of heuene is born o hast</L>
<L N="180">Shrifte wi&thorn;oute contricioun.</L>
<L>And werkys wi&thorn;oute discrecioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;ifte plese&thorn; not god to pay,</L>
<L>Ne preyer wi&thorn;oute deuocioun:</L>
<L N="184">God nyl not here what &thorn;ey say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sum-tyme, and a worschip felle</L>
<L>To a lord, in batayle, by goddis grace,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a glosere wolde telle</L>
<L N="188">Among folk, byfore his face,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lord wolde bidde hym voyde &thorn;e place.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou corayest ffauel, and stelest his hay.</L>
<L>Of alle degre, of eche astate,</L>
<L N="192">After &thorn;ey lyue, alle folk wole say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A cheuenteyn may fy&yogh;te o day,</L>
<L>&THORN;e victorye wi&thorn; hym stande;</L>
<L>ffor synne god mon tak it away,</L>
<L N="196">And put his swerd in enemys hande.
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>Vertues make free, vices make bonde.</L>
<L>To-day is quyk, to-morwe is fay.</L>
<L>&THORN;at knew hym-self, he wolde wonde</L>
<L N="200">Any good of him self wolde say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What a glosere here or see,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; it shulde to shame falle,</L>
<L>He knowe&thorn; in chambre preuytee,</L>
<L N="204">Telle&thorn; his felow in &thorn;e halle;</L>
<L>And felow to felow, tyl &thorn;ey knowe alle,</L>
<L>ffro toun to toun, in all contray.</L>
<L>The glosere &thorn;e comoun voyce hit calle,</L>
<L N="208">ffor non shulde knowe who first dede say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A good man do&thorn; a lord gret ese,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is a trewe officere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wel can serue a lord to plese,</L>
<L N="212">Passe not &thorn;e boundes of his powere.</L>
<L>In preuyte vnwetand he may come nere.</L>
<L>Be handles, and stele no &thorn;yng away;</L>
<L>Be blynd of ey&yogh;e, and deef of here;</L>
<L N="216">Be dombe of mouth, and no &thorn;yng say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I wolde suche a statute were,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-vpon set a payne,</L>
<L>What soget<MILESTONE N="103b" UNIT="folio"> wolde make his souereyn swere</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at he tolde in counseil layne.</L>
<L>Oft glosere make&thorn; lordis fayne,</L>
<L>Passe &thorn;e boundes of here play.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at trou&thorn;e ha&thorn; herd and sayne,</L>
<L N="224">All tymes nys not so&thorn; to say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>&para; When al &thorn;e world is &thorn;urgh sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In his best tyme is worst to trest.</L>
<L>&THORN;is world is a fayre nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="228">A fals lemman, &thorn;at chaunge lest;
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>His last ende is had-y-wist,</L>
<L>When de&thorn; ha&thorn; &thorn;y lyues kay.</L>
<L>"Litel while he mon be myst,"</L>
<L N="232">So &thorn;e executours wol say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L>&para; They rekene his richesse what it amountes,</L>
<L>Ete and drynke, synge 'hay &yogh;ol hayl,'</L>
<L>&THORN;e while &thorn;e fendis his synnes countes,</L>
<L N="236">And bryng to hym &thorn;e countertayl;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hard paynes hym assaile.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; berkande fendis brou&yogh;t to bay,</L>
<L>What helpe&thorn; his riches or wys counsaile?</L>
<L N="240">Hym self his owen tale shal say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God made oo lawe for eche astate,</L>
<L>Riche and pore in al degre:</L>
<L>Do no wrong ne [no] debate,</L>
<L N="244">But as &thorn;ou wolde men dede by &thorn;e.</L>
<L>ffor god hym self, &thorn;is wrot he,</L>
<L>Betok to Moyses in his lay.</L>
<L>Be goddis childre in charyte,</L>
<L N="248">As god do&thorn; in the gospell say.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="5" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>V. Wyt &amp; Wille.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 103, <I>back.</I>] [9 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Man, be war of wikkid counsaile,</L>
<L>He wol the lede in wayes slidre;</L>
<L>In day of batayle he wol &thorn;e faile,</L>
<L N="4">And make &thorn;i goode men to shidre.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as hay, &thorn;ey mon widre;</L>
<L>As blades of gres, his seed do&thorn; spille.</L>
<L>Gostly blynd go&thorn;, and not neuere whidre,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at leue&thorn; wit, and worchi&thorn; by wille.
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="23"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who so wist, what tresoure</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; &thorn;at worche&thorn; by wit;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader of heuene is gouernoure,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e holigost, &thorn;e sone wi&thorn; hit.</L>
<L>In oo godhede alle &thorn;re are knyt,</L>
<L>Non departe fro o&thorn;er nylle;</L>
<L>In eche mannys herte, alle &thorn;re &thorn;ey syt,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at make&thorn; wit lord aboue his wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who so wyste what wille harmes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at willefully fro wyt wendes;</L>
<L>ffro &thorn;e fader of heuene his soule he charmes,</L>
<L N="20">ffro grace of &thorn;e holygost hym blendes,</L>
<L>ffro angels pere, soget to fendes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nyl not mende, but ay don ylle.</L>
<L>Gostely and bodily hym self he shendes,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at leue&thorn; wyt, and worche&thorn; by wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In kyngdom, what make&thorn; debate,</L>
<L>Riche and pore both anoy&yogh;ed?</L>
<L>&YOGH;ong counseil, and preuey hate,</L>
<L N="28">And syngulere profit ys aspi&yogh;ed,</L>
<L>Hi&yogh;e and lowe men aby&yogh;ed;</L>
<L>Echon wayte o&thorn;er for to kille.</L>
<L>&THORN;at kyngdom mot nede be stri&yogh;ed,</L>
<L N="32">That leue&thorn; wit, and worche&thorn; by wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That leue&thorn; trou&thorn;e, and falshed vse,</L>
<L>And<MILESTONE N="104a" UNIT="folio"> lyue not after goddis sawe,</L>
<L>Suche folk god do&thorn; despuse,</L>
<L N="36">Rebell and ryse a&yogh;en his lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o puple that stondes of god non awe,</L>
<L>But robbe and reue, coffres to fylle:</L>
<L>&THORN;e swerd of vengeaunce on hem is drawe,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at leue&thorn; wit, and worche&thorn; by wille.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That ouer puple han gouernaunce,</L>
<L>Loke how goddis lawe &yogh;e vse;</L>
<L>Whom &yogh;e refuse, and whiche auaunce,</L>
<L N="44">ffor goddis loue, or &yogh;oure owen seruyce,</L>
<L>Whiche is &thorn;e charge &yogh;ow auyse.</L>
<L>Let eche man serue his charge in skylle,</L>
<L>And &yogh;oure werkis preue &yogh;ow wyse.</L>
<L N="48">Let wit be lord aboue thy wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Be not to crowele in &thorn;y wele,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nost how sone &thorn;ou my&yogh;t haue lesse.</L>
<L>Be not to sykere of &thorn;yne hele,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;ou not how sone falle in sykenesse.</L>
<L>De&thorn; clayme&thorn; eche man for hesse,</L>
<L>And sodeyn, de&thorn; no dayes selle.</L>
<L>Si&thorn; no man is in sykernesse,</L>
<L N="56">Be redy euere at goddis wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And on &thorn;y streng&thorn;e be not to bold,</L>
<L>Ne skorne no pore, ne feble of elde.</L>
<L>ffor lyue longe &yogh;e mon be old,</L>
<L N="60">In feblenes to hoke and helde,</L>
<L>In cowardys &yogh;oure corage kelde.</L>
<L>But &yogh;e had help, &yogh;e shuld spille.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at heuene blisse wole welde,</L>
<L N="64">Let wit be lord aboue &yogh;oure wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God ha&thorn; lent &yogh;ow discrecioun</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of wele and of woo,</L>
<L>Werkis of deuocioun,</L>
<L N="68">Vyces, vertues, frend, and foo.</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &yogh;e can part hem wel o two,</L>
<L>Let vyces on &yogh;ow brynge no bille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e weye of grace, and &yogh;e wol go,</L>
<L N="72">Let wyt be lord aboue &yogh;oure wille.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="6" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000059.tif" N="25">
<HEAD>VI. To lyf<NOTE PLACE="foot">read 'lyue,' <I>vb.</I></NOTE> bodyly, is perylous.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 104.] [9 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Lerne bodyly to lyue.</L>
<L>&THORN;y seruaunt, non hyre &thorn;ou pay.</L>
<L>Pore ne riche, no &yogh;iftes &yogh;eue,</L>
<L N="4">But take and gedre al &thorn;at &thorn;ou may;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; it come wi&thorn; wrong, say not nay,</L>
<L>But falsely loke &thorn;ou swere and li&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore man is the riches pray.</L>
<L N="8">Lerne &thorn;us to lyue bodilye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; There market beteres gadere in &thorn;rong,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at company &thorn;ou lede.</L>
<L>Stalwor&thorn;ly mayntene wrong;</L>
<L N="12">So may &thorn;ou wynne moche mede.</L>
<L>To reue fro pore take non hede.</L>
<L>Do as &thorn;ou &thorn;ou&yogh;t neuere to dye.</L>
<L>Say no&thorn;er pater noster ne crede.</L>
<L N="16">Lyue &thorn;ou in ese bodyly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Rechelesly &thorn;e gouerne,</L>
<L>Day and ny&yogh;t; walke late</L>
<L>At cokes hostry and tauerne.</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;at no man o&thorn;ere hate,</L>
<L>Go not er &thorn;ou make debate.</L>
<L>To lewed, lettred, and clergye,</L>
<L>Do no reuerence to non astate:</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;an men wole drede &thorn;e bodylye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Th&eacute; &thorn;at &thorn;e good wolde teche,</L>
<L>Rebuke hem, and foule despise;</L>
<L>Byd hem go to &thorn;e chirche and preche.</L>
<L N="28">ffolwe <MILESTONE N="104b" UNIT="folio">fooles, and fle fro wyse.
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>&YOGH;eue no doom in ri&yogh;t assyse.</L>
<L>ffle fro trou&thorn;e and &thorn;ou hym spye.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou be proudest in alle gyse:</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;an men wole preyse &thorn;e bodylye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Loke &thorn;ou haue sorwe sad</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ou seest folk haue welfare;</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou be mery and glad</L>
<L N="36">Whan &thorn;ou wost folk haue sorwe and care.</L>
<L>ffede non hungry, ne clo&thorn;e no bare;</L>
<L>Lete herberweles &thorn;erout ly;</L>
<L>Visite no syke, and prisoners spare.</L>
<L N="40">Loue &thorn;y seluen &thorn;us bodyly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;y man be a good seruaunt</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e were lo&thorn; to for-go,</L>
<L>Stele &thorn;yn owen good fro his hand,</L>
<L N="44">Bere on hym he stal it so.</L>
<L>Bryng hym in presoun tho,</L>
<L>Longe there for to lye,</L>
<L>Til he be fayn, for sorwe and wo,</L>
<L N="48">To swere to serue &thorn;e bodylye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &yogh;if &thorn;ou haue a damysele</L>
<L>&THORN;at serue&thorn; &thorn;e wel, of trewe lynage,</L>
<L>ffonde to make here wombe to swelle,</L>
<L N="52">Make no fors of no maryage.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if she grucche wi&thorn; &thorn;e to rage,</L>
<L>And alway fro the wole wrye,</L>
<L>Bete here, and &yogh;eue here non o&thorn;er wage,</L>
<L N="56">And lyue in lustes bodylye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thus make &thorn;e byknowe.</L>
<L>After &thorn;y dede, resceyue thy name.</L>
<L>So shal &thorn;yn horn oft[e] blowe,</L>
<L N="60">And hunte after his owen shame.
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be of feble fame,</L>
<L>Bere good visage, &thorn;y nou&yogh;t aspye,</L>
<L>Make &thorn;erof but iape and game</L>
<L N="64">In fleschly lustis bodylye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; At masse, at matyns, rule &yogh;ow so:</L>
<L>Leue dewe deuocioun &yogh;ow byhynde.</L>
<L>Speke no good of frend ne foo,</L>
<L N="68">Lete non skorneles fro &yogh;ow wende;</L>
<L>Loke no man be thy frende;</L>
<L>Lete no man thryue, but do hem nye;</L>
<L>Kepe hem pore, and to &thorn;e bende:</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;en wole &thorn;ey drede &thorn;e bodylye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="7" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>VII. Man, know thy self, and lerne to dye.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 104, <I>back</I>.] [15 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Mannys soule is sotyl and queynt,</L>
<L>Shal neuere ende &thorn;ou&yogh; he dede gynne.</L>
<L>The flesch is fals[e], frele, and feynt,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e world alone wolde wynne;</L>
<L>Is wormes mete, and sek of synne;</L>
<L>He nys neuere filt of glotonye;</L>
<L>His clo&thorn;yng is a dedly skynne.</L>
<L N="8">Man, knowe &thorn;y self, and lerne to dye!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lerne to dye, and go to skole,</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &thorn;ou fro de&thorn; may not fle.</L>
<L>Lete not &thorn;y werkys preue &thorn;e fool.</L>
<L N="12">Whan de&thorn; wole assaile &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Sende warnestor to &thorn;y soule to be;</L>
<L>&THORN;y vices fro &thorn;y vertues tri&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e sette &yogh;oure soule in kynges gre,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at lerne&thorn; wisely for to di&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche man in certayn is to dye,</L>
<L>At domesday stonde in drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere al &thorn;e worldis tresorye</L>
<L N="20">May not bye <MILESTONE N="105a" UNIT="folio">thy lyf for mede,</L>
<L>No wys counseil &thorn;at dede &thorn;e lede,</L>
<L>Ne glosere wi&thorn; his flaterye;</L>
<L>Non may helpe o&thorn;er at nede:</L>
<L N="24">ffor thy, man, wysely lerne to dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What may thy richesse &thorn;e auayle<NOTE PLACE="marg">[nota]</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ou art to de&thorn;e dryue?</L>
<L>Thy wynd is layd, &thorn;ou mayst not sayle,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou lete out bonet and ryue.</L>
<L>Loke to vertues &thorn;ou &thorn;e &yogh;yue</L>
<L>Er tombe be held to &thorn;e li&yogh;e;</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at gostly wel do&thorn; lyue,</L>
<L N="32">He lerne&thorn; wysely for to di&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Two skilles y wole telle</L>
<L>Why eche man shuld repreue o&thorn;eres synne:</L>
<L>And he wyst hym self shuld go to helle,</L>
<L N="36">Counseyle no mo to come &thorn;er-ynne:</L>
<L>&THORN;e mo brondes, &thorn;e hattere brynne,</L>
<L>Incresyng of his maladye;</L>
<L>Here nys no charite, &yogh;ut shal he wynne</L>
<L N="40">To lasse his pyne after he dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &yogh;if he wiste to heuene to go,</L>
<L>His soule be saued in sikirnes,</L>
<L>He shulde counseile all folk do so,</L>
<L N="44">Saue here soules, and do not mys;</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t for here profyt, but al for his,</L>
<L>His owen ioye for to hy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;e mo soules, &thorn;e more blis.</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;enk here-on, and lerne to dy&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="29"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thy wikked werkis in &thorn;y &yogh;owthe,</L>
<L>Seke hem wel tyll &thorn;ou hem fynde,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;y tyme ri&yogh;t til now&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="52">Loke &thorn;at fardel &thorn;ou vnbynde,</L>
<L>And shewe it wel wi&thorn; shrift wynde;</L>
<L>No fende spot vppon the spy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>And haue repentaunce in mynde.</L>
<L N="56">On &thorn;is manere lerne to dy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; While man do&thorn; synne in werkis wylde,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at tyme he nys but ded;</L>
<L>He nys not counted as fool ne childe,</L>
<L N="60">But as a man can good and qued.</L>
<L>ffor his soule he telye&thorn; no bred;</L>
<L>Here landis of vertue laye don ly&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Do comaundementis &thorn;at god bed,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;an lernest &thorn;ou wysely to dy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Pore, nedy, and gredy, &thorn;at not ne haue,</L>
<L>In goddis name &yogh;eue &thorn;at asken ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Pore, nedy, and not gredy, &thorn;at no&yogh;t ne craue,</L>
<L N="68">&YOGH;eue hem &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey ne aske nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And nedeles gredy &thorn;yn almes sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue hem no &thorn;yng &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey crye:</L>
<L>&THORN;ere nys no nede, &yogh;ifte ha&thorn; no mede.</L>
<L N="72">Suche almesdede mon neuere dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What argument may beter preue</L>
<L>Why men ben bent to don o mys?</L>
<L>Not but defaute of byleue.</L>
<L N="76">I trowe &thorn;ey wene no god &thorn;er nys,</L>
<L>Ne helle pyne ne heuene blys,</L>
<L>Paradis ne purgatorie,</L>
<L>Or elles, a-no&thorn;er heresy &thorn;ere is,</L>
<L N="80">As a best wi&thorn;oute soule to die.
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="30"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, of his owen, nou&yogh;ten haue;</L>
<L>Al is goddis, and he it lent.</L>
<L>&THORN;erof god wole rekenyng craue,</L>
<L N="84">How &thorn;ou it wan, held, and spent;</L>
<L>&THORN;y leste &thorn;ou&yogh;t, and what it ment;</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e, <MILESTONE N="105b" UNIT="folio">and lesyng &thorn;ou dede li&yogh;e;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et &thorn;y soule is goddis rent:</L>
<L N="88">So quyte &thorn;at wel, lerne to di&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whanne &thorn;ou dest &thorn;yn almesdede,</L>
<L>Crie god mercie it is so lite.</L>
<L>To counte &thorn;y richesse &thorn;ou my&yogh;t haue drede,</L>
<L N="92">In partye of payment so litel quyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou do mys, god nyl not flyte</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;rete &thorn;e ones ne twy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Body and soule he can smyte.</L>
<L N="96">Man, drede god, so lerne to dy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, synne not in ouerhope,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wynnest not goddis mercy wi&thorn; fi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Hit wolde brynge &thorn;e in-to wanhope,</L>
<L N="100">To wene no mercy &thorn;ou haue ne my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Goddis mercy is medled wi&thorn; his ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And fro ry&yogh;t, god nyl not ply&yogh;e;</L>
<L>After &thorn;e dede, &thorn;e doom is dy&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="104">Man, knowe &thorn;is wile er &thorn;ou dy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche dedly synne is a dedly knyf.</L>
<L>Why loue men &thorn;anne so ofte to synne?</L>
<L>Eche vertue is a plastre of lyf.</L>
<L N="108">He ha&thorn; fre wille; lese, or wynne.</L>
<L>To salue &yogh;oure sores now begynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holigost &yogh;oure grace gy&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Si&thorn; body and soule mon parte o twynne,</L>
<L N="112">To saue &thorn;y soule, lerne to dy&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="31"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Truste not al to o&thorn;ere men,</L>
<L>In almes dede ne preyere;</L>
<L>ffor state of soule can no man kenne,</L>
<L N="116">ffor &thorn;ey ben alle in goddis daungere,</L>
<L>In helle pyne, or blisse clere.</L>
<L>Repentaunce mot mercy by&yogh;e.</L>
<L>While &thorn;y dede is in &thorn;y powere,</L>
<L N="120">Be &thorn;yn awen frend er &thorn;ou dy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="8" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>VIII. A good makynge of iour delaye.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Against the Clergy. A.D. 1408-9] [<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 105, <I>back</I>.] [13 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Man, haue hit in &thorn;y &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of what matere &thorn;ou maked is.</L>
<L>God made the of nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="4">Al &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast, &thorn;ou wost, is his.</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er hast &thorn;ou serued pyne or blisse,</L>
<L>Seche &thorn;y werkis, and assaye;</L>
<L>&THORN;y getyng, &thorn;y holdyng, &thorn;y spendyng mysse,</L>
<L N="8">ffro blisse wolde make Iour delaye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To &thorn;y bed whan &thorn;ou shalt go,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk what &thorn;ou hast don sen morn;</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er serued blisse or wo,</L>
<L N="12">Or goddis name in ydel sworn,</L>
<L>Or ellys fals[e] witnesse born,</L>
<L>Letted pore men of here pray,</L>
<L>In &thorn;y defaut here goodis lorn:</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;ou shalt answere here iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who take&thorn; cure, he bere&thorn; charge</L>
<L>By goddis lawe, &thorn;e folk to preche</L>
<L>&THORN;ey make conscience large,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">Take ty&thorn;e, and nyl not teche.
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="32"></L>
<L>Crist his postles tau&yogh;t in speche<NOTE PLACE="marg">[nota]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffro worldis worschip to wende a-way,</L>
<L>Gostly and bodyly &thorn;e soules to leche,</L>
<L N="24">And bad hem make no iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Worldis good nes not holichirche;</L>
<L>Richesse and worschep y &yogh;ow forbede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e folkis cherche, in hem &yogh;e worche;</L>
<L N="28">Here noo o&thorn;er to don &thorn;y dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;at do&thorn; &thorn;e dede, is wor&thorn;y mede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst not serue two lordis to pay;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on he serue&thorn; in loue and drede,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at o&thorn;ere he serue&thorn; wi&thorn; iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who ressayue&thorn; benefys for richesse and ese</L>
<L>To haue his lyuyng in sykernes</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;ere &thorn;an serue god to plese,</L>
<L N="36">He ressayue&thorn; hit o mys.</L>
<L>ffor ri&yogh;t <MILESTONE N="106a" UNIT="folio">as Iudas dede kys</L>
<L>Ihesus, and after, hym betray,</L>
<L>So &thorn;ey gyle &thorn;e soules fro blisse,</L>
<L N="40">Of goddis seruyce make iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Many seyn, "god is so wys,</L>
<L>Endeles ful of all mercy;</L>
<L>God nyl not, &thorn;ou&yogh; y be nys,</L>
<L N="44">Lese me &thorn;urgh myn owen foly;</L>
<L>So dere god mankynde dede bye;</L>
<L>What greue&thorn; god, &thorn;ou&yogh; y go gay?"</L>
<L>&THORN;at synnen in ouerhope, in helle mon ly&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;ere-of mon be non iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Many wole say, &thorn;at leue vneuene,</L>
<L>"And it were so&thorn; &thorn;at clerkis telle,</L>
<L>ffewe folkes shulde come in heuene,</L>
<L N="52">So fele as shulde renne hedlyng to helle,
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>Hit were hard &thorn;ere to dwelle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; helle houndis stonde to bay."</L>
<L>Synne mon be punsched, as sai&thorn; &thorn;e gospelle;</L>
<L N="56">&thorn;erof mon be no iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That ouere puple haue astate,</L>
<L>Colege or eny o&thorn;er degre,</L>
<L>Mayntene no debate</L>
<L N="60">ffor synguler profyt of temperalte.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure rule is groundid in charyte,</L>
<L>As li&yogh;t of lanterne to lede &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>To gouerne &thorn;e puple in vnyte,</L>
<L N="64">God bad hem make no iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Beter is litel ry&yogh;twys wonne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere-of among &thorn;e pore to dele,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ouer moche geten wi&thorn; synne,</L>
<L N="68">Wi&thorn;outen desert take pore mennys wele,</L>
<L>And helpe not &thorn;e soule to hele,</L>
<L>But crye in pyne wey-laway.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soules &thorn;e curatours wole apele</L>
<L N="72">To answere of here iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Why ressayue &yogh;e worschipe &thorn;at &yogh;e haue?</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;oure vertues, or for &yogh;oure vys?</L>
<L>And &yogh;e ful worschip saue,</L>
<L N="76">In word and werk &yogh;e mot be wys.</L>
<L>&THORN;is worldly wysdom is gostly nys,</L>
<L>Whan werk acorde&thorn; not wi&thorn; wordis &yogh;e say.</L>
<L>Heuene blys, and &thorn;is worldis delys,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at on wil make iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thow may not knowe a cristen man</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou here hym say his crede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten comaundementis tan,</L>
<L N="84">And speke, and do not &thorn;e dede,
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>Ne serue god in loue and drede,</L>
<L>Is heretyk out of fay.</L>
<L>After &yogh;oure werkis, ressayue &thorn;y mede;</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;erof mon be no iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou&yogh; worldis richesse on &thorn;e falle,</L>
<L>And wolde gon bytwen god and &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Suffre not &thorn;y soule be &thorn;ralle;</L>
<L N="92">&thorn;enk, god bou&yogh;t it to make &thorn;e fre.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;y mayster a tyraunt be,</L>
<L>ffro goddis lawe wolde say nay,</L>
<L>Do as [thapostle] Poule bad &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="96">Abyde, and suffre wi&thorn; iour delay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, &thorn;ou wost wel &thorn;ou shalt dy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>What de&thorn;, ne where, &thorn;ou nost whenne.</L>
<L>And synnes wolde &thorn;y soule ny&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="100">Ay more and more rerage we renne,</L>
<L>And sodeyn de&thorn; nyl no man kenne.</L>
<L>I rede we drede domesday;</L>
<L>Be euene wi&thorn; world er &yogh;e gon henne,</L>
<L N="104">ffor &thorn;ere schal be no iour delay.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="9" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>IX. With god of loue &amp; pes, &yogh;e trete.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Easter, 1410.] [<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 106, <I>back</I>.] [24 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>This holy tyme make &yogh;ow clene,</L>
<L>Burnysche bry&yogh;t &yogh;oure soules blake.</L>
<L>ffro &yogh;ow to god, let &thorn;e prest be mene.</L>
<L N="4">To do penaunce, and synnes forsake,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; almes dede amendes make,</L>
<L>And repentaunce may grace gete.</L>
<L>In goode werkis wysely wake,</L>
<L N="8">And wi&thorn; god of pes, y rede &yogh;e trete.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="35"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; soulis bri&yogh;t in god &yogh;e glade</L>
<L>As shynyng angels out of synne,</L>
<L>In worschip of hym &thorn;at &yogh;ow made,</L>
<L N="12">To knowe &yogh;oure seluen now bygynne.</L>
<L>To stryue wi&thorn; god we may not wynne;</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e body and soule he can bete.</L>
<L>Ihesus is bro&thorn;er of oure kynne;</L>
<L N="16">ffor-&thorn;y wi&thorn; god of [pes] &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ofte han we treted wi&thorn; god o trewe,</L>
<L>And sayde no more synne we wolde;</L>
<L>And euery &yogh;eere we breke it newe,</L>
<L N="20">Thre dayes no trewes wi&thorn; hym nele holde;</L>
<L>Synne to bay many a folde</L>
<L>On soules helle houndes slete.</L>
<L>Er &yogh;e come &thorn;ere, &yogh;onge and olde,</L>
<L N="24">Wi&thorn; god of pes y rede &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Trete while &yogh;e haue &yogh;oure hele,</L>
<L>ffor sodeyn de&thorn; stomblen as blynde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e grettere lordschipe of worldis wele,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;e more in &thorn;raldom hit do&thorn; hem bynde.</L>
<L>Man, &thorn;enke &thorn;y lyf is but a wynde;</L>
<L>When &thorn;at is blowen, &thorn;ou art for&yogh;ete;</L>
<L>Holde couenaunt to god, and be kynde.</L>
<L N="32">ffor-&thorn;y, wi&thorn; god of pes &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;e mot hit shewe, wi&thorn; herte sorwe,</L>
<L>To a prest, and weel &yogh;ow shryue;</L>
<L>No&yogh;t turne a&yogh;en &thorn;erto to-morwe,</L>
<L N="36">But &thorn;enke be good al thy lyue.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; goddis sonde looke &yogh;e not stryue,</L>
<L>Ne derne mornyng counterfete.</L>
<L>Rekne wysely all &thorn;y wittes fyue,</L>
<L N="40">Wi&thorn; god of pes when &yogh;e do trete.
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The synnes &thorn;at wolde &thorn;y soule apayre,</L>
<L>To a prest shewe &thorn;e cas.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou not paynte hit fayre,</L>
<L N="44">But shewe it for&thorn; ri&yogh;t ful as it was.</L>
<L>&THORN;at shame is mede for &thorn;y trespas;</L>
<L>ffor synne &thorn;at wolde &thorn;y soule &thorn;rete,</L>
<L>Aske mercy, and seche gras,</L>
<L N="48">Wi&thorn; god of pes when &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That clippen money, &thorn;ey haue &thorn;e curs</L>
<L>ffoure tymes in &thorn;e &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>Here wa&yogh;tes, &thorn;at &thorn;ey waye &thorn;e wors,</L>
<L N="52">&YOGH;erde or elne, fer or nere;</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ey selle good chep or dere:</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey &thorn;e full mesure mete,</L>
<L>Hit seme&thorn; in skornyng &thorn;at it were,</L>
<L N="56">Wi&thorn; god of pes whan &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Auyse &yogh;ow &thorn;at leden lawe,</L>
<L>ffor drede of lordschipe or for mede</L>
<L>Holde no pore men in awe</L>
<L N="60">To storble here ry&yogh;t or lette here nede.</L>
<L>Hit brynge&thorn; &thorn;e soule in gret drede,</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens goddis lawe to plete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e rolles ari&yogh;t y red &yogh;e rede,</L>
<L N="64">Wi&thorn; god of pes when &yogh;e trete.<MILESTONE N="107a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That halde&thorn; questes or assise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at take&thorn; or &yogh;eue&thorn; fee or hire,</L>
<L>Lette not lawe fro ri&yogh;t gyse,</L>
<L N="68">Ne mayntene wrongis as master and sire.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey may be ferd for helle fire,</L>
<L>To ete here ney&yogh;ebores at here mete.</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyf shal not euere more dure;</L>
<L N="72">ffor-&thorn;y, wi&thorn; god of pes &yogh;e trete.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;e &thorn;at come&thorn; to goddis berd,</L>
<L>Resceyue&thorn; hym in clene lyf;</L>
<L>Holde non old synnes in hord,</L>
<L N="76">ffor &thorn;anne begynne&thorn; a newe stryf;</L>
<L>ffor he to god ha&thorn; drawen his knyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;enke&thorn; in skorne &thorn;ere wolde hym ete.</L>
<L>Here be war, man and wyf,</L>
<L N="80">Horde no synne when &yogh;e trete!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, &yogh;if &thorn;ou haue tan a fal,</L>
<L>Ryse vp, and no more slyde;</L>
<L>O prest, &thorn;y shrifte schewe it al,</L>
<L N="84">But hyde no synne in hord by syde.</L>
<L>In venyale synne longe to byde,</L>
<L>Make&thorn; dedly synnes to growe grete.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;oure werkis &yogh;e mot chyde,</L>
<L N="88">Wi&thorn; god of pes when &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Seuene sy&thorn;es on &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>Men seyn, the ri&yogh;twis man do&thorn; falle.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne he &thorn;at falle&thorn; in synnes alway,</L>
<L N="92">How shulde he rekene &thorn;o synnes alle?</L>
<L>But he wrot hem, grette and smalle,</L>
<L>Summe at shrifte he schulde for&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>He shulde &thorn;e prest &thorn;e oftere calle,</L>
<L N="96">Wi&thorn; god of pes when &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffoure acountes &thorn;ou shalt &yogh;elde:<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L>God made &thorn;e lyk to his ymage;</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou it wan, how &thorn;ou it helde,</L>
<L N="100">How &thorn;ou it spendid in wast outrage.</L>
<L>fforfete not heuene, &thorn;yn heritage;</L>
<L>Among seyntes &thorn;y soule sete.</L>
<L>Rekene ere &thorn;ou renne in rerage,</L>
<L N="104">And wi&thorn; god of pes &yogh;e trete.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Holy writ bidde&thorn; god sende vengeaunce</L>
<L>To kyngdom &thorn;at nele not holde his lawe,</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e and stryf and alle greuaunce</L>
<L N="108">Among prynces and pore men &thorn;rawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nele not leue goddis sawe</L>
<L>Ne counte his gynnyng at o clete.</L>
<L>To werkis of wysdom, by tyme &yogh;e drawe,</L>
<L N="112">And wi&thorn; god of pes &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who so leued &thorn;at god were trewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wolde &thorn;ey do &thorn;at god hem bede.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mende no mysse, but synne ay newe,</L>
<L N="116">Hem lakke&thorn; all &thorn;e poyntes of &thorn;e crede.</L>
<L>Serue god for helle drede</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;y soule falle in chete;</L>
<L>And loue god for heuene mede;</L>
<L N="120">Wi&thorn; loue and drede wi&thorn; god &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou take ordre or religeoun,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute charite &thorn;ou seruest no mede.<MILESTONE N="107b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;eue drynke to &thorn;ursty, &thorn;at han and mown,</L>
<L N="124">Clo&thorn;e &thorn;e naked, and hungry fede,</L>
<L>Vysite &thorn;e pore and syk &thorn;at nede,</L>
<L>And giltles presoneres, loos &yogh;e lete,</L>
<L>And burye &thorn;e dede, is charite dede;</L>
<L N="128">Wi&thorn; &thorn;es werkis, wi&thorn; god &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ere &thorn;ou hast borwed, quyte &thorn;y dette,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;y seruaunt &thorn;at reson is.</L>
<L>Loke what degre god ha&thorn; &thorn;e sette;</L>
<L N="132">Quyte hym &thorn;y dette, &thorn;y soule is his,</L>
<L>And resceyue &thorn;y dette, heuene blis;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere thar &thorn;e no&thorn;er swynke ne swete;</L>
<L>And ordeyne &thorn;e wele, and amende &thorn;y mys.</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;us wi&thorn; god of pes &yogh;e trete.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Caste &thorn;e not to couetys,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at ry&yogh;twys werryours be,</L>
<L>But loke where ri&yogh;t querel lys;</L>
<L N="140">Chastise &thorn;e rebell in charite.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere god is frend, his foomen fle;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e thar not counte hem at o pete.</L>
<L>God do&thorn; batayle, and not &yogh;e;</L>
<L N="144">fforthy, with god of pes &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &yogh;e in batayle haue maystrie,</L>
<L>And fortune serue, and god &yogh;ow spede,</L>
<L>Thank god &thorn;e victorie,</L>
<L N="148">And holde it not &yogh;oure owen dede.</L>
<L>Serue god in loue and drede,</L>
<L>And be not proud of &yogh;oure by&yogh;ete.</L>
<L>After &yogh;oure werkis, wayte aftur &yogh;oure mede,</L>
<L N="152">And so wi&thorn; god of pes &yogh;e trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if a clerk haue &thorn;urgh hap</L>
<L>Cure of soules or bischopriche,</L>
<L>He hat not bischop, he hat a byshap;</L>
<L N="156">Make o&thorn;ere after his werkis like.</L>
<L>To kepe his shep fro helle tike,</L>
<L>In folde go, amonge hem blete;</L>
<L>Saf and sounde brynge hem y-lyk,</L>
<L N="160">Bytwen god and hem to trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Benefice of holychirche first was graunted,</L>
<L>For prestis, holy lyf to lede;</L>
<L>Dryue out synne, suffre non be haunted;</L>
<L N="164">Here non o&thorn;er to do his dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e werkman is wor&thorn;y his mede</L>
<L>In felde, in toun, and in strete.</L>
<L>Teche vnwys, helpe hem &thorn;at nede,</L>
<L N="168">Byfore god for hem to trete.
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In wordis &thorn;ey sayn &thorn;ey wil do wel,</L>
<L>Take cure of soules as worthi clerkis,</L>
<L>And resceyue &thorn;e charge euery del</L>
<L N="172">To wasche synful soules serkis.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey preue hemself fooles in werkis;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; holy water nele no parischen wete.</L>
<L>Caste away Antecrist merkis,</L>
<L N="176">Go&thorn; wi&thorn; god of pes to trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Now sumwhat y haue &yogh;ow sayd</L>
<L>What is salue to &yogh;oure sore.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. store]</NOTE></L>
<L>To sau&yogh;ten wi&thorn; god, holde &yogh;ow payed,</L>
<L N="180">And arraye &yogh;ow wel &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>To resceyue god, &yogh;oure soules store,</L>
<L>His body in forme of bred o whete,</L>
<L>And kepe hym: so &yogh;e nede no more</L>
<L N="184">Eft of pes wi&thorn; hym to trete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;ou hast told al &thorn;y greuaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;an do as &thorn;e prest &thorn;e tau&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Holde wel &thorn;y penaunce;</L>
<L N="188">Repentaunce, <MILESTONE N="108a" UNIT="folio">for&yogh;ete &thorn;at nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Whan &yogh;e wi&thorn; loue god han lau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Neuere fro &yogh;ow hym &yogh;e lete.</L>
<L>God brynge &yogh;ow to his angels sau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;ere neuere nys nede o pes to trete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="10" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>X. A good steryng to heuenward.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 108.] [15 stanzas of 14, <I>abab, abab, cc, ddd, c.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Many man is lo&thorn; to here</L>
<L>Repref of vices and werkis ylle;</L>
<L>For pride hem &thorn;enke&thorn; goddis pere,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at welde &thorn;is worldis wele at wylle;</L>
<L>At a sarmon wil bid a frere</L>
<L>Make it short, or ellys be stylle.
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>Hym &thorn;at is lo&thorn;, good to lere,</L>
<L N="8">He shal, whe&thorn;er he wole or nylle.</L>
<L>We fare&thorn; as knaue &thorn;at take&thorn; his hyre byfore,</L>
<L>Serue his mayster wel &thorn;e worse &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L>Richesse and hele make&thorn; men vnkynde,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at goddis seruyce is out of mynde;</L>
<L>For graceles and gostly blynde</L>
<L>&THORN;e flesch distroye&thorn; soules store.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God sei&thorn;, "Man, y made &thorn;e of nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="16">And put the into paradys,</L>
<L>Of er&thorn;ely &thorn;ynges &thorn;at y wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To neme &thorn;at neded to &thorn;yn eys.</L>
<L>I lent &thorn;e fre wil and &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="20">Warnyng of foly to be wys;</L>
<L>At &thorn;e tre of wysdom, foly &thorn;ou sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;af for an appyl &thorn;e most of prys.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same mou&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e appyl gnewe,</L>
<L N="24">In &thorn;at mou&thorn; &thorn;e holy croys grewe,</L>
<L>Wheron y dyed for &yogh;oure gylt;</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &thorn;e herte and &thorn;urgh &thorn;e mylt</L>
<L>I hadde &thorn;e poynt, and &yogh;e &thorn;e hylt;</L>
<L N="28">&YOGH;oure heritage y bou&yogh;t &yogh;ow newe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;e &thorn;ou&yogh;te &yogh;e had not ynow</L>
<L>Euere lastyng lyf and euere more rest;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e braken my byddyng, &yogh;e benden a bow,</L>
<L N="32">&YOGH;e boten an appyl &thorn;at &thorn;irled my brest.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; water, for synne &thorn;e world y slow,</L>
<L>Saue seuene, and noe &thorn;at was my gest.</L>
<L>My loue to man it was so tow,</L>
<L N="36">Hit lasted for&thorn; and nolde not brest.</L>
<L>For mannys loue I come fro blisse to pyne.</L>
<L>Man was so pore, he had not to fyne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure gyltes greued god so sare,</L>
<L N="40">&YOGH;oure gyltes on my bak y bare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god my fader nolde me not spare</L>
<L>Tyl he had &yogh;euen my lyf for &thorn;yne.
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My puple, where greued y &yogh;ow or pyne?</L>
<L N="44">But ladde &yogh;ow &thorn;urgh &thorn;e see so rede</L>
<L>With Aaron and moyses, myn owen hyne,</L>
<L>And alle &yogh;oure enemys y drowned to dede,</L>
<L>For &yogh;e shuld kepe lawe myne.</L>
<L N="48">In wildernes y made &yogh;oure stede,</L>
<L>To &yogh;ow y planted myn owen vyne,</L>
<L>And fourty &yogh;eer fed &yogh;ow wi&thorn; angels brede.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loue I dede &yogh;ow my lawe to teche,</L>
<L N="52">Bycom a man to be &yogh;oure soule leche.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a spere &yogh;e shed myn herte blood.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore &yogh;e harme, and do no good.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue I chastyse, &yogh;e calle me wood;</L>
<L N="56">And but &yogh;e mende, y wol take wreche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, hast &thorn;ou ou&yogh;t in mynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pyne y suffred wi&thorn; &thorn;e iewes felle?</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure soules of derkenes to vnbynde,</L>
<L N="60"><MILESTONE N="108b" UNIT="folio">I suffred de&thorn;, and heryed helle.</L>
<L>Answere me, man! was y kynde?</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t y do more, canst &thorn;ou me telle?</L>
<L>A beter frend, and &thorn;ou can fynde,</L>
<L N="64">Leue me, and go wi&thorn; hym dwelle.</L>
<L>I do &thorn;e wele, why dost me woo?</L>
<L>I am &thorn;y frend, &thorn;ou art my foo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere y &yogh;eue pes, &thorn;ou makest debate.</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;ere y loue, &thorn;ou dost hate,</L>
<L>And stekest me wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e &yogh;ate.</L>
<L>My worldys goodis &thorn;ou holdest me fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, &thorn;ou dost as a thef</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at hat holycherche gre,</L>
<L>Whan men wold take hem wi&thorn; repref,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to chirche he wole fle.</L>
<L>So do&thorn; man &thorn;at is in gref</L>
<L N="76">Or in syknes; &thorn;an calle&thorn; he me.
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>And &yogh;ut, man, &thorn;ou art me so lef,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mercy and ru&thorn;e y bowe to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if y byd &thorn;e my lawe to fulfille,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;ou hauntest &thorn;y synne, and wonest &thorn;eryn stille.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hatest all &thorn;at loue my name.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost &thorn;ou seruest so gret blame:</L>
<L>How darst &thorn;ou byd me, for shame,</L>
<L N="84">To bowe to &thorn;e or worche &thorn;y wille?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, &thorn;ou to my lawe art knyt;</L>
<L>Why ho[l]ddest &thorn;ou werre agaynes me,</L>
<L>My worldis goodis in hord to pyt</L>
<L N="88">Fro pore &thorn;at &thorn;y bre&thorn;eren be?</L>
<L>Art &thorn;ou not warned by holy writ?</L>
<L>I made, and bou&yogh;te hem as dere as &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Hit is wanhope go&thorn; byfore &yogh;oure wit.</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at &yogh;e hyde, ful bry&yogh;t y se.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e pyne y dede for &yogh;ow dry&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue &thorn;yn herte, wi&thorn; teres of &thorn;yn ey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Repente sore for &thorn;y trespas!</L>
<L N="96">So ly&yogh;tly my&yogh;t &thorn;ou come to gras,</L>
<L>To heuene, to &thorn;at wor&thorn;y plas,</L>
<L>To by&yogh;e to &thorn;e, on rode gan dy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, how darst &thorn;ou my lawe preche,</L>
<L N="100">And telle &thorn;e articles of &thorn;e fay?</L>
<L>My wit word, wi&thorn; &thorn;y mou&thorn; teche,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;y werkis &thorn;ou seyst hit nay?</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; theues and wi&thorn; spouse breche</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;ou delest and rennest ny&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L>In pyne &thorn;ou sechest &thorn;yn owen wreche.</L>
<L>Thow temptest me to be wra&thorn;&thorn;eful ay.</L>
<L>I mad &thorn;e wys and fayre, angels pere,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;ou makest &thorn;e fool, and foul fendis fere.</L>
<L>&THORN;y ly&yogh;tnes &thorn;ou spendest in harlotrye;</L>
<L>&THORN;y streng&thorn;e, in wra&thorn;&thorn;e and tyrauntrye;</L>
<L>&THORN;y fayrenesse, in pryde and lecherye.</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;ou settest at nou&yogh;t, y bou&yogh;t so dere.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To greue me, men &thorn;enke it game</L>
<L>To breke &thorn;e lawe &thorn;at y &thorn;e bed;</L>
<L>In despyt, forswere name,</L>
<L N="116">By woundis y had in handis and hed.</L>
<L>I do &thorn;e worschipe, &thorn;ou dost me shame;</L>
<L>I &yogh;af &thorn;e lyf, &thorn;ou &yogh;af me ded,</L>
<L>Mirre and galle to drynke wi&thorn; grame.</L>
<L N="120">I &yogh;eue &thorn;e my body in fourme of bred.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e fare wi&thorn; me, as gest his yn do&thorn; borwe,</L>
<L>Resceyue to-day, and put me out to <MILESTONE N="109a" UNIT="folio">morwe.</L>
<L>Agayn to synne whan &yogh;e go,</L>
<L N="124">Shamely &yogh;e put me &yogh;ow fro.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e desyre I be &yogh;oure foo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e gete but wreche and dowble sorwe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &yogh;e defoule my holy place,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at turne&thorn; &thorn;e chirche out of his gyse.</L>
<L>Holy chirche is spirytuall grace;</L>
<L>&THORN;e duwe dette, deuyne seruyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey calle me as he &thorn;at no god was.</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at cure of soules don despise,</L>
<L>ffro hem y wole turne my face,</L>
<L>And calle hem as fooles out-casten fro wyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;at sellen soules for temperal getyng,</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;ey maken skourges to here owe betyng;</L>
<L>Here good dayes ben wastyng,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey, to helle hastyng</L>
<L>To be wi&thorn; fendis chastyng,</L>
<L N="140">fulfille on hem my thretyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My swerd is fyre &thorn;at brynne&thorn; bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Shal shede &thorn;e ri&yogh;t fro &thorn;e wrong.</L>
<L>I brenne sheldis and swerdis in fy&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="144">As whirlewynd y skatre &thorn;e fals &thorn;rong.</L>
<L>No kyng shal be saued by his my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e geaunt, be he neuere so strong.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y am god, &yogh;e shal knowe ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="148">Nes non bot I, endeles long.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e may not serue two lordis to plese,</L>
<L>ffede fatte shep in greceles lese.</L>
<L>&THORN;at plesen me, &yogh;e holde hem nys;</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at gyle&thorn; &thorn;e world, &yogh;e holde hem wys.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e may not wynne, wi&thorn; &yogh;oure delys,</L>
<L>Here and in heuene bo&thorn;e, &yogh;oure ese.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In this world, to folk ful fele</L>
<L N="156">Goddis wordis &thorn;is my&yogh;t be:</L>
<L>Man, &thorn;ou serued me not in &thorn;i wele;</L>
<L>Why shulde y knowe &thorn;i pouerte?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou loued me not in &thorn;i hele;</L>
<L N="160">In syknes why shulde y rewe &thorn;e?</L>
<L>Fro my comaundement &thorn;ou dede stele:</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;ou serued, fong &thorn;y fee!</L>
<L>&YOGH;et, o god, &thorn;e fader of blysse,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e holy gost salue&thorn; soule syknesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; we agylte &thorn;e godhed,</L>
<L>Mercy moue&thorn; &thorn;e manhed,</L>
<L>ffor loue of his bre&thorn;ered,</L>
<L N="168">&YOGH;eue mercy to mekenesse!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if man ligge long in synne,</L>
<L>And wilfully flee&thorn; fro grace,</L>
<L>To sharpe my wreche y wole bygynne,</L>
<L N="172">Take vengeaunce for his trespas.</L>
<L>His enemys, I wole leten hem ynne,</L>
<L>As bestes in forestes, &yogh;ow to chas.</L>
<L>For drede &yogh;e shal nowhere wynne,</L>
<L N="176">But fynde my wra&thorn;&thorn;e byfore here face.</L>
<L>I saued moyses in &thorn;e rede see,</L>
<L>Ionas in whales wombe dayes &thorn;re;</L>
<L>&THORN;re children in &thorn;e fyre so rede.</L>
<L N="180">Dauyd slow golyas to dede.</L>
<L>Do &yogh;e &thorn;e lawe &thorn;at y hem bede,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e shal haue &thorn;e same degre.
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="46"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, I can do &thorn;e er&thorn;e to shake,<MILESTONE N="109b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="184">Wi&thorn; flood and drowtes distroye &yogh;oure wele.</L>
<L>I chastise er&thorn;e; &yogh;e sample take:</L>
<L>I may sle, &yogh;eue lyf and hele,</L>
<L>ffyre and thonder fro heuene make;</L>
<L N="188">Nes non fro my strokes may stele.</L>
<L>At domesday do &yogh;ow alle quake</L>
<L>Whan &yogh;oure owen werkis wole &yogh;ow apele;</L>
<L>&THORN;anne knaue, beggere, pore bro&thorn;elyng,</L>
<L N="192">May apere wi&thorn; pape and wi&thorn; kyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere shal non reuerence haue,</L>
<L>Ne mercy, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey wolde craue.</L>
<L>Here dedis shal hem deme, or saue.</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;an alle to me shal &yogh;elde rekenyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, &thorn;e worldis good is myn;</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou it spende tak good hede.</L>
<L>Hit is myn, and not &thorn;yn,</L>
<L N="200">No more &thorn;an &thorn;ou hast of nede;</L>
<L>Not to fostre &thorn;e as a swyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;y foule flesche in fyl&thorn;e to fede,</L>
<L>And leue &thorn;e pore in hunger and pyn,</L>
<L N="204">And fynde hem no&thorn;er foode ne wede.</L>
<L>And pore folk on &thorn;y defaute dy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; diues in pyne &thorn;ou shalt ly&yogh;e;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou shuld &yogh;eue, god dede &thorn;e sende.</L>
<L N="208">Tak kep how &thorn;ou it spende;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at leue&thorn; &thorn;e byhende,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow mon rekene, or &thorn;e aby&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="11" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XI. God &amp; man ben made atte on.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Easter, 1412]</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 109, <I>back.</I>] (15 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc.</I>)</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Glade in god, &thorn;is solempne fest,</L>
<L>Now Alleluya is vnloken.</L>
<L>&THORN;enke&thorn; how god, lest and mest,</L>
<L N="4">On oure enemys ha&thorn; vs wroken,
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>&THORN;at hadde vs in cheynes stoken,</L>
<L>Wrappid in synnes many on.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendis are flowen, &thorn;e cheynes are broken,</L>
<L N="8">And god and man are wel at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffirst whan god wi&thorn; man was wro&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Adam forfeted for his vys,</L>
<L>Man to angels was so lo&thorn;,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;ey dreuen hym out of paradys.</L>
<L>To amende here foly, god so wys,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fals iewes let hym slon;</L>
<L>Here raunsom was his blod o prys;</L>
<L N="16">So was god and man at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &yogh;it a ferly more byfelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god dede &thorn;urgh his grete my&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;e soules he loued, he fet fro helle</L>
<L N="20">To paradys among his angels bry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Hem &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at was a wonder sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Among here frendes, brynge here foon.</L>
<L>Al on wrong, god made ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="24">So made god angels and man at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The &thorn;ridde saw&yogh;tenyng mowe &yogh;e proue.</L>
<L>When posteles stryuen for hi&yogh;e degre,</L>
<L>God spak to hem a word of loue,</L>
<L N="28">And seyde, "pes wi&thorn; &yogh;ow be!</L>
<L>Elles &yogh;e may not folwe me,</L>
<L>But &yogh;e will in my gates gon."</L>
<L>So god bond man in charite,</L>
<L N="32">Byddis man and man be wel at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The fer&thorn;e saw&yogh;tenyng, god vs tau&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;at best may kepe eche in state.</L>
<L>Let body and soule to-gydre be sau&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="36">Kepe god<MILESTONE N="110a" UNIT="folio"> wi&thorn;-yn &yogh;oure ynnere &yogh;ate.
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>For who so loue&thorn; &thorn;ere god do&thorn; hate,</L>
<L>Is bersell to his owen flon.</L>
<L>We ben vnkynde, wi&thorn; god debate,</L>
<L N="40">ffor euere he profre&thorn; to ben at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The fyfte saw&yogh;tnyng, synne refuse.</L>
<L>Let eche man haue &thorn;at shulde ben his.</L>
<L>On mannys syde, repentaunce do&thorn; rise,</L>
<L N="44">And on goddis syde, mercy is;</L>
<L>&THORN;ay trete&thorn; of pynes and of blis.</L>
<L>Repentaunce make&thorn; wepyng mon.</L>
<L>When repentaunce and mercy kys,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;an is god and man at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thow made not &thorn;y self; god dede &thorn;e make,</L>
<L>Put soule of resoun in flesche so frele.</L>
<L>God can leue, god can take,</L>
<L N="52">Richesse, streng&thorn;, fayrnesse, and hele.</L>
<L>He is victorye in batayles fele,</L>
<L>Can sle soule, blod, and bon.</L>
<L>Nes non fro his strokes may stele.</L>
<L N="56">Glade in god, &yogh;e ben at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God &yogh;af er&thorn;e to mankynde,</L>
<L>And heuene to hem &thorn;at wole be wys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holden his lawe, haue hym in mynde;</L>
<L N="60">And helle to hem &thorn;at wole be nys.</L>
<L>In oure fre wille, &thorn;e choys it lys,</L>
<L>Heuene, or helle, to haue that on.</L>
<L>In heuene, and &yogh;e wole haue delys,</L>
<L N="64">Let body and soule be wel at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God may say, fern &yogh;ere, folk were fayn</L>
<L>To resceyue me ymydde here brest;</L>
<L>On morwe &thorn;ey put me out a&yogh;ayn;</L>
<L N="68">In my palays &thorn;ey made &thorn;e fendis nest.
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="49"></L>
<L>To lityl whyle y was here gest.</L>
<L>My loue y loste, y make my mon.</L>
<L>Let god now lengere wi&thorn; &yogh;ow rest,</L>
<L N="72">Now god and man is wel at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Folk &thorn;at were fendis fere,</L>
<L>Sulpid in synne derk as ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Now are &thorn;ey fayre angels pere,</L>
<L N="76">As shynyng sune in goddis sy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue resceyued &yogh;oure god of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ay&thorn;er in o&thorn;er, &yogh;oure wille is on.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure hertys were heuy, &thorn;ey may be li&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="80">Glade in god, &yogh;e ben at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, and &yogh;e holde my lawe,</L>
<L>All &thorn;yn enemys shal &thorn;e drede;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou stonde of me non awe,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;yn enemys outeray &thorn;e in dede.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere as I my frendis lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey shul not sporne at stok ne ston.</L>
<L>In all here werkis &thorn;ey shal wel spede,</L>
<L N="88">&YOGH;if god and man be wel at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Myn enemys, y shal reue here sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue syknes and drede, pouert and wo;</L>
<L>My frendis, y &yogh;eue sy&yogh;t and my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="92">Richesse, streng&thorn;e ouer here foo;</L>
<L>Hem thar not drede, where &thorn;ey go,</L>
<L>Here wele and worschip, in euery won.</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &yogh;e be syker, kepe &yogh;ow so.</L>
<L N="96">Now god and &yogh;e are<MILESTONE N="110b" UNIT="folio"> wel at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, y aske no &thorn;yng of &thorn;yn.</L>
<L>For loue, my loued in helle y sou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue me &thorn;y loue, &thorn;y soule is myn;</L>
<L N="100">Or &yogh;eue it hym &thorn;at it<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. ha&thorn; it]</NOTE> derrere bou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="50"></L>
<L>Suffre pyne for &thorn;e, me nedid nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In hed, in hand, in foot, ne ton.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure gyltis y bare in herte and &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="104">I made my fadir and &yogh;ow at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sum of my kyndenes, &yogh;e my&yogh;te me quyte.</L>
<L>Do &thorn;re wordis of my comandement:</L>
<L>My name, my pyle take not in despite;</L>
<L N="108">Rule wel &thorn;y selue in good atent.</L>
<L>Thow nost how sone be after sent,</L>
<L>To &yogh;elde rekenyng of goddis lon.</L>
<L>The rolles of rerage &thorn;e fendis han brent,</L>
<L N="112">ffor god and man is wel at on.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou me loued, &thorn;ou wolde me leue,</L>
<L>And do my lawe, and holde it trewe.</L>
<L>How my&yogh;test &thorn;ou me more repreue</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;an leue my lawe, and tak[e] newe?</L>
<L>&THORN;y vyces wole make &thorn;y soule to rewe:</L>
<L>In derkenes neuere sonne shon;</L>
<L>Vertues shyne bry&yogh;t of hewe.</L>
<L N="120">Holde goddis lawe, &yogh;e ben at on.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="12" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XII. God saue the kyng, and kepe the croun.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Easter, 1413.] [<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 110, <I>back.</I>] [19 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Glade in god, call hom &yogh;oure herte,</L>
<L>In ioye and blisse &yogh;oure mer&thorn;e encres,</L>
<L>And kepe goddis lawe in querte;</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;es holy tyme, lete sorwe ases.</L>
<L>Among oure self, god sende vs pes!</L>
<L>&THORN;erto eche man be boun:</L>
<L>To letten fooles of here res,</L>
<L N="8">Stonde wi&thorn; &thorn;e kyng, mayntene &thorn;e croun.
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What do&thorn; a kynges crowne signyfye,</L>
<L>Whan stones and floures on sercle is bent?</L>
<L>Lordis, comouns, and clergye</L>
<L N="12">To ben all at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>at</I> is added by another hand.</NOTE> on assent.</L>
<L>To kepe &thorn;at crowne, take good tent,</L>
<L>In wode, in feld, in dale, and downe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e leste lyge-man, wi&thorn; body and rent,</L>
<L N="16">He is a parcel of &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What signyfye&thorn; &thorn;e stones aboute?</L>
<L>Richesse, streng&thorn;e, and gret bounte;</L>
<L>Oure townes and castels, &thorn;e reme wi&thorn;-oute,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;ey are oure stones of gret pouste.</L>
<L>In pes &thorn;ey kepe all &thorn;is contre,</L>
<L>Holynes, contemplacioun.</L>
<L>God, let hem neuer skaterid be,</L>
<L N="24">And saue &thorn;e kyng, and kepe &thorn;e crowne!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; By-&yogh;onde &thorn;e see, and we had nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But all oure enemys so ney&yogh;e vs were,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; all here gold were hider brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="28">I wolde set hit at lytel store.</L>
<L>Oure enemys wolde coke &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ordynaunce and habergeoun,</L>
<L>Wynne &thorn;at, and wel more:</L>
<L N="32">Oure landes, oure lyues, &thorn;e reme, &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if we among oure self debate,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ende&thorn; floure of chyualrie.</L>
<L>Alle o&thorn;ere londis &thorn;at do&thorn; vs hate,</L>
<L N="36">Oure feblenes wole aspye;</L>
<L>On euery syde &thorn;ey<MILESTONE N="111a" UNIT="folio"> wole in hye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stalwor&thorn;e cast &thorn;e feble adoun.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ey wi&thorn; my&yogh;t haue maystrye,</L>
<L N="40">ffro &thorn;e ri&yogh;t heire wolde take &thorn;e crowne.
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if sercle, and floures, and riche stones,</L>
<L>Were eche a pece fro o&thorn;er flet;</L>
<L>Were &thorn;e crowne broken ones,</L>
<L N="44">Hit were ful hard a&yogh;en to knet.</L>
<L>Auyse &yogh;ow er &yogh;e suffre &thorn;at fit;</L>
<L>Amende, &yogh;e &thorn;at mende mown!</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at ben wysest, cast &yogh;oure wyt;</L>
<L N="48">Stonde wi&thorn; &thorn;e kyng to kepe &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To kepe &thorn;e crowne, god graunte &yogh;ow grace,</L>
<L>And let it neuere be to-broken;</L>
<L>For word of wynd lityl trespase;</L>
<L N="52">Non harm nys don, &thorn;ou&yogh; word be spoken.</L>
<L>Let wysdom be vnloken,</L>
<L>Apert and preuyly to rowne.</L>
<L>For non euyll wille no man be wroken,</L>
<L N="56">But stonde wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t, mayntene &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A man my&yogh;te be forborn</L>
<L>Fer fro a kynges place,</L>
<L>Wolde make a kyng to be forsworn</L>
<L N="60">To lette &thorn;e lawe, it most not passe,</L>
<L>And make hym wene &thorn;at he grace,</L>
<L>And holy in condicioun,</L>
<L>And mayntene hym in his trespace,</L>
<L N="64">While he pyke&thorn; &thorn;e stones out of &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A kyngdom must be gouerned by ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To chastyse false &thorn;at ar aspyed.</L>
<L>Falsed and trou&thorn;e to-gydre wole fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="68">Til oon &thorn;at o&thorn;er ha&thorn; distroyd;</L>
<L>Til trou&thorn;e be fro treson tryed,</L>
<L>Shal neuere be pes in regyon.</L>
<L>In all kyngdomes &thorn;at man ha&thorn; gyed,</L>
<L N="72">To &thorn;e place of vertues, god geue&thorn; &thorn;e crowne.
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou&yogh; falsed trou&thorn;e defame,<NOTE PLACE="marg">veritas</NOTE></L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e seche&thorn; non hernes to shewe his speche;</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e, of his craft &thorn;enke&thorn; no shame;</L>
<L N="76">He is bold, alle folk his craft to teche;</L>
<L>And euere by trou&thorn;e stondes wreche,</L>
<L>For wreche is goddis champioun.</L>
<L>Or wreche smyte, god be leche,</L>
<L N="80">And saue &thorn;e kyng, and kepe &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Loke of &thorn;yng &thorn;at &yogh;e bygynne,</L>
<L>Caste before how it wole ende,</L>
<L>Gostly, bodyly, what mowe &yogh;e wynne.</L>
<L N="84">Eche man destroy&yogh;e his best frend:</L>
<L>So dede Flaundres; how dede it wende?</L>
<L>Of noblay &thorn;ey han lore &thorn;e sown;</L>
<L>Pray we god his bowe of wra&thorn;&thorn;e vnbende,</L>
<L N="88">And saue &thorn;e kyng, and kepe &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God &yogh;eue&thorn; his doom to alle kynges &thorn;at be;</L>
<L>As a god, in er&thorn;e a kyng ha&thorn; my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Holy writ byd, blissed be he</L>
<L N="92">In alle tymes &thorn;at deme&thorn; ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Men do in derk, god see&thorn; in ly&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Synne, mor&thorn;ere, derne tresoun,</L>
<L>Not may be hyd fro goddis sy&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="96">To ry&yogh;twys Iuge, god &yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That <MILESTONE N="111b" UNIT="folio">lord loue&thorn; lityl hym selue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;eue&thorn; his blisse for sorwe and woo,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of ten or twelue,</L>
<L N="100">Make alle folk his foo,</L>
<L>And lese &thorn;e loue of god also,</L>
<L>For fawte of perfeccyone.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; he had no vauntage but of &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="104">He my&yogh;te were a symple crowne.
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche a kyng ha&thorn; goddis power,</L>
<L>Of lyf and leme to saue and spille.</L>
<L>He muste make god his partener,</L>
<L N="108">And do not his owen wille.</L>
<L>For god resceyue&thorn; eche pore mannys bille,</L>
<L>And of here playnt, god here&thorn; &thorn;e sowne.</L>
<L>Sette &yogh;oure in euene skille,</L>
<L N="112">Counseile &thorn;e kyng to kepe &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The fadir, &thorn;e wanton child wole kenne,</L>
<L>Chastyse wi&thorn; &yogh;erde, and bete hit sore.</L>
<L>So after, &thorn;e fadyr &thorn;e &yogh;erde wole brenne,</L>
<L N="116">When child is wys, and take&thorn; to lore.</L>
<L>We han ben goddis &yogh;erde &yogh;ore,</L>
<L>Chastysed kyngdom, castell, and towne.</L>
<L>Twyggis of oure &yogh;erde we haue forlore.</L>
<L N="120">God saue &thorn;e kyng, and kepe &thorn;e crowne!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Englische men dede maystry&yogh;es make;</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh all &thorn;e world, here word it sprong.</L>
<L>Cristen and he&thorn;en &thorn;ey mad to quake,</L>
<L N="124">Tok and slowen kynges strong.</L>
<L>God let neuere werre be vs among,</L>
<L>To lese &thorn;at blo of gret renowne,</L>
<L>Ne neuere oure ri&yogh;t be turned to wrong.</L>
<L N="128">God saue &thorn;e kyng, and kepe &thorn;e crowne!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Among oure self, &yogh;if fi&yogh;t be raysed,</L>
<L>&THORN;an stroye we oure awen nest.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; victor, wole be euel payed,</L>
<L N="132">So many good men ben lest.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it is beter bowe &thorn;an brest.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. berst]</NOTE></L>
<L>Eche man is bounden to resoun.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at ben wysest, take &thorn;e best;</L>
<L N="136">Conseile &thorn;e kyng, mayntene &thorn;e crowne!
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="55"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A comons my&yogh;t sone be shent,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen kyng or gouernour,</L>
<L>And a kyng wi&thorn;oute rent</L>
<L N="140">My&yogh;t li&yogh;tly trussen his tresour,</L>
<L>For comons mayntene lordis honour,</L>
<L>Holy chirche, and religyoun,</L>
<L>For comouns is &thorn;e fayrest flour</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at euere god sette on er&thorn;ely crown.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God, lete &thorn;is kyngdom neuere be lorn</L>
<L>Among oure self, in no distance!</L>
<L>O&thorn;er kyngdomes lau&yogh;he vs not to skorn,</L>
<L N="148">And sey, for synne god send vengeance.</L>
<L>God, &yogh;eue vs space of repe[n]tance,</L>
<L>Good lyf, and deuocioun;</L>
<L>And god, kepe in &thorn;y gouernance</L>
<L N="152">Oure comely kyng, and saue &thorn;e crowne!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="13" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XIII. Dede is worchyng.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[A.D. 1414. In 2 Parts.] [<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 111, <I>back</I>.] [21 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part I. 1)</HEAD>
<L>Whanne alle a kyngdom gadrid ysse</L>
<L>In goddis lawe, by on assent,</L>
<L>For to amende &thorn;at was mysse,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;erfore is ordayned a parlement.<MILESTONE N="112a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e wi&thorn; glad chere &thorn;eder went,</L>
<L>And falsed stondis ay in drede</L>
<L>For ferd of ry&yogh;twis iugement,</L>
<L N="8">ffor to be demed after his dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In doom of parlement ofte is fauour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at afterward it harme&thorn; grete;</L>
<L>Make o&thorn;ere bold take &thorn;erof sauour</L>
<L N="12">To mayntene falsed for be&yogh;ete.
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>Slou&thorn;e vn-tyme eft mon swete</L>
<L>When it is hot, and glowe&thorn; as glede.</L>
<L>Stonde wi&thorn; trou&thorn;e, and smyte an hete,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at god &thorn;onke &yogh;ow for &yogh;oure dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lawe &yogh;eue&thorn; kyng lyf and leme;</L>
<L>To hasty slau&yogh;t, and sodeyn fed,</L>
<L>Lawe &yogh;eue&thorn; no grace to heme;</L>
<L N="20">Mor&thorn;ere, ne treson, ne forcast ded,</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue &thorn;ere mercy, god forbed;</L>
<L>&THORN;at fauour my&yogh;t destroye a &thorn;ede.</L>
<L>God in his lawe &yogh;af moyses red,</L>
<L N="24">Wi&thorn;-oute he dampne&thorn; &thorn;e dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In alle kyngdomes, here lawe is wryten;</L>
<L>For mede ne drede, &thorn;ey chaunge it nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In Engeland, as all men wyten,</L>
<L N="28">Lawe, as best, is solde and bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Eche &yogh;eer newe lawe is wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And clo&thorn;e falsed in trou&thorn;e wede.</L>
<L>Fern &yogh;er was lawe; now nes it nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="32">We ben newe fangyl, vnstable in dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To stonde wi&thorn; comons in here ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Is hy&yogh;est poynt of charite.</L>
<L>To quyte &thorn;at dede, no man my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="36">Saue onely god in trynyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;e comons vnkonnyng be,</L>
<L>God &yogh;eue&thorn; &yogh;ow neuere &thorn;e lasse mede.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mede aske&thorn; so hey&yogh; degre,</L>
<L N="40">Nes non bot god may quyte &thorn;at dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;et o wysdom mot &yogh;e lere,</L>
<L>Most profyt, and heyest honour;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure tenauntes playntes &yogh;e mot here,</L>
<L N="44">ffor &thorn;ey kepen all &yogh;oure tresour.
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e are holden to ben here socour.</L>
<L>Non wi&thorn; wrong o&thorn;er mysbede:</L>
<L>For-&thorn;y god made &yogh;ow gouernour,</L>
<L N="48">In goddis ry&yogh;t to deme &thorn;e dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lordis &thorn;at han castels and toures,</L>
<L>Alle folk stonden of &yogh;ow awe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e puple is goddis, and no&yogh;t &yogh;oures.</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;ey paye &yogh;oure rente, to gouerne lawe.</L>
<L>Let no man here ry&yogh;t wi&thorn;drawe,</L>
<L>Body ne catell hem mysbede.</L>
<L>Who do&thorn; so, god say&thorn; in sawe,</L>
<L N="56">He shal haue heuene for &thorn;at dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e lord &thorn;at wole haue good loos,</L>
<L>Stonde fast in trou&thorn;e, waxe not faynt.</L>
<L>Let trou&thorn;e gon out of cloos,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at alle folk may here his playnt.</L>
<L>Let treson be shamely ataynt,</L>
<L>Graunte hem no mercy, ne take no mede;</L>
<L>For mede wi&thorn; poyson sotyly is maynt;</L>
<L N="64">Mercy my&yogh;t cherische hem in here dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if a man wolde &thorn;e ouertylt,</L>
<L>Caste &thorn;y de&thorn; for to kille,</L>
<L>Let not a-no&thorn;er by&yogh;e his gylt,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at <MILESTONE N="112b" UNIT="folio">neuere in dede dede &thorn;e ylle.</L>
<L>Dampne no man for non euyl wille</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e gylteles blod to blede.</L>
<L>Sette &yogh;oure domes in euene skille;</L>
<L N="72">In drede of god, &yogh;e deme &yogh;oure dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who skorne&thorn; hem &thorn;at telle&thorn; hem wit,</L>
<L>Is rebell to god, &thorn;at repreue&thorn; reson;</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue&thorn; hym most, &thorn;at hate&thorn; hit,</L>
<L N="76">A&yogh;enst goddis counseill cast a-cheson;
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="58"></L>
<L>To worschipe hym &thorn;ere wit is geson;</L>
<L>For fawte of grace, vertue ben gyde.</L>
<L>To chastyse fooles is ay in seson,</L>
<L N="80">To worschip or shame, after &thorn;e dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Syngulerte is sotyle &thorn;efte.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey calle hit custom, trou&thorn;e to blende.</L>
<L>Whan trou&thorn;e wole reherce &thorn;at efte,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;an god wil vengeance wi&thorn; trou&thorn;e sende,</L>
<L>Shamely falsed to shende,</L>
<L>Drede and stryf among hem shede.</L>
<L>To preue who is goddis frend,</L>
<L N="88">Comons be witnesse of here dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Putte fro court, &thorn;at cheriche&thorn; vys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at place of vertues wolde shende.</L>
<L>Nedeles delys, and nedeles gys,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;e wastours out of worschip spende.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wit and vysement all amende.</L>
<L>Lete werk be witnes &yogh;e can &yogh;oure Crede.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; corage and hardynes &yogh;oure reme defende,</L>
<L N="96">In goddis querell &yogh;e do &yogh;oure dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A trewe man recche&thorn; neuere a dell</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; all &thorn;e world his werkis aspy&yogh;ed;</L>
<L>And falsed, for he do&thorn; not well,</L>
<L N="100">He wolde trou&thorn;es tonge were ty&yogh;ed,</L>
<L>For he shulde not telle who hym ny&yogh;ed.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;e fals &thorn;e false fede,</L>
<L>Til trou&thorn;e in preson be faste aly&yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="104">And dampne trou&thorn;e for falsed dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part II. 14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whanne &yogh;e han made pes wi&thorn;-ynne,</L>
<L>All &yogh;oure reme in vnyte,</L>
<L>Vttere-more &yogh;e mot bygynne;</L>
<L N="108">Streng&thorn;e &yogh;oure marche, and kepe &thorn;e see.
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>Ofte haue &yogh;e made &yogh;oure fomen fle,</L>
<L>Here hatest blod o brod to sprede.</L>
<L>God do&thorn; batayle, and not &yogh;e;</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;ou&yogh; &yogh;e fau&yogh;t, god do&thorn; &thorn;e dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part II. 15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To ffraunce, kyng Edward had queryle,</L>
<L>Hit was his kynde heritage;</L>
<L>And &yogh;e han &thorn;e same style,</L>
<L N="116">Wi&thorn; armes of &thorn;e selue parage;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it &yogh;oure querell dede neuere aswage;</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ha&thorn; shewed in &yogh;oure manhede:</L>
<L>On see, on land, in eche vyage,</L>
<L N="120">In dent of swerd, god demed &yogh;oure dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part II. 16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Stuffe &yogh;oure castels in eche coost,</L>
<L>Warnestor and folk &thorn;eder sende;</L>
<L>So mow &yogh;e abate &yogh;oure enemys bost,</L>
<L N="124">But not in trete, in wast to spende.</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &yogh;e assayle or defende,</L>
<L>On see or land, god &yogh;ow spede!</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; word of wynd, mad neuere <MILESTONE N="113a" UNIT="folio">werre ende,</L>
<L N="128">But dent of swerd endid &thorn;e dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part II. 17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &yogh;e &thorn;enke werre to holde,</L>
<L>Do after hem [&thorn;at] is most wys.</L>
<L>Corage of &yogh;ong, and wit of olde,</L>
<L N="132">Can telle where &thorn;e vauntage lys,</L>
<L>In dede of armes wonnen prys.</L>
<L>Whan gloser and flaterer on tapetis trede,</L>
<L>For wynnyng &thorn;ey counseled to cowardys.</L>
<L N="136">Man wan neuere worschip by here dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part II. 18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Als ofte as &yogh;e trete,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure enemys, ordynaunce &thorn;ey di&yogh;t.</L>
<L>While &yogh;e trete, ay &thorn;ey gete.</L>
<L N="140">&YOGH;e trete &yogh;oure self out of &yogh;oure ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere lakke&thorn; conscience of kny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Lete falsed growe tyl he sede.
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="60"></L>
<L>Ordre of kny&yogh;t was mad to fy&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota Milicia &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="144">In goddis ri&yogh;t, to ende &thorn;e dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part II. 19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ordre of kny&yogh;t hardest is</L>
<L>On see, on lond, on sholde, and depe;</L>
<L>He passe&thorn; relegous ywis,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey preye and faste wepe.</L>
<L>Ofte wi&thorn; ful wombe relegous slepe,</L>
<L>Whan kny&yogh;tes han hunger, and moche in drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e beter in clene lyf &thorn;ey au&yogh;t hem kepe,</L>
<L N="152">As goddis kny&yogh;t to don here dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part II. 20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; On of two, &yogh;e mot chese:</L>
<L>On lond or see or shippes bord,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fi&yogh;t &yogh;e wynne, wi&thorn; trete &yogh;e lese.</L>
<L N="156">&YOGH;oure enemys han &thorn;at eure in hord,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey wynne wi&thorn; word</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure townes and castels in leng&thorn;e and brede;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &yogh;e wynne, &yogh;e wynne wi&thorn; sword.</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;erfore wi&thorn; swerd do &yogh;oure dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(Part II. 21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God &yogh;eue &yogh;ow grace &thorn;is reme to &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>To cherische &thorn;e goode, and chastyse &thorn;e nys.</L>
<L>And also serue god to queme,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;at &yogh;oure werkis preue &yogh;ow wys.</L>
<L>And in &yogh;ow &thorn;e helpe it lys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e puple in goddis lawe to hede.</L>
<L>Do so now, &yogh;e wynne &yogh;ow prys</L>
<L N="168">And heuene blisse for &yogh;oure dede. Amen!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Amen</I> is struck through in <I>red</I> ink; but whether it is meant to be erased or not, is doubtful.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="14" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XIV. Man, be warre er the be woo.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Early in 1418.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 113.] [14 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>The herrere degre, &thorn;e more wys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gretter worschip, &thorn;e noblere fame;
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>&THORN;e herrere degre, &thorn;e more nys;</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e gretter foly, &thorn;e more blame.</L>
<L>After foly, folwe&thorn; &thorn;e shame;</L>
<L>Repreued of frendis, and scorned of fo,</L>
<L>After &thorn;y dede, ressayue &thorn;y name.</L>
<L N="8">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou be kyngis chaunceller,</L>
<L>Kepe &thorn;e crowne hool in stat;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be kyngis counselere,</L>
<L N="12">Loke no stones &thorn;erof abate.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if o&thorn;er wolde make &thorn;e kyng &thorn;e hate,</L>
<L>Or falsed ouer trou&thorn;e go,</L>
<L>Tak &thorn;y leue, and kisse &thorn;e &yogh;ate.</L>
<L N="16">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; On a mowntayne, a sete may not be hyd,</L>
<L>Ne lordis werkis in no degre.</L>
<L>A lordis werkis, wi&thorn; comouns is kyd,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at he do&thorn; most in preuete.</L>
<L>Gouernour of kyngdom or Cyte,</L>
<L>After &thorn;ey lyue, men deme so.</L>
<L>For eche a werk, god <MILESTONE N="113b" UNIT="folio">&yogh;eue&thorn; a fe.</L>
<L N="24">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A symple prest wole synge his masse</L>
<L>While his lyuyng is but smal.</L>
<L>As summe encrese, serue god &thorn;e lasse,</L>
<L N="28">Wi&thorn; benefices, ten my&yogh;te lyue wi&thorn;-al,</L>
<L>And fynde &thorn;ere no&thorn;er houshold ne halle,</L>
<L>Ne serue &thorn;e parische, but take hem fro.</L>
<L>Er god suche rekenyng calle,</L>
<L N="32">Be tyme be war, er &thorn;ey be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, do resoun &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be riche,</L>
<L>Ouer cite or town hast gouernaunce.</L>
<L>Loue al crafty folk yliche,</L>
<L N="36">Mayntene no party in distaunce.
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>Sette mendis for trespas in euene balaunce;</L>
<L>For a penyworth of harm, tak not two.</L>
<L>Rule wel mesure and sustenaunce.</L>
<L N="40">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e wyseman his sone forbed<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L>Masouncraft and all clymbyng,</L>
<L>And shipman craft, for perile of dede,</L>
<L N="44">And preuey in counseil be ney&yogh; no kyng.</L>
<L>For his mys-rulyng &thorn;ou my&yogh;t hyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at shep my&yogh;te grese vnder &thorn;y to.</L>
<L>To fli&yogh;e to hy&yogh;e, treste not &thorn;y wyng.</L>
<L N="48">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;y kyng be fre to &yogh;yue,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou not gredy to craue,</L>
<L>Make o&thorn;ere folk &thorn;e worse to lyue,</L>
<L N="52">For synguler profyt &thorn;ou wolde haue.</L>
<L>Er drede and r&eacute;pref &thorn;y berd shaue,</L>
<L>Asese of Couetys, and say hoo.</L>
<L>The man &thorn;at wole his worship saue,</L>
<L N="56">Be tyme be war, er him be woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; For to amende &thorn;at was mys,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore is ordeyned eche Iustice.</L>
<L>Lat eche man haue &thorn;at shulde ben his,</L>
<L N="60">And turne not lawe for couetyse.</L>
<L>Ne contryue tresons &thorn;ere trou&thorn; lys,</L>
<L>In tyrauntrie to robbe and slo.</L>
<L>Er &yogh;oure werkis preue &yogh;ow nys,</L>
<L N="64">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &yogh;e wole haue pes of &yogh;ong and old,</L>
<L>Let eche man haue &thorn;at is ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Let comon lawe his cours hold,</L>
<L N="68">Euene mesure, mett, and wy&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>Man, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be moche of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Mende fawtes er &thorn;ou make mo.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &yogh;e hid, god see&thorn; in sy&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="72">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche lord knowe&thorn; his astate,</L>
<L>Lyue on &thorn;at god hym lent.</L>
<L>&THORN;at borwe&thorn; moche, he gete&thorn; hate.</L>
<L N="76">Spende waste, passyng his rent,</L>
<L>For suche a kyngdom ha&thorn; ben shent.</L>
<L>Stryf wi&thorn; comons, threp, and thro,</L>
<L>To brynge &thorn;at in amendement,</L>
<L N="80">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whanne holichirche suffre&thorn; symonye,</L>
<L>And is <MILESTONE N="114a" UNIT="folio">wi&thorn; hym enchaunted,</L>
<L>And lawe of land suffre&thorn; vsurye,</L>
<L N="84">Vnkyndely synne, and shameles haunted,</L>
<L>And vicious folk auaunsed and dawnted,</L>
<L>And vertues flemed fro eche a wro:</L>
<L>In &thorn;at kyngdom, god ha&thorn; vengeaunce graunted.</L>
<L N="88">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In a kyngdom, what make&thorn; stryf,</L>
<L>No man standes of o&thorn;er awe?</L>
<L>Vnkyndely synne, and tyrauntes lyf;</L>
<L N="92">Vsurye, symonye, and letter of lawe,</L>
<L>And holy chirche rebell to goddis sawe.</L>
<L>To kepe his comaundement, &thorn;ey say no.</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;at kyngdom, god his loue wil drawe.</L>
<L N="96">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if eny folk forge&thorn; gyles,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; falsed &thorn;y de&thorn; to cast,</L>
<L>Pulle vp &thorn;e stakes, and breke &thorn;e styles;</L>
<L N="100">Lete hem no more styke so faste.
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>And whan &yogh;e be &thorn;e perile paste,</L>
<L>Kepe &yogh;ow wel fro de&thorn;es flo,</L>
<L>Fro costage, and be no more agaste.</L>
<L N="104">Eche man be war, er hym be wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e flesch ha&thorn; many frele frendis,</L>
<L>Richesse, streng&thorn;e, fayrenesse, and hele;</L>
<L>Whan it is mysvsed, &thorn;e soule it schendis.</L>
<L N="108">Richesse, rauenere of worldis wele,</L>
<L>Take fro &thorn;e nedy, to &thorn;e nedeles dele,</L>
<L>And wylde recheles as a roo.</L>
<L>Er &yogh;oure synnes &yogh;oure soules apele,</L>
<L N="112">Eche man be war, er hym be woo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="15" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XV. The descryuyng of mannes membres.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 114.] [19 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Where-of is mad al mankynde?</L>
<L>Of seuene &thorn;ynges, and it be sou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Er&thorn;e and water, fyre and wynde,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;erof is &thorn;e body wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule of &thorn;re, &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e mynde,</L>
<L>Of lyf, felyng, and of &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule fro &thorn;e body vnbende,</L>
<L N="8">Whan on of &thorn;ese lakke&thorn; ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The heued, y likne to a kyng,</L>
<L>For he is lord souereyn of al,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; foure to his gouernyng:</L>
<L N="12">Mou&thorn; and nose, and eyen wi&thorn;-al,</L>
<L>Eryn fayre to his heryng,</L>
<L>To serue &thorn;e brayn is pryncypal</L>
<L>Chef of counseil ymagenyng,</L>
<L N="16">To caste before, er after fal.
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I lykne &thorn;e nekke, moche of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at body and heued to-gydre knyt,</L>
<L>To a Iustice &thorn;at deme&thorn; ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="20">For, &thorn;urgh it, come&thorn; all wordis of wyt.</L>
<L>&yogh;if a man take ordre of kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e coler in &thorn;e nekke het;</L>
<L>And feloun forfete in &thorn;efte or fy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;e iugement in &thorn;e nekke set.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Now I lykne mannys brest,</L>
<L>To presthod in good degre,</L>
<L>Most in perile, lest in rest</L>
<L N="28">For besynesse in spiritualte;</L>
<L>In penaunce and in preyer prest;</L>
<L>Meke of spirit in pouerte</L>
<L>Holde hospytal to goddis gest,<MILESTONE N="114b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">And fede &thorn;e pore in charyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e shuldres and &thorn;e bakebon,</L>
<L>I likne to lordis of &thorn;e lond;</L>
<L>&THORN;e armes, to kny&yogh;tes, to fende fro fon;</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;e squyers, I likne to &thorn;e hondes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyngres, to &yogh;emen &thorn;at byfore gon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bent bowes and bry&yogh;t brondes.</L>
<L>While all &thorn;ys lymes arn wel at on,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;e body, in good plyt it stondes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Mannys rybbes, y likne now&mdash;</L>
<L>Flesch and skyn in body hydes,&mdash;</L>
<L>To men of lawe is to alow,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at kepes in loue bo&thorn;e sydes.</L>
<L>Rybbes, to resoun &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey bow,</L>
<L>So lawe do&thorn;: ofte in fauour bydes,</L>
<L>Tyl ground be sou&yogh;t &thorn;ere lawe do&thorn; grow,</L>
<L N="48">Ende in charite, &thorn;at no man chydes.
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="66"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I likne &thorn;e thies, flesch and bon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at beren &thorn;e body quantite,</L>
<L>To marchaundes, in perile ride and gon,</L>
<L N="52">Bryngen wynnyng, gold, and fee,</L>
<L>Make hi&yogh;e houses of lym and ston,</L>
<L>Mayntene burgh, toun, and cyte,</L>
<L>Wel&thorn;e and worschip in here won,</L>
<L N="56">And good houshold of gret plente.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Mannys leggis, likne y may</L>
<L>To all craftes &thorn;at worche wi&thorn; handes,</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e body beren &thorn;ay,</L>
<L N="60">As a tre &thorn;at bere&thorn; wandes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feet, to lykne, y wole assay,</L>
<L>To alle trewe tylyers of landes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e plough, and all &thorn;at dygge in clay;</L>
<L N="64">Alle &thorn;e world on hem standes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The toes of &thorn;e mennys feet,</L>
<L>&THORN;o y likne to trewe hyne</L>
<L>&THORN;at trauayle bo&thorn;e in drye and weet,</L>
<L N="68">In &thorn;urst, in hungere, and in pyne,</L>
<L>In het, in cold, in snow and slet,</L>
<L>Many hi&yogh;e none, er &thorn;ey dyne,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; good mete selde met;</L>
<L N="72">But after howsel &thorn;ey drynke no wyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Toes helpe&thorn; man fro fal to ryse.</L>
<L>He may not stonde, &thorn;at ha&thorn; no toon,</L>
<L>Lepe ne renne, ne ryde in syse,</L>
<L N="76">Wrastle ne fy&yogh;te, ne put &thorn;e ston.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if seruant &thorn;e maystere refuse,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seruant lyuyng sone were gon.</L>
<L>And maystres, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey ben wyse,</L>
<L N="80">Wi&thorn;-out seruant lyue not alon.
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I likne &thorn;e wombe, and &thorn;at wi&thorn;-ynne,</L>
<L>To botemeles purs, &thorn;at moche do&thorn; take;</L>
<L>To couetous, no wyket pynne;</L>
<L N="84">To glotoun, &thorn;e garner wyd open make.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wombe preyed &thorn;e mou&thorn; to blynne:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou etest and drynkest, &thorn;at y ake."</L>
<L>"To slepe," quod &thorn;e ey&yogh;e, "we may not wynne</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;e wrecched wombe so do&thorn; vs wake."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "We dulle of heryng," quod &thorn;e ere.</L>
<L>"We dase for dronken," quod &thorn;e ey&yogh;e:</L>
<L>"I wende but o mone &thorn;ere were,</L>
<L N="92">And me &thorn;ou&yogh;te two y sey&yogh;e."</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e handis, "fro mou&thorn; may we not vs were."</L>
<L>Quod<MILESTONE N="115a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e mou&thorn;, "y drank while y my&yogh;te drye."</L>
<L>"Allas," quod &thorn;e feet, "all we bere,</L>
<L N="96">And &yogh;oure bargayn dere abye."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The handes and feet, &thorn;e mou&thorn; gan preye,</L>
<L>"Let vs thre dayes reste,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;yn o&thorn;ere lymes pleye,</L>
<L N="100">Wi&thorn; felaschip, frend, and geste."</L>
<L>&THORN;e mou&thorn;, in anger he dede saye,</L>
<L>"&THORN;es &thorn;re dayes do &yogh;our best.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at tyme, ny&yogh;t ne daye,</L>
<L N="104">No mete ne drynk come in my brest."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thre dayes the mou&thorn; dede faste,</L>
<L>Tyl wombe calde &thorn;e mou&thorn; vnkynde.</L>
<L>"Vnkynde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[?<I>for</I> Vnbynde]</NOTE> thyn handes, are &thorn;ey faste?</L>
<L N="108">Stere, and lete &thorn;e mylle grynde."</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e eren, "oure heryng is at &thorn;e laste."</L>
<L>Quod eyen, "we dase, and waxe blynd."</L>
<L>Quod handes and feet, "oure streng&thorn;e is paste,"</L>
<L N="112">Quod brayn and herte, "vs wantes mynde."
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="68"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Quod &thorn;e mou&thorn;e, "&yogh;e playne whyle y ete;</L>
<L>And while y faste, &yogh;e make gret doel."</L>
<L>Quod hondes and feet, "also we gete</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at &thorn;ou spendest eche a deel.</L>
<L>We may play, swynke, and swete,</L>
<L>While mou&thorn;e in mesure make&thorn; his mele.</L>
<L>For mesure kepe&thorn; kynde hete,</L>
<L N="120">And al &thorn;at tyme we fare wele."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I likne a kyngdom in good astate,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota bene</NOTE></L>
<L>To stalwor&thorn;e man, my&yogh;ty in hele.</L>
<L>While non of his lymes o&thorn;er hate,</L>
<L N="124">He is my&yogh;ty, wi&thorn; a-no&thorn;er to dele.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eche of his lymes wi&thorn; o&thorn;er debate,</L>
<L>He waxe&thorn; syk, for flesch is frele.</L>
<L>His enemys wayte erly and late,</L>
<L N="128">In his feblenesse, on hym to stele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And hed were fro &thorn;e body stad,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er partye were set at nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And body wi&thorn;oute armes sprad.</L>
<L N="132">Were armes wi&thorn;-oute handis ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Ne handis, but &thorn;ey fyngres had?</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;oute fingere, what were wrou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>&THORN;es lymes make&thorn; hed ful glad,</L>
<L N="136">And al &thorn;e body, and it be sou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if a man hurte &thorn;y fynger or too,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou make deffens o ferre,</L>
<L>Leg or arm may take &thorn;e fro;</L>
<L N="140">To body or hed, auntre hym herre.</L>
<L>Ensample to kyngdom, y set this so:</L>
<L>And oure frendis be distroyed by werre,</L>
<L>&THORN;an kepe &thorn;e wisely fro &thorn;y foo;</L>
<L N="144">For wi&thorn; all his my&yogh;t he wole come nerre.
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God saue &thorn;is man is so deuysed,</L>
<L>Hed and body, all lymes in kynde.</L>
<L>But &thorn;ere as vertues ben despysed,</L>
<L N="148">To preye to god, &thorn;ey waste here wynde.</L>
<L>God leue &thorn;at synne may be refused,</L>
<L>And of dedly synnes vs vnbynde,</L>
<L>And eche stat in his kynde be vsed.</L>
<L N="152">God, of his mercy, haue vs in mynde! Amen!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="16" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XVI. A remembraunce of LIJ folyes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">I printed this, from my copy of the MS., in <I>Englisch Studien</I> 1897, in forgetfulness of Dr. Kail.&mdash;F. J. F.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[A.D. 1419]</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 115.] [9 stanzas of 14, <I>abab, abab, cc ddd c.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Loke how Flaundres do&thorn; fare wi&thorn; his folyhede!</L>
<L>Durste no man dygge after trou&thorn;e wi&thorn; no manere toles.</L>
<L>To wynne<MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio"> wrongly wele, wod &thorn;ey gan wede,</L>
<L N="4">But werkis of wys men were cast vnder stoles.</L>
<L>Glosers counseled lordis for to take mede,</L>
<L>To maken hem riche, and here lordis pore foles.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e souereyns were set, here sogettis to drede,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e glosers skulked away, for shame of here sooles.</L>
<L>Falsed shal neuere ben ateynt</L>
<L>Til Iuge here eche mannys pleynt.</L>
<L>Redresse, and make an ende,</L>
<L N="12">Or ellys to mercy bende;</L>
<L>Make hem kyssen and be frende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were fon feynt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Fyfty folyes ben, and two;</L>
<L N="16">Alle &thorn;o y wole mynne among.</L>
<L>To triste in trete to his fo</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; begyled hem ofte and long,</L>
<L>And hate hem &thorn;at telle hym so,</L>
<L N="20">And wilfully wolle suffre wrong:
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>It is worthy he smerte and be wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his owen skyn wole kerue a thong.</L>
<L>&THORN;at chepen moche, and not han to paye,</L>
<L N="24">And wi&thorn; his lord to homly wole playe,</L>
<L>Swere moche, and not be trowed;</L>
<L>Boste moche, and not allowed;</L>
<L>Threte alle men, and neuere on bowed:</L>
<L N="28">All are folyes, &thorn;at y say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; He is a fool, &thorn;at werre wole wake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may not maynten it wi&thorn; mede,</L>
<L>And so moche vndertake,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at wot wel he may not spede,</L>
<L>And of his ney&yogh;ebour his enemy make</L>
<L>For a straunge mannys dede;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at mesure wole forsake,</L>
<L N="36">And nedles put hym-self in drede;</L>
<L>Of mannys de&thorn; haue no rou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>But hate hem &thorn;at tellen hym trou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Loue hym &thorn;at cherische hym in synne,</L>
<L N="40">And suche games bygynne</L>
<L>Where &thorn;at he wot he may not wynne,</L>
<L>But besyen hym in slou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; He is a fool, &thorn;at no good can,</L>
<L N="44">Ne non wole lere, but slow in dede.</L>
<L>A gret fool, y holde &thorn;at man</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his enemys ha&thorn; no drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh suche foly, Flaundres be-gan;</L>
<L N="48">Of after perile &thorn;ey tok non hede.</L>
<L>Hit is worthy, he ete bred of bran,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; floure his foo wil fede.</L>
<L>And truste al in gloser charmes,</L>
<L N="52">In hyndryng in worschip of armes,</L>
<L>And lette lawe it mot not syt,</L>
<L>And conscience away flyt,</L>
<L>May brynge a lord, er &thorn;at he wyt,</L>
<L N="56">Emyddis grete harmes.
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="71"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Flaundres was &thorn;e richest land, and meriest to mynne;</L>
<L>Now is it wrappid in wo, and moche wel&thorn;e raft.</L>
<L>For defaute of Iustice, and singulere to wynne,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;ey were rebell, to ryse craft a&yogh;en craft.</L>
<L>Here lord had part of &thorn;e foly &thorn;ey were wounden ynne;</L>
<L>For-thy he les his lordshipe, and here fraunchise raft.</L>
<L>Here enemys lawhen hem to skorne, and seyn, 'for synne,</L>
<L N="64">Of here banere of grace, god broken ha&thorn; &thorn;e shaft.'</L>
<L>When prelat is forbode to preche,<MILESTONE N="116a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>No trewe man trou&thorn;e dar teche,</L>
<L>Encresyng of temperalte</L>
<L N="68">Suspende spiritualte:</L>
<L>What land is gouerned in &thorn;at degre,</L>
<L>May wayte after wreche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I holde hym a fool, &thorn;ou&yogh; he be wys,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at speke&thorn; among men of name</L>
<L>&THORN;at at his wysdom set no prys,</L>
<L>But skorne hym, and don blame;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at telle&thorn; where peryle lys,</L>
<L N="76">And gete no &thorn;onk, but harm and shame;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at pleyne&thorn;, y holde hym nys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at get no mendys, but dowble grame.</L>
<L>By &thorn;ese poyntes fflaundres was lest;</L>
<L N="80">Now is it out of rule and of rest.</L>
<L>Drede is here chef gayte.</L>
<L>So eche man on hem bayte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;et &thorn;ey honge in awayte</L>
<L N="84">Of a newe conquest.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; He &thorn;at my&yogh;t thryue, and nel not thee,</L>
<L>Ne his owen harmes knawe,</L>
<L>Apert ne in preuytee</L>
<L N="88">Serue god for loue ne awe,</L>
<L>Ne gouerne wel his owen degre,</L>
<L>Ne rule hymself in ry&yogh;twys lawe:</L>
<L>Whan wyse men fro hym fle,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;en god his grace wole fro hem drawe.
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="72"></L>
<L>&THORN;at moche wynne&thorn;, and no thyng wole haue,</L>
<L>But &yogh;eue it awey, to nedeles &thorn;at craue,</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens conscience despit</L>
<L N="96">Borwe moche, and neuere quyt:</L>
<L>When god for &thorn;at gylt smyt,</L>
<L>What glosere can &thorn;at wounde saue?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;at freek may wel be holden a fool,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at wayue&thorn; wit, and worche&thorn; by wille,</L>
<L>And skippe into sclaundre scol,</L>
<L>And scorne hym &thorn;at telle&thorn; hym skylle;</L>
<L>And lyue in Lenton as in &yogh;ool,</L>
<L N="104">His flesch in foly to fulfille.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;e dotard deye in dool,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ry&yogh;twys nel not rewe his ylle.</L>
<L>Who so wil not knowe his awen astat,</L>
<L N="108">Ne deliuere chekkys, er &thorn;at he be mat,</L>
<L>He shal haue worldis wondryng,</L>
<L>And his soule hyndryng,</L>
<L>And ay in paynes pondryng;</L>
<L N="112">To mende &thorn;anne, is to late.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Of all folk vppon fold, y fynde but foure trewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at don here deuere dewely, and take no mede:</L>
<L>Syknes is oon, and sorw do&thorn; sewe,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;e thridde hat 'de&thorn;,' and &thorn;e fier&thorn;e 'drede.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ey clayme vs by custom, for &thorn;ey oure kyn knewe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota</NOTE></L>
<L>And endid wi&thorn; oure aunsetres tyl &thorn;ey to er&thorn;e &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey spare prynce ne pore, old ne newe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey crepe in-to his cors, and clo&thorn;e hem in his wede.</L>
<L N="121">Drede brynge&thorn; man to buxomnes;</L>
<L>Sorwe of herte make&thorn; synnes les;</L>
<L>Syknes, bre&thorn;e stekenyng,</L>
<L N="124">And bowe to a bekenyng,</L>
<L>And brynge&thorn; hem to rekenyng,</L>
<L>Tyl de&thorn; all redresse.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="17" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000107.tif" N="73">
<HEAD>XVII. Loue that god loueth.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 116.] [25 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>That ilke man wole lerne wel</L>
<L>To loue god wi&thorn; al his my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue in his herte fele.</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;ere god do&thorn; loue, loue &thorn;ou ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>There god do&thorn; hate euerydele,</L>
<L>Hate it bo&thorn;e day and ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue hym <MILESTONE N="116b" UNIT="folio">no&thorn;er mete ne mele,</L>
<L N="8">But flyt hym fere out of &yogh;oure sy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Many gret[e] causes is,</L>
<L>To loue god, why men ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>He shop vs lyk ymage his,</L>
<L N="12">And wi&thorn; his de&thorn;, fro pyne vs bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ut, &thorn;ou&yogh; we don ofte amys,</L>
<L>For eche a gylt he bete&thorn; vs nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And we &thorn;enke to amende, he profre&thorn; to kys.</L>
<L N="16">Man, of loue he ha&thorn; besou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if a lord &yogh;eue fee or rent</L>
<L>For to do a gret office,</L>
<L>To serue hym wel is &thorn;yn atent,</L>
<L N="20">For thy profyt, but not for his,</L>
<L>For he fynde&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;y vaunsement;</L>
<L>&THORN;y loue vppon &thorn;e profyt lys.</L>
<L>Suche worldly louers are gostly blent;</L>
<L N="24">Suche loue to god is cold as yse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou serue god for helle drede,</L>
<L>Or loue god for his blisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue is worth no parfyt mede:</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ou [sechest] thy profyt, and not hisse.
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>To pyne ne blis, take non hede,</L>
<L>But loue god, for good he is.</L>
<L>Suche loue to god, his erande do&thorn; spede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota de amore dei &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">And plese&thorn; best to god y-wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Fleschly man may do wele</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuene werkes of mercy &thorn;at god bed:</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue pore folk mete and mele,</L>
<L N="36">Herberwe, drynk, clo&thorn;e, and fed,</L>
<L>For syngulere profyt, eche a dele,</L>
<L>For drede of pyne, and couetys of mede.</L>
<L>Loue god ouer all, for good he is;</L>
<L N="40">To pyne ne blisse, take non hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou sette loue in &thorn;at degre,</L>
<L>To loue god, for he &thorn;e wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;an make &thorn;ou hym as he dede &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;an loue for loue, euene is brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;ou loue god, for he made &thorn;e fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dy&yogh;ed for the, to blisse &thorn;e bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;an dy&yogh;e &thorn;ou for hym, as he dy&yogh;ed for &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="48">&YOGH;ut heuene blisse, &thorn;ou quytest hym nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;it o thyng &thorn;ere is byhende,</L>
<L>Man, &thorn;at god aske&thorn; of the:</L>
<L>"Alle worldys delys, fro &thorn;yn herte wende,</L>
<L N="52">Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;yn herte, loue &thorn;ou me.</L>
<L>&THORN;y swete &thorn;ou&yogh;tes [&thorn;ou] me sende;</L>
<L>For worldis goodis, myn are he.</L>
<L>Loue me gostly, &thorn;at am &thorn;y frende,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;anne al euyl shal fro &thorn;e fle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;at loue me gostly, y can assay,</L>
<L>For gostly loue in herte y sou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Do worldly thyng fro &thorn;yn herte away,</L>
<L N="60">And haue me principal in &thorn;y &thorn;ou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>Be lord, and haue richesse, &thorn;ou may;</L>
<L>Worldis richesse, for man was wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Gostly loue, &thorn;at is my pray;<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">But worldly goodis, in heuene come&thorn; nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; For gold and syluer, and precyous stones,</L>
<L>Swetnes of floures, er&thorn;ely bewte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e shrynes wi&thorn; all seyntes bones,</L>
<L N="68">In heuene were foul fel&thorn;e to se.</L>
<L>Tyl body and soule a&yogh;en arn ones</L>
<L>Mad parfyt in claryte,</L>
<L>Saue god hym self, in heuene wones,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;e principal, mankynde shal be."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'God! how may y, man, bygynne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; myn herte to loue &thorn;e?'</L>
<L>"Repente, and wylne no more synne,</L>
<L N="76">So mowe we<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &yogh;e</NOTE> <MILESTONE N="117a" UNIT="folio">frendis be,</L>
<L>Good soule, sybbe to my kynne;</L>
<L>For y made it lik to me.</L>
<L>Mankynde y tok, a mayden wi&thorn;-ynne,</L>
<L N="80">So, gostly and bodyly, bre&thorn;eren be we.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. wet</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who loue&thorn; god, he wil bygynne</L>
<L>For to folwe goddis lore;</L>
<L>Loke where he dede wrongly wynne,</L>
<L N="84">Make amendis, a&yogh;en restore.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure loue, fro me &yogh;e parten o twynne</L>
<L>For worldis worship, ryches in store,</L>
<L>Heuene &yogh;ates &yogh;e steken and pynne;</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at ye shulde saue, &yogh;e haue forlore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To gete loue &thorn;us bygynne:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; clene herte, and swete &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; trewe tong, not falsely wynne,</L>
<L N="92">Ne stele, ne flatre, ne ly&yogh;e nou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>Do ry&yogh;twys dede, out and ynne,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;y werkys be euene wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Do almes and penaunce, and leue &thorn;y synne:</L>
<L N="96">Wi&thorn; &thorn;ese &thorn;re loue is bou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God speke&thorn; to man, and lerne&thorn; lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e comaundementis and &thorn;e Crede.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;eue me &thorn;y loue, y aske no more,</L>
<L N="100">Wi&thorn; al &thorn;y herte, in loue and drede.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou nylt &yogh;eue it me, warne me byfore;</L>
<L>Sette pris to selle it; loue and bede,</L>
<L>I wole &yogh;eue the myself &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L N="104">Where my&yogh;test &thorn;ou haue a beter mede?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou nelt &yogh;eue ne selle it me,</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens me &thorn;ou wilt debate,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wil y gon away fro &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="108">And &yogh;elde to &thorn;e hate for hate.</L>
<L>My face wi&thorn; loue shalt &thorn;ou not se,</L>
<L>But steke &thorn;e wi&thorn;oute heuene &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>Fro alle vertues and charyte,</L>
<L N="112">Wi&thorn; helle houndes, in endeles date.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Haue y &thorn;y loue, so may &thorn;ou quyte</L>
<L>I mad &thorn;e lik ymage to me;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;e &thorn;enke &thorn;at was to lyte,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;anne &thorn;enk, y dyed on rode tre.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou trespas, y do not smyte,</L>
<L>But byd &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt mendid be.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou be lost, whom wiltow wyte?</L>
<L N="120">Is it long on me or &thorn;e?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Discrecioun of &yogh;ong and old</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ynge nou&yogh;t ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at may be bou&yogh;t and sold,</L>
<L N="124">Loue for loue is euenest bou&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>Whan worldis loue do&thorn; fayle and folde,</L>
<L>Goddis loue fayle&thorn; nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Trewe loue make&thorn; men be bolde;</L>
<L N="128">Wi&thorn; loue, felawship to-gydre is brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor loue, god com fro heuene toure,</L>
<L>In mayden Mary tok mankynde.</L>
<L>ffor oure swete, he drank ful soure.</L>
<L N="132">Where my&yogh;t we trewere loue fynde?</L>
<L>His loue passe&thorn; worldis tresoure,</L>
<L>&YOGH;af sy&yogh;t in helle to gostly blynde.</L>
<L>And we wole knytte his loue to oure,</L>
<L N="136">ffor so&thorn;e, &thorn;at knot shal neuere vnbynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Haue y &thorn;y loue, so may &thorn;ou gete</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue wole &thorn;y soule saue,</L>
<L>Among myn angels haue a sete,</L>
<L N="140">In ioye of heuene, as seyntes haue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou nelt <MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio">y wol &thorn;e &thorn;rete,</L>
<L>In helle pyne be fendis knaue.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;y conscience &thorn;ou trete,</L>
<L N="144">Whe&thorn;er is &thorn;e leuere for to haue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou madde in &thorn;y mood,</L>
<L>To werne me &thorn;e loue &thorn;ou has,</L>
<L>I wole caste on &thorn;e myn herte blod,</L>
<L N="148">To bere witnesse &thorn;ou forfetest gras,</L>
<L>And my vengeance, &thorn;at is so wood,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; helle houndis in fyre &thorn;e chas.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast fre wille, knowest euyll and good:</L>
<L N="152">Chese where wyltow take &thorn;y plas.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou of &thorn;y loue daungere make,</L>
<L>What may thy loue profyte me?</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou woldest me forsake,</L>
<L N="156">Out of my lordschipe &thorn;ou my&yogh;t not fle.
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>Angels bry&yogh;t, and deueles blake,</L>
<L>In helle and heuene, my lordschipes be.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere be no mo wayes to take;</L>
<L N="160">Is loue or hate more profyt to &thorn;e?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;y loue to &thorn;y flesch do&thorn; bende,</L>
<L>To greue me &thorn;ou dost bygynne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou loue &thorn;e world &thorn;at wole make ende,</L>
<L N="164">Of hym &thorn;ou shalt more lese &thorn;an wynne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be suget, and loue &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>He wole &thorn;e hate, and &yogh;eue pyne for synne.</L>
<L>Loue me! y am god, &thorn;y frende,</L>
<L N="168">And oure loues shal neuere twynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whe&thorn;er trewe loue go or sende,</L>
<L>Hym thar not tary in his dede.</L>
<L>When mede ha&thorn; leue to stande byhynde,</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;anne trewe loue, his erande may spede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; trewe loue haue lityl to spende,</L>
<L>Euere he fynde&thorn; a frend at nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fro his foon wole hym fende.</L>
<L N="176">Who so is loued, hym thar not drede."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God say&thorn;, "y haue mercyes to dele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wole amende, no more do mys.</L>
<L>My mercyes, &thorn;ousandes mo ken fele</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;an &thorn;ousandis worldis wikkidnes."</L>
<L>His herte blod wrot oure hele,</L>
<L>And Ihesus body, &thorn;e parchemyn is;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; trewe loue he prented oure sele,</L>
<L N="184">&THORN;at is heritage of oure blis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ere is an herbe &thorn;at hatte&thorn; 'trewe loue,'</L>
<L>And by name it ha&thorn; no pere,</L>
<L>Is lykned to Ihesus, y may proue:</L>
<L N="188">His handes and feet, &thorn;e leves were;
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>His herte was wi&thorn; a spere &thorn;urgh-shoue,</L>
<L>Mannys loue was hym so dere.</L>
<L>What soule is syk, lay &thorn;at herbe aboue,</L>
<L N="192">Hit make&thorn; hool al y-fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God biddi&thorn; vs do no &thorn;ynges but two:</L>
<L>In loue and drede to hym bende;</L>
<L>Lede &thorn;y soule, lustes fro,</L>
<L N="196">World and flesch, and fro &thorn;e fende.</L>
<L>Ihesus herte was cleued so,</L>
<L>To lete out trewe loue to his frende.</L>
<L>In that blisse, god, graunte vs go,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;ere trewe loue wone&thorn; wi&thorn;outen ende!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="18" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XVIII. The declaryng of religioun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[A.D. 1421]</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 117, <I>back</I>.] [24 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Who &thorn;at wole knowe condicion</L>
<L>Of parfyt lyf in alle degre:</L>
<L>God is foundour of religion,</L>
<L N="4">Obedyent to charyte.</L>
<L>Swete &thorn;ou&yogh;t in deuocion,</L>
<L>Is weddid <MILESTONE N="118a" UNIT="folio">to chastite,</L>
<L>In brennyng contemplacion,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e hi&yogh;est lyf of spiritualte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The goode lyueres in spiritualte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e worldly lyueres hem do&thorn; hate,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; occupacioun of temperalte</L>
<L N="12">Dryue&thorn; relegeon out at &thorn;e &yogh;ate</L>
<L>For besynesse of vanyte,</L>
<L>Vaynglory, and hy&yogh;e astate.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;us chaungen here degre,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;ey come to heuene, neuere or late.
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="80"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What is religion in mynde?</L>
<L>In clene herte is soule o prys;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;raldom do&thorn; vnbynde;</L>
<L N="20">A louer of vertues, a hatere of vys.</L>
<L>Eche soule is parfyt clerk of kynde</L>
<L>In hy&yogh;e discrecion, and wys.</L>
<L>Of soules, men may no fooles fynde</L>
<L N="24">But assente to &thorn;e flesch, and make hym nys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Religeon is champion in batayle,</L>
<L>Discomfites hys enemy;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if temptacions hym assayle,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ere he hath &thorn;e victory.</L>
<L>Religeon is trewe trauayle,</L>
<L>In goddis seruyce neuere werye.</L>
<L>Haue mede wi&thorn; martyres, he may not fayle,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at euere is redy for to dy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Werkys wi&thorn;-oute discrecion,</L>
<L>Vaynglory in staat is brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And shrift wi&thorn;-oute contricion,</L>
<L N="36">In skorne &thorn;e sacrament &thorn;ey sou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And preyere wi&thorn;-oute deuocion,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey preye, god here&thorn; hem nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;e lippes turne preyers vp so doun,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at speke&thorn; o&thorn;er &thorn;an herte &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Cherische no vices in &yogh;oure warde</L>
<L>To serue god in good atent,</L>
<L>And non wi&thorn; other be to harde,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at ben professed in &yogh;oure couent;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey my&yogh;te for-&thorn;enke it afterward</L>
<L>&THORN;ey tok &thorn;e abyte, and wolde repente;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey lese of god a gret reward</L>
<L N="48">Whan wille fro religeon is wente.
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="81"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A questyon of &yogh;ow y craue,&mdash;</L>
<L>Resoun assoyle&thorn; it by skille,&mdash;</L>
<L>Who may here soules saue,</L>
<L N="52">To were an abyte, wole or nelle?</L>
<L>&THORN;enk on &thorn;y ber&thorn;e, &thorn;enk on &thorn;y graue,</L>
<L>&THORN;y fleschely lustes not fulfille;</L>
<L>For, helle ne heuene shal no man haue,</L>
<L N="56">Mawgre his tee&thorn;, a&yogh;eyns his wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou&yogh; &thorn;ou be of gentyl blod,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk all com of Adam and Eue.</L>
<L>Gadre not in propre, worldis good;</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at nes no religeous, but worldis reue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e herre degre, &thorn;e mekere of mood.</L>
<L>Tak no vengeance, &thorn;ou&yogh; folk &thorn;e a-reue.</L>
<L>Lat comon lawe stonde as hit stood,</L>
<L N="64">Loke no proude herte &thorn;y charyte meue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Haue non enuye, <MILESTONE N="118b" UNIT="folio">day ne ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To goode lyuers bet &thorn;an &yogh;e,</L>
<L>But auy&yogh;e faste wi&thorn; all &thorn;y my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="68">To lyue beter &thorn;an do&thorn; he:</L>
<L>&THORN;an countrefetest &thorn;ou goddis kny&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is enuye in charite.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ou&yogh;tes in goddis doom are di&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="72">And dedes, after &thorn;at &thorn;ey be.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Tho &thorn;at lyuen in fleschly delys,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;at companye remewe;</L>
<L>Loue here bodyes, but not here vys,</L>
<L N="76">And cherische hem to good vertue;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at wil al-gate be nys,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou no&yogh;t here maneres sewe.</L>
<L>Go to company &thorn;at is wys,</L>
<L N="80">Lete fooles drynke &thorn;at &thorn;ey dede brewe.
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="82"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Religeous, be war, wi&thorn; whom &yogh;e stonde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gentyles or folk &thorn;at worldly is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e grype not hand in honde.</L>
<L N="84">When &yogh;e take leue, loke not &yogh;e kys.</L>
<L>Man to man hem thar not wonde,</L>
<L>Ne woman to woman no peryle ne is;</L>
<L>But man to woman my&yogh;te breke &thorn;e bonde;</L>
<L N="88">In towche is susspescioun of mys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Suche towches not &yogh;e byde,</L>
<L>Wolde buffete &thorn;e soule, and wounde wi&thorn;-ynne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue o&thorn;ere cause, &thorn;at stonde bysyde,</L>
<L N="92">To wene it were a bargayn of synne.</L>
<L>Towches, in custom, &thorn;ou&yogh;tis hide;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sclaundre and shame nyll not twynne.</L>
<L>With conscience, sclaundre and shame do&thorn; chide;</L>
<L N="96">To shewe opert he wol be-gynne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota de religione, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; With mekenesse &yogh;e may heuene gete.</L>
<L>Dispyse non in low degre.</L>
<L>Resceyue no worschip, ne hy&yogh;e sete,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at pryde go bytwen god and &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wolde make to hem self for&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>For worldis ryches and vanyte.</L>
<L>War for dronkenesse of drynkes grete,</L>
<L N="104">Fro glotry of metes of gret daynte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To religeon mekely bende,</L>
<L>To serue god in loue and drede.</L>
<L>To herkene tydynges, not &yogh;e wende,</L>
<L N="108">Ne bokes of vanyte, not &yogh;e rede.</L>
<L>Resceyue no lettere, ne non out sende,</L>
<L>But hit be for &yogh;oure hous nede,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er to kyn or certeyn frende,</L>
<L N="112">In goodnes &yogh;oure erande for to spede.
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="83"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Kepe &yogh;oure wacche and seruyce dewe,</L>
<L>And rule of habyte clenely &yogh;eme;</L>
<L>And fille &yogh;oure hertes wi&thorn; good vertue,</L>
<L N="116">And wikked vyces fro &yogh;ow &yogh;e fleme;</L>
<L>But loke deuocion growe ay newe.</L>
<L>Be suche wi&thorn;-ynne, as &yogh;e outward seme.</L>
<L>Good aungel and wikked bo&thorn;e &yogh;ow sewe,</L>
<L N="120">And wryten &yogh;oure dedes, &thorn;at shal &yogh;ow deme.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wacche not outrage in wast despence,</L>
<L>Fro hard to nyce, &thorn;y fflesch to fede.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bischop or shryfte &yogh;e mowe despence,</L>
<L N="124">Fro hard to hardere &yogh;oure lyf to lede.</L>
<L>Withstonde temptacions, make defence;</L>
<L>&THORN;e moo &yogh;e withstonde, &thorn;e more mede.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e wi&thorn; seyntes will haue reuerence,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;an moste &yogh;e countrefete here dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Kepe <MILESTONE N="119a" UNIT="folio">sylence, whyder &yogh;e byde or go,</L>
<L>Fro wordis of vanyte, &yogh;oure lippes steke.</L>
<L>Speke faire to frend and fo,</L>
<L N="132">For fayre speche do&thorn; wra&thorn;&thorn;e breke.</L>
<L>&THORN;at do&thorn; wrong, deme so.</L>
<L>Lete not vengeance, &thorn;y wra&thorn;&thorn;e wreke.</L>
<L>Vengeance is goddis, he deme&thorn; &thorn;o</L>
<L N="136">In werk and word, all &thorn;at men speke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In rule of religeon is ordeyned &yogh;ore:</L>
<L>By&yogh;e no thyng to selle and wynne.</L>
<L>Marchaunt and religeous, on mot be forbore;</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;ey may not wone, on herte wi&thorn;ynne.</L>
<L>Ne kepe no iewels ne propre in store;</L>
<L>&THORN;at nes no religeous, but dedly synne</L>
<L>In fleschly delices, and loue it more</L>
<L N="144">To parte &thorn;y loue and god atwynne.
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="84"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That &thorn;enke&thorn; good &thorn;ou&yogh;t in sylence,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey speken to god in specyale.</L>
<L>How mow &yogh;e lette hem, for conscience,</L>
<L N="148">Calle hem to werkis generall?</L>
<L>Summe bidden, in vertue of obedience,</L>
<L>Contemplatyf in spirituale;</L>
<L>To religeon they don a gret defence,</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at bryngen hem to werkis temperale.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Hy&yogh;e astate, ne gentyl blod,</L>
<L>Brynge&thorn; no man to heuene blisse.</L>
<L>Gret hors ne iewel, ne browded hood,</L>
<L N="156">Nes no cause of holynesse,</L>
<L>But pore of spirit and meke of mood.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue god &thorn;y soule, and eche man hisse.</L>
<L>Gret lordschipe, ne myche good,</L>
<L N="160">Nes no cause of sykernesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Tonsure, abyte, ne no wede,</L>
<L>Nes no cause of religeon,</L>
<L>Ne wakyng, ne fastyng, ne almesdede,</L>
<L N="164">Ne preyere ne oreson,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e herte &thorn;erto take hede,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; werkys of discrecion.</L>
<L>Deuocion make&thorn; soules to spede</L>
<L N="168">Wi&thorn; werkis of contemplacion.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Religeon is most meke</L>
<L>In abyte, of alle vertues floures.</L>
<L>Richesse, ne worldis worschipe, seke,</L>
<L N="172">But offre to god alle honoures.</L>
<L>Richesse and worschipe make soules syke</L>
<L>In vaynglory and sharp[e] shoures.</L>
<L>Make vertues &thorn;e wax, deuocioun &thorn;e wyke,</L>
<L N="176">To brenne bri&yogh;t in heuene boures.
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="85"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Iustice is religeon in sete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at deme&thorn; ri&yogh;t in all degre.</L>
<L>And queste is religeon, trou&thorn;e to trete;</L>
<L N="180">&YOGH;eue&thorn; eche man, &thorn;at his shulde be.</L>
<L>A child may wi&thorn; his fader plete,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ut kepe his charyte,</L>
<L>And of his kyng blameles gete</L>
<L N="184">Lawe is so gentyll and so fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; summe of thy bre&thorn;eren don a trespas,</L>
<L>He wole amende and do no moo.</L>
<L>Parauenture &thorn;ou art in &thorn;e same cas,</L>
<L N="188">Or after, my&yogh;t ben in suche two.</L>
<L>Loke not &thorn;at &thorn;ou hym chace,</L>
<L>Ne sclaundre hym not to haue shame and wo.</L>
<L>Pray god for&yogh;eue hym of his grace,</L>
<L N="192">And kepe &thorn;e wel &thorn;ou do not so.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="19" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XIX. [God's Appeal to Man.]</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 119, <I>back</I>.] [14 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>In my conscience I fynde,</L>
<L>And in my soule I here and see,</L>
<L>To repreue man &thorn;at is vnkynde,</L>
<L N="4">Goddis wordis &thorn;is may be:</L>
<L>"Man of resoun, haue in mynde,</L>
<L>I made &thorn;e lyk ymage to me;</L>
<L>For loue y hadde to mankynde,</L>
<L N="8">I toke manhed, lyk to &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Mannys loue y &yogh;erned &yogh;ore;</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue was in myn herte sou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Mannys loue sat me so sore,</L>
<L N="12">Nas neuere bargayn derrere bou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>Man! is &thorn;e laft no loue in store?</L>
<L>What is &thorn;e cause &thorn;ou louest me nou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Telle me &yogh;if y my&yogh;te don more.</L>
<L N="16">What is byhynd, &thorn;at lakke&thorn; &thorn;e ou&yogh;t?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; For &thorn;y loue y meked me lowe,</L>
<L>And dy&yogh;ed on &thorn;e rode tre.</L>
<L>Answere, man, and be aknowe:</L>
<L N="20">Shewe what &thorn;ou suffred for me;</L>
<L>For suche seed as &thorn;ou dost sowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof shal &thorn;yn heruest be,</L>
<L>In heuene or helle to repe and mowe.</L>
<L N="24">As &thorn;ou deserued, fong &thorn;y fee.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, to &thorn;e y make my mone:</L>
<L>I bou&yogh;t &thorn;e fro pyne to blisse;</L>
<L>Melte &thorn;yn herte, as hard as stone;</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ou&yogh; it be late, amende &thorn;y mysse.</L>
<L>In wra&thorn;&thorn;e, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be fro me gon,</L>
<L>Turne a&yogh;ayn, y wol &thorn;e kysse.</L>
<L>To make me frendis of my fon,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;erfore y &yogh;af my lyf for hysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Be war, and loue not worldis good</L>
<L>To gete wi&thorn; wrong, and calle it thyn.</L>
<L>Man, haue it in &thorn;y mood,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;ou shalt rekene; for alle is myn.</L>
<L>Why bou&yogh;te y &thorn;e on the rood?</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou shulde serue, and be myn hyne.</L>
<L>Make not myn argumentis wood,</L>
<L N="40">To caste &thorn;e fro blisse to pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, why turmentest &thorn;ou me so?</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;y synnes don encresce,</L>
<L>And &thorn;y vices waxen moo,</L>
<L N="44">And &thorn;y vertues wanen lesse.
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>Thenke good y be, thy foo.</L>
<L>Whanne wylt &thorn;ou of &thorn;y synne ses,</L>
<L>Haue mercy on &thorn;y soule woo,</L>
<L N="48">Or haue mynde on me, and &yogh;eue me pes?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To suffre de&thorn;, y meked me,</L>
<L>Fro pyne to blisse, &thorn;y soule to wynne.</L>
<L>To me so shuldest &thorn;ou meke &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="52">Leue and forbere &thorn;y synne.</L>
<L>Fro my lordschipe my&yogh;t &thorn;ou not fle,</L>
<L>Heuene ne helle, ne see wi&thorn;-ynne,</L>
<L>But where and whenne my wille be,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;y body and soule to parte o twynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou&yogh; y haue graunted &thorn;e grace</L>
<L>To knowe bo&thorn;e good and ylle,</L>
<L>Wyte &thorn;y self in eche a place,</L>
<L N="60">Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou wylt &thorn;y self spille.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; flesch and world and fend [&thorn;e] chas,</L>
<L>Temptacion profre &thorn;e tille,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou my&yogh;t forbere and nou&yogh;t trespas;</L>
<L N="64">I lente &thorn;e knoweleche and fre wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In syknesse and pouerte,</L>
<L>Glade &thorn;erynne, and &thorn;anke me all.</L>
<L>&THORN;e more &thorn;ou hast &thorn;erof plente,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e nerre &thorn;e, be y shall.</L>
<L>&THORN;an say, 'Lord, kepe me ney&yogh; &thorn;e!<MILESTONE N="110a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>At nede, here me when y call!</L>
<L>Take fro me hele and prosperite</L>
<L N="72">Ra&thorn;ere &thorn;an lete me fro &thorn;e fall!'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, rewe on my paynes sore,</L>
<L>Repente &thorn;y synne, and mercy craue.</L>
<L>By my woundes, swere no more.</L>
<L N="76">Dysmembre no lymes &thorn;at y haue.
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>&THORN;y wrong wynnyng, a&yogh;en restore.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt &thorn;y soule saue,</L>
<L>Lete soule be lord, and go byfore,</L>
<L N="80">And make &thorn;y body &thorn;y soule knaue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, and &thorn;ou wist how,</L>
<L>So li&yogh;tly my gre to make,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou noldest, for alle &thorn;e worldis prow,</L>
<L N="84">For fleschly lustes me forsake.</L>
<L>In &thorn;y lyue, besye &thorn;e now;</L>
<L>In goode werkis wysely wake;</L>
<L>In loue, drede, to me bow,</L>
<L N="88">And fle to me fro synnes blake.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Seuene werkis of mercy, kepe hem well,</L>
<L>&THORN;e comaundementis and &thorn;e Crede,</L>
<L>All &thorn;y lyue, as y &thorn;e telle;</L>
<L N="92">&YOGH;eue me &thorn;yn herte in loue and drede.</L>
<L>Whyle body and soule togydre dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou my&yogh;t serue pyne and mede.</L>
<L>When soule is out of flesch and felle,</L>
<L N="96">Shal neuere do synne ne almesdede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Mayntene not wrong, to calle it ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Vengeaunce and mercy, ney&yogh;ebores ben &thorn;o.</L>
<L>As messageres &thorn;ey ben dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="100">Mercy to frend, vengeaunce to foo.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure dede in derk, y se in sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere nys n&oacute; &thorn;ou&yogh;t hid me fro.</L>
<L>After &thorn;y dede, &thorn;e doom is dy&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="104">Vengeaunce and mercy departe&thorn; hem so.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; For my doom is ri&yogh;twisnesse;</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;twys longe&thorn; to &thorn;e godhede;</L>
<L>And my sones dom is wys,</L>
<L N="108">For mercy longe&thorn; to &thorn;e manhede.
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>&THORN;e holy gost grace lys,</L>
<L>He &yogh;eue&thorn; lyf, he &yogh;eue&thorn; no dede.</L>
<L>Ouercome my wra&thorn;&thorn;e, and fle fro vys,</L>
<L N="112">And do &thorn;e comaundementis &thorn;at y bede."</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="20" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XX. [How Man's flesh complained to God against Christ.]</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 120.] [27 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>The tixt of holy writ, men sayn,</L>
<L>Hit slee&thorn;, but glose be among.</L>
<L>The spirit of vnderstandyng quykene&thorn; agayn,</L>
<L N="4">And make&thorn; the lyue endeles long.</L>
<L>A fantasie y herde sayn,</L>
<L>There-of me lust to make a song,</L>
<L>'How mannys flesch to god dede playn</L>
<L N="8">On Ihesu Crist, had don hym wrong.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The flesch, his playnt &thorn;us do&thorn; bygynne</L>
<L>To god fader, in heuene on hy&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"Ihesu, brother of oure kynne,</L>
<L N="12">Ha&thorn; bygyled me wi&thorn; his sley&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; parted my soule and me o twynne,</L>
<L>And raft [it] fro me by his my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Now, ry&yogh;twys god, let mercy blynne!</L>
<L N="16">On Ihesu, &thorn;y sone, do me ry&yogh;t!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Body and soule, &thorn;ou dede me make,</L>
<L>In vnyte to-gydre so.</L>
<L>Now ha&thorn; Ihesu my soule take,</L>
<L N="20">And &thorn;us parted oure loue o two.</L>
<L>My soule ha&thorn; me [now] forsake;</L>
<L>Sumtyme was frend, now is fo;</L>
<L>Byd me go wolward, faste, and wake,</L>
<L N="24">Alle here ioye is of my woo.
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="90"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Fro me, to &thorn;y sone, my soule is flet;</L>
<L>Ful ofte &thorn;y sone in me here sou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Now here loue to hym so fast is knete,</L>
<L N="28">Away fro hym wol sche nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>She semes dronken, or out of wit;<MILESTONE N="120b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of myn euelfare she has no &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;at sorwe is so in myn herte hit,</L>
<L N="32">I trowe to de&thorn;e y mon be brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sum-tyme my soule was mylde</L>
<L>To my biddyng, in hoot and colde,</L>
<L>Synge, or playe, or chambres bylde,</L>
<L N="36">Chef seruaunt of myn housholde.</L>
<L>Now Ihesu ha&thorn; made here made and wylde;</L>
<L>ffro hym, departe neuere she nolde.</L>
<L>She sette&thorn; on hym ri&yogh;t as a childe;</L>
<L N="40">A&yogh;ens me she bere&thorn; here bolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whan I of here counseil craue,</L>
<L>Of fleschly lustes to haue my wille,</L>
<L>She calle&thorn; me wod, and sey&thorn; y raue;</L>
<L N="44">She will neuere graunte &thorn;ertille.</L>
<L>She bidde&thorn; me haue mynde of my graue,</L>
<L>Rule me in resoun and skille.</L>
<L>I was mayster, now am y knaue;</L>
<L N="48">In that stat, brynge me she wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wolde y be proud, she bidde&thorn; be meke;</L>
<L>Wolde y be gloton, she bidde&thorn; me faste;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere y wolde take, she biddes me eke;</L>
<L N="52">Wolde y be lyther, she biddis be chaste;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if y fy&yogh;te, she biddes ley for&thorn; my cheke;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere y am slow, she biddis be haste;</L>
<L>Here answere is not to seke;</L>
<L N="56">To speke to here, my wynde y waste.
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="91"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ihesu com fro heuene blisse,</L>
<L>And tok flesch in a mayden fre,</L>
<L>Lowely, and most [of] mekenesse,</L>
<L N="60">Hyd vnder flesch<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. flesch fleschly]</NOTE> oure fraternite;</L>
<L>Now wold [he] take my soule to his,</L>
<L>ffor he suffred pyne and pouerte.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it sumwhat y my&yogh;te acorde to &thorn;is;</L>
<L N="64">But why shulde my soule hate me?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whan Ihesu and my soule be met,</L>
<L>Sone my werkis &thorn;ey aspi&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Here wit on me fast &thorn;ey whet:</L>
<L N="68">'In shame, and skorne, and vylenye,</L>
<L>To folwe &thorn;y fleschly lustes let,</L>
<L>Or ellis bo&thorn;e &yogh;e shal dy&yogh;e.'</L>
<L>&THORN;us am y vnder and ouer set.</L>
<L N="72">She spettes on me, and do&thorn; me fy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; me, my soule he do&thorn; &thorn;rete,</L>
<L>And make&thorn; my soule me to hate.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; plesande wordis, he hote&thorn; here gete</L>
<L N="76">In heuene blisse, a quenes astate.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come&thorn; she hom in wra&thorn;&thorn;e-ful hete,</L>
<L>Bede&thorn; here lette, bo&thorn;e erly and late,</L>
<L>Caste&thorn; me doun, and do&thorn; me bete,</L>
<L N="80">And trede&thorn; on me, and make&thorn; debate.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thanne renne&thorn; she a&yogh;en as she were wood;</L>
<L>To Ihesu, &thorn;y sone, she do&thorn; fly&yogh;e.</L>
<L>He fede&thorn; here wi&thorn; his flesch and blood,</L>
<L N="84">But &thorn;anne here &thorn;ou&yogh;tes mownten hy&yogh;e.</L>
<L>She biddi&thorn; me water and bred to food;</L>
<L>As mortkyn forsaken, she let me li&yogh;e.</L>
<L>She holde&thorn; me euyll, and no &thorn;yng good,</L>
<L N="88">But a stynkyng carayne in here ey&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="92"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;us my soule, my body slees</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret anguysche and turment.</L>
<L>She telles, Ihesu dy&yogh;ed for pes;</L>
<L N="92">But fro his skole she is went;</L>
<L>Bytwen vs werre do&thorn; encres.</L>
<L>Here swerd is drawen, here bow is bent.</L>
<L>She say&thorn; but, 'fleschly lustes, sees!</L>
<L N="96">We mon be dede, and bo&thorn;e be shent.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; She acordid wi&thorn; Ihesu, and me dede flyte,</L>
<L>And sayde y shulde be <MILESTONE N="121a" UNIT="folio">maked tame,</L>
<L>And sayde my werkys me adyte,</L>
<L N="100">And bryngen me in wikked fame.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if worldly men me don smyte,</L>
<L>And don me bo&thorn;e wrong and grame,</L>
<L>She loue&thorn; that don me despyte,</L>
<L N="104">And preye&thorn; for all &thorn;at don me shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Hy&yogh;e fader, god of ri&yogh;twisnes,</L>
<L>Haue mynde of my sorwe sore!</L>
<L>And it be founden Ihesu loued mysse,</L>
<L N="108">To me my soule a&yogh;en restore&mdash;</L>
<L>A litil playnt nes no&yogh;t &thorn;isse,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at y haue sayd &yogh;ore&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at y and my soule be frendis and kisse,</L>
<L N="112">And loue, as we dede here byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; For my soule, Ihesu suffred wo,</L>
<L>Bounden and beten wi&thorn; skourges ynowe,</L>
<L>Crowned wi&thorn; thorn, nayled also</L>
<L N="116">On croos, tyl de&thorn; dede hym bowe.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a spere, his herte let cleue a two,</L>
<L>Wyde open his loue my&yogh;te out flowe,</L>
<L>So lo&thorn; hym was his loue forgo;</L>
<L N="120">He is wor&thorn;y be loued, &thorn;at so dede wowe.
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="93"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My soule, y holde, holy es it,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. it es]</NOTE></L>
<L>For she loue&thorn; Ihesu, &thorn;at loue&thorn; here wel.</L>
<L>But loue were tendere to loue vsed,</L>
<L N="124">Were harder &thorn;an ston, and styffere &thorn;an stel.</L>
<L>On Ihesu she is amerous and ful auysed.</L>
<L>What worldly &thorn;yng she see&thorn; or fele,</L>
<L>Al worldly ioye she ha&thorn; refused,</L>
<L N="128">And me she loue&thorn; neuere a dele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I wante my wille, and euel fare y,</L>
<L>Fro worldly mer&thorn;e put o syde.</L>
<L>Fro worldis worschip she do&thorn; me tary.</L>
<L N="132">I may no &thorn;ou&yogh;t fro here hyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere y blisse, she do&thorn; wary;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere y speke fayre, she do&thorn; chyde.</L>
<L>She is newe waxen al contrary.</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;ere y dwelle, she nyl not byde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; She repreue&thorn; my dagged clo&thorn;es,</L>
<L>And longe pyked crakowed shon;</L>
<L>Vpbreyde[&thorn;] me my grete o&thorn;es,</L>
<L N="140">And say&thorn; y breke goddis bone.</L>
<L>&THORN;at me is lef, all she lo&thorn;es.</L>
<L>I seye 'o&thorn;ere men so don.'</L>
<L>She sey&thorn;, &thorn;ey go to helle wo&thorn;es,</L>
<L N="144">Wole to wende, wi&thorn; hem to wone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; Ihesu, alway is she,</L>
<L>And now she ly&thorn; wi&thorn; hym in cracche,</L>
<L>Now into Egipt wi&thorn; hym do&thorn; fle</L>
<L N="148">Fro Herowdes, lest he hem cacche.</L>
<L>In his moder armes, born wol she be,</L>
<L>And sowke wi&thorn; hym, as chylde in tacche.</L>
<L>She folwe&thorn; hym in al degre,</L>
<L N="152">And countrefete&thorn; to ben his macche.
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="94"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; hym do&thorn; drynke and ete,</L>
<L>To lerne of his discressioun;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hym sche is skourged and bete,</L>
<L N="156">And crucyfyed in his passioun;</L>
<L>She is wi&thorn; hym in helle hete,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hym in his resurexioun,</L>
<L>And stye in-to heuene in his fadres se[t]e;</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;ens nolde she neuere come doun."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Now &thorn;e playnt is at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>God answerd wi&thorn; mylde soun:</L>
<L>'fflesch,' he sayde, '&thorn;ou iangelest fast</L>
<L N="164">Moche dene, and no resoun.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;y wordes &thorn;ou dost waste.</L>
<L>Wille wi&thorn;oute discressioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;yn awen pleynt &thorn;e do&thorn; caste;</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;ou turnest &thorn;y self vp so doun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thou makest maystershepe in al vys,<MILESTONE N="121b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And here [turnest] fro my way,</L>
<L>And makest here &thorn;ral to fleschely delys,</L>
<L N="172">In vanyte to al worldly play.</L>
<L>She is ashamed, now she is wys;</L>
<L>Sche lyued in vowtrye so many a day.</L>
<L>She ha&thorn; chosen &thorn;e loue most o prys,</L>
<L N="176">And cast &thorn;e fals[e] loue away.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God sei&thorn;: 'man, y made &thorn;e of nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And kyd &thorn;at y loued &thorn;e dere,</L>
<L>And soule of resoun in &thorn;e wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="180">ffayre and wys, angels pere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast defouled &thorn;e ymage &thorn;at y wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In seruage to fendis and fendis fere.</L>
<L>She folwed &thorn;y wille in dede and &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="184">In alle place, fer and nere.
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="95"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>&para; On Ihesu &thorn;ou pleynt dost make,</L>
<L>Sayde he bigyled &thorn;e wi&thorn; sley&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And biddest me lete mercy slake,</L>
<L N="188">And on Ihesu do &thorn;e ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>My sone, for &thorn;e, dede deth take,</L>
<L>And kydde &thorn;e loue most of my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; he loue dede forsake,</L>
<L N="192">How woldest &thorn;ou &thorn;is doom were dy&yogh;t?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Flesch, &thorn;y synnes mochil is;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art cast in &thorn;yn awen caas.</L>
<L>Knowleche, repente, and mende &thorn;y mys,</L>
<L N="196">And be in wille no more trespas.</L>
<L>I nel deme &thorn;e in ry&yogh;twisnes,</L>
<L>But medle &thorn;erwi&thorn; mercy and grace,</L>
<L>And brynge &thorn;y soule to heuene blys,</L>
<L N="200">Wi&thorn; loue to se my fayre face.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In ouerhope, be not to bold</L>
<L>In synne, for to haue mercy.</L>
<L>Let not wanhope in &thorn;e be old,</L>
<L N="204">For my grace is euere redy.</L>
<L>Fro helle pynes hoot and cold</L>
<L>I assoyle &thorn;e, and out of purgatory.</L>
<L>At &thorn;y deth, or body be cold,</L>
<L N="208">To Ihesu in heuene &thorn;y soule shal fleye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In good werkis wysely wake,</L>
<L>Playne not on Ihesu, what he sende.</L>
<L>Sykenes, pouerte, mekely take;</L>
<L N="212">Richesse and hele wysely spende,</L>
<L>And helpe all pore for goddis sake.</L>
<L>&THORN;an god wole lede &yogh;ow, as his frend,</L>
<L>To ioye of heuene &thorn;at shal neuere slake.'</L>
<L N="216">In-to &thorn;at blisse, god graunte vs wende! Amen!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="21" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000130.tif" N="96">
<HEAD>XXI. A lernyng to good leuynge.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 121, <I>back</I>.] [20 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>POre of spirit, blessed be:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; he be lord of richesse fele,</L>
<L>He bere&thorn; penaunce and pouerte.</L>
<L N="4">That of his good to pore folk dele,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kyngdom of heuene a lord is he.</L>
<L>&THORN;at counseyle&thorn; wel to soule hele,</L>
<L>And lyue&thorn; in werkis of charyte,</L>
<L N="8">Suche folk to heuene preuyly stele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Si&thorn; god do&thorn; blisse, and graunte&thorn; blis</L>
<L>&THORN;at don his word, and holde it trewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;at man cursed is,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at lyue&thorn; contrarious &thorn;at vertue.</L>
<L>&THORN;at fille&thorn; his herte wi&thorn; ryches,</L>
<L>Nedeles aueryce gadryng newe,</L>
<L>For wikkid counseil, helle is his,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;ere neuere nes reste, but euere remewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Blessid be man &thorn;at in herte is mylde,</L>
<L>Buxom to lerne, and lef to teche,</L>
<L>Shal owe &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="122a" UNIT="folio">er&thorn;e, and &thorn;eron bylde,</L>
<L N="20">In helpe of mony his rychesse reche,</L>
<L>Of shrewes, make goddis childe,</L>
<L>Of gostly woundes, be soule leche;</L>
<L>Make tame to god, &thorn;o &thorn;at were wylde.</L>
<L N="24">Of eche good lyuere, his werkis preche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne cursed be man in herte ruyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere nel lere ne vnderstond.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; he owe er&thorn;e, he shal not byde,</L>
<L N="28">Til it be, out of his hond.
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>When conscience his werkis chyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at man shal neuere reioyse lond.</L>
<L>Fro alle vertues &thorn;at do&thorn; hym hyde,</L>
<L N="32">To alle myscheues he make&thorn; hym bond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Blessed be he &thorn;at morne&thorn; sore</L>
<L>His bre&thorn;ere synnes, his awen mysdede,</L>
<L>Repente, and wille to do no more,</L>
<L N="36">But holde &thorn;e hestes &thorn;at god bede;</L>
<L>His wrong wynnyng a&yogh;en restore,</L>
<L>And helpe pore &thorn;at han nede.</L>
<L>He shal be counforted &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L N="40">In heuene blisse haue his mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Than cursed be he ha&thorn; ioye of synne,</L>
<L>And euere encrese&thorn; mo and mo,</L>
<L>Boste &thorn;erof, delyte &thorn;erynne,</L>
<L N="44">&YOGH;eue men ensample to do so.</L>
<L>Heuene &yogh;ates fro hem they pynne,</L>
<L>Of goddis frendis make goddis foo;</L>
<L>In helle &thorn;ey purchas here ynne;</L>
<L N="48">His felaschipe, with hym thay go.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Blessed euere mote he be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hungren and thursten ry&yogh;twisnes;</L>
<L>He wolde were wel in al degre,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at god and man echon had his.</L>
<L>Gostly hunger and thurstes he</L>
<L>&THORN;at fayn wolde mende &thorn;at is mys.</L>
<L>Ful filled he shal wi&thorn; grete deynte</L>
<L N="56">At goddis feste in heuene blisse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Than cursed is he &thorn;at ful is fylde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wrong take pore mennys thrift,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; pore men be spilde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS.: spi&yogh;ed.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">For synguler profyt is sotyll theft;
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>Make gulteles folk presoned and kylde,</L>
<L>Of hous and land make wrongwys gyft;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hunger and &thorn;irst his hous is bylde.</L>
<L N="64">In helle is shewed euell-sponnen wyft.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Blessid be &thorn;e mercyable;</L>
<L>Mercy and mede, of god he fonges.</L>
<L>In goddis doom he stondes stable,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at wreke&thorn; not all his owen wronges.</L>
<L>To pore folk he is profytable,</L>
<L>&THORN;at leue&thorn; his good hem amonges.</L>
<L>Sorefull and hungry, he fynde&thorn; hem table,</L>
<L N="72">The sorwefull he glade&thorn; to synge songes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thanne, how of hem han hertis stoute</L>
<L>&THORN;at rewe&thorn; non pore &thorn;at han penaunce,</L>
<L>Han nedeles gold no&yogh;t to lene it oute,</L>
<L N="76">But to &thorn;e borwere gret greuaunce;</L>
<L>But he may quyte, is &yogh;erne aboute</L>
<L>To presone hym or make destaunce:</L>
<L>But he be cursed, it is in dowte;</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at ha&thorn; no mercy, <MILESTONE N="122b" UNIT="folio">mote haue vengeaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Blessed be he &thorn;at loue&thorn; pes,</L>
<L>Mekely to goddis byddyng bende.</L>
<L>He shal be cleped, at goddis dees,</L>
<L N="84">Goddis sone, good and hende.</L>
<L>He wolde all werre shulde asses,</L>
<L>Of goddis foon, make goddis frende;</L>
<L>Make soule wi&thorn; ioye to heuene pres,</L>
<L N="88">And sorwe and werre to helle wi&thorn; fende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Than, how of hem &thorn;at pes do&thorn; hate,</L>
<L>Wolde ouerall were werre and woo,</L>
<L>Eche man wi&thorn; o&thorn;er debate,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at shulde be frend, make hem foo;
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>For synguler wynnyng to his astate,</L>
<L>Lede his men, o&thorn;ere to sloo:</L>
<L>He shal be blessed neuere or late;</L>
<L N="96">His werkis curse&thorn; hym, where he go.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The clene of herte, blissed be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyue&thorn; after goddis lore.</L>
<L>God hym self he shal see,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ere as blisse is euere more;</L>
<L>And gouerne&thorn; wel his owen degre,</L>
<L>And do&thorn; &thorn;e dede &thorn;at he come fore;</L>
<L>Fulfylle&thorn; &thorn;e werkis of charyte:</L>
<L N="104">His vertue gadereth mede in store.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The herte &thorn;at is fyled in synne,</L>
<L>And sulpe&thorn; his soule wi&thorn; spottes of blame,</L>
<L>Goddis curs he do&thorn; wynne,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at spyse&thorn; hym-self and goddis name.</L>
<L>His astate, he nele not dwelle &thorn;erynne;</L>
<L>To serue god hym &thorn;enke&thorn; shame.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if god and he departe o twynne,</L>
<L N="112">In helle he may be meked tame.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That is pursued<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. presued]</NOTE> for ri&yogh;twisnes</L>
<L>Is blessid, where he go or ryde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyngdom of heuene is his,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at querell to ende, in charite byde.</L>
<L>God wole brynge hym to heuene blis,</L>
<L>And fro his enemys &thorn;ere wole hym hyde;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at pursue hym with mys,</L>
<L N="120">To helle &thorn;ey ben here awen gyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thanne are they cursed in here lyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;at auaunce&thorn; &thorn;e fals, and stroye&thorn; &thorn;e trewe,</L>
<L>Mayntene fals querell and stryf,</L>
<L N="124">Ri&yogh;twis men wrongly pursue,
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>Defowle bo&thorn;e mayden and wyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;at shulde be clene in alle vertue.</L>
<L>Eche dedly synne is a dedly knyf;</L>
<L N="128">For he shal repe &thorn;at he sewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;e shal be blessid, erly and late,</L>
<L>By vertue of gospell &thorn;at &yogh;e preche.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shul be blessid, whan folk &yogh;ow hate,</L>
<L N="132">And cursen &yogh;ow for &yogh;oure speche.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure tonge is kaye of heuene &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure word, &thorn;e way to heuene hem teche.</L>
<L>Folk wi&thorn; &yogh;ow schal debate,</L>
<L N="136">ffor me wi&thorn; lesynges &yogh;ow apeche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Glade &yogh;e wi&thorn;-ynne, and ioye wi&thorn;-oute;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure mede in heuene moche is.</L>
<L>Drede no tyrauntes sterne and stoute</L>
<L N="140">May sle &thorn;y body, and take as his.</L>
<L>God, &thorn;e fader of heuene, &yogh;e dowte</L>
<L>May brynge &thorn;e soule to pyne or blis;</L>
<L>He schal deme all &thorn;e world aboute,<MILESTONE N="123a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="144">To heuene for goode, to hell for mys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Of er&thorn;e &yogh;e ben cleped 'salt,'</L>
<L>ffor salt of wisdom soule saues;</L>
<L>Go vp-ri&yogh;t and be not halt,</L>
<L N="148">ffor mayster of seruaunt his seruice craues.</L>
<L>&THORN;yn astate rekene &thorn;ou shalt,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou it gat, how &thorn;ou it saues.</L>
<L>Fewe ben chosen, &thorn;ou&yogh; mony ben calt,</L>
<L N="152">Fro goddis seruyce are worldly knaues.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To lanterne &yogh;e ben likned ri&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota</NOTE></L>
<L>In all &thorn;e world &yogh;e shal be kyd.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure prechyng shal be candel li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="156">Nou&yogh;t vnder worldly buschel hyd,
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="101"></L>
<L>But on a candel-styke on hi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t vnder a chiste, vnder a lyd;</L>
<L>In good werkis shyne &yogh;e bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="160">And lyue &yogh;e so, ri&yogh;t as &yogh;e byd.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="22" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XXII. Knowe thy self and thy god.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 123.] [9 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Thenke hertely in &thorn;y &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of what matere &thorn;ou dede bygynne.</L>
<L>Of fylthy seed &thorn;ou were wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="4">And wan in at &thorn;e wyket of synne.</L>
<L>Foulere fyl&thorn;e knowe y nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ou were fed &thorn;y moder wi&thorn;-ynne;</L>
<L>In a sake ful of fil&thorn;e &thorn;ou was out brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8">In wrecchednes horyble, and stynkyng skynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What &thorn;ou art, knowe &thorn;y self wel.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou were conceyued in synne, and born wi&thorn; woo.</L>
<L>&THORN;y moder and &thorn;ou, on fortune whel,</L>
<L N="12">In perile of de&thorn;, parted a-twoo.</L>
<L>Of pynes of helle, what soules fele,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou in mynde keped &thorn;oo,</L>
<L>Hit wolde make &thorn;y corage kele,</L>
<L N="16">Whan &thorn;ou hadde wil, to synne goo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God made &thorn;e of nou&yogh;t, haue in mynde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; soule of resoun; lyk his ymage.</L>
<L>In heuene, wi&thorn; angels, aboue &thorn;e wynde,</L>
<L N="20">He ordeyned &thorn;e endeles heritage.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; more loue he dede &thorn;e bynde:</L>
<L>Bycome &thorn;y brother in mannys lynage.</L>
<L>He, ielous louer and trewest to fynde,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;y soule is spouse to his maryage.
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="102"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To god, thy wedlok wi&thorn; loue holde,</L>
<L>In brennyng contemplacion,</L>
<L>And make nou&yogh;t hym cokewolde,</L>
<L N="28">To loue in fornycacion.</L>
<L>On goddis mercy be not to bolde,</L>
<L>To falle in temptacion.</L>
<L>Kepe charite hot, let it not colde</L>
<L N="32">For quenchyng of deuocion.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Loue all folk in charyte,</L>
<L>Body and soule in good atent,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou wolde &thorn;ey dede &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at is goddis comaundement.</L>
<L>Who breke &thorn;o hestes, cursed is he</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ey come to mendement.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou preyest euere-more in all degre</L>
<L N="40">Til &thorn;at &thorn;ou to synne assent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That &thorn;ou hast don si&thorn; &thorn;ou were bore,</L>
<L>All &thorn;y lyuyng by&thorn;enk &thorn;e newe.</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er hast &thorn;ou more in store,</L>
<L N="44">Or of vices or of vertue;</L>
<L>And whe&thorn;er hast &thorn;ou folwed more</L>
<L>Good aungel or wykked, for bo&thorn;e &thorn;e sewe;</L>
<L>&THORN;y countretayle &thorn;ey wil shewe, &thorn;e skore,</L>
<L N="48">In helle or in heuene, <MILESTONE N="123b" UNIT="folio">wreten trewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Haue mynde, god sente his sone adoun,</L>
<L>Tok mankynde in flesch and felle,</L>
<L>And suffred hard passioun,</L>
<L N="52">Dyed on croys, and heryed helle.</L>
<L>Haue mynde of his resurexioun;</L>
<L>Byleue all &thorn;is trewe gospelle.</L>
<L>Haue mynde on his Assencioun;</L>
<L N="56">On god his fader ri&yogh;t hond, do&thorn; dwelle.
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="103"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;enke &thorn;ou shalt dye, and nost whenne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art incertayn, &thorn;erfore drede.</L>
<L>Fro heueue to er&thorn;e, god shal come &thorn;enne,</L>
<L N="60">Deme euel and good, after here dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e good, to heuene blisse renne,</L>
<L>In endeles lyf to haue here mede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wikked, in helle for to brenne,</L>
<L N="64">In endeles pyne, de&thorn; shal hem fede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The ten comaundementis, &thorn;ou hem kepe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen werkis of mercy, wel hem vse;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuene synnes &thorn;ou be-wepe,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;y fyue wittes &thorn;e auyse.</L>
<L>Do penaunce, and preye whyle &thorn;ou schuld slepe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend and fals[e] world despise;</L>
<L>No fleschly lustes &thorn;e vndercrepe;</L>
<L N="72">Fle all foly, and folwe &thorn;e wise!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="23" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XXIII. Of the sacrament of the Altere.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 123, <I>back</I>.] (16 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab</I>.)</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> wole be mendid &yogh;if y say mys.</L>
<L>Holychirche nes no&thorn;er tre ne stones.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hous of preyers, god nempned &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="4">Bo&thorn;e goode men and wikked ressayue&thorn; at ones.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere as gadryng of goode men ys,</L>
<L>Is holychyrche of flesch and bones.</L>
<L>Prestes are lanterne, hem to wysse</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e wise weyes to heuene wones.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Holychirche, hery&yogh;e &thorn;y saueour,</L>
<L>&THORN;ynk &thorn;y hurd, god on hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; song and ympnes, tyde and houre,</L>
<L N="12">Reioys in hym day and ny&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>For he is more &thorn;an any honour,</L>
<L>For his honour passe&thorn; oure my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For we ben his, and he is oure;</L>
<L N="16">All &thorn;ou&yogh;tes ben to hym dy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A specyall tyme of heryeng here.</L>
<L>Lyueliche quyk bred is put for&thorn; &thorn;is day,</L>
<L>Whyche in &thorn;e table of &thorn;e holy sopere,</L>
<L N="20">Wi&thorn;-outen doute was &yogh;ouen oure fay</L>
<L>To &thorn;e company of twelfe bre&thorn;eren &thorn;ere were.</L>
<L>By here ful heryenge, ioyed &thorn;ay;</L>
<L>Wel sowned in here ere,</L>
<L N="24">Wi&thorn; ioly herte, fayre song to say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A day is mad of solempnyte,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is table first ordynaunce is worschipful tolde.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is newe kynges table, now knowe we</L>
<L N="28">Newe Estren ende&thorn; the olde.</L>
<L>Newe thyng dryue&thorn; old &thorn;yng fro his degre;</L>
<L>Out of mynde, &thorn;e lasse of tolde.</L>
<L>So so&thorn;fast sunne, by hys pouste,</L>
<L N="32">Dryue&thorn; awey shadewe, and stri&yogh;e&thorn; colde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; As ly&yogh;t li&yogh;tene&thorn; ny&yogh;t, fro derkenes of kynde,</L>
<L>So dede crist at &thorn;e holy sopere,</L>
<L>Bad pertely do so of hym mynde,</L>
<L N="36">By holy ordynaunce tau&yogh;t vs to lere,</L>
<L>Halwe bred and wyn, by hys word and wynd,</L>
<L>To an ost of hel&thorn;e to cristen men here,</L>
<L>ffro shadwe of de&thorn;, to gostly blynd,</L>
<L N="40">To li&yogh;t of lyf, to shynen clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lore is &yogh;ouen to cristen men,</L>
<L>In-to flesch passe&thorn; &thorn;e bred;</L>
<L>As holychirche do&thorn; vs kenne,<MILESTONE N="124a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="44">&THORN;e wyn, to blod, &thorn;at is so red.
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou seest not fleschly &thorn;ou takest &thorn;enne;</L>
<L>&THORN;y byleue of herte, make&thorn; &thorn;e fast fro ded,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen ordre of &thorn;ynges, to renne,</L>
<L N="48">By tokene and word &thorn;at he bede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn;-outen help of ordre of &thorn;yngis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bok of oure byleue is lent,</L>
<L>Vnder dyuerce spices only tokenynges,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;e spices fro hym be went,</L>
<L>Not durked ne hyd, but ri&yogh;t shynynges,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; fleschly sy&yogh;t fro hym be blent,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule ha&thorn; ioye, and mery synges,</L>
<L N="56">When good byleue see&thorn; &thorn;e sacrament.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e blod is drynk, &thorn;e flesch is mete,</L>
<L>Ys gostly fode, &thorn;e soules delys;</L>
<L>Neuere-&thorn;e-lattere, of crist to trete,</L>
<L N="60">He dwelle&thorn; vnder ay&thorn;er spys.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ressayuour counte&thorn; not &thorn;at &thorn;ey ete,</L>
<L>Ne breke&thorn; it not, but hool it lys.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; a thowsand take at o sete,</L>
<L N="64">Alone on take&thorn; as moche o prys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; While obley in yrnes, or boyst ys stoken,</L>
<L>Hit nys but bred, and sengyl bake;</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;e prest, to hit, goddis wordis hath spoken,</L>
<L N="68">Crystys quyk body, vndir bred o cake.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; it a &thorn;ousand peces seme broken,</L>
<L>Nes parted ne wasted, but al holl take.</L>
<L>In byleue of holychirche, who wyl hym &yogh;oken,</L>
<L N="72">A&yogh;en &thorn;is, non argument may make.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That ressayue&thorn;, children, man, and wyf,</L>
<L>Not al yliche deuocioun.</L>
<L>Summe taken it in synne and stryf,</L>
<L N="76">As bestes wi&thorn;-outen discrecioun.
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>&THORN;e wikkid resceue&thorn; a dedly knyf,</L>
<L>And his endeles dampnacioun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e good resceyue&thorn; endeles lyf,</L>
<L N="80">To body and soule saluacioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; When &thorn;ou to chirche gost</L>
<L>To resceyue god, wisely go.</L>
<L>I suppose &thorn;e prest haue but on ost,</L>
<L N="84">Breke it, and parte to twenty and mo:</L>
<L>As moche is &thorn;e leste cost</L>
<L>As in &thorn;e grettest pece of &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Deme all yliche, lest and most;</L>
<L N="88">Quaue not, ne drede not, to sen hit so.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;e prest &thorn;e sacrament clyue</L>
<L>In a &thorn;owsand peces and &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&THORN;e state, ne stature, ne my&yogh;t do&thorn; myue,</L>
<L N="92">Ne lese&thorn; ne lasse&thorn; of his pouste.</L>
<L>&THORN;y fleschly sy&yogh;t &thorn;ou shalt not lyue;</L>
<L>But tokene of brekyng make&thorn; he;</L>
<L>For fleschly skyn, no sacrement kan preue,</L>
<L N="96">In gostly bylyue shal saued be.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In old[e] lawe, &yogh;e wyten how</L>
<L>At estren &thorn;ey eten a lamb al ded,</L>
<L>Is ouer put in newe lawe now;</L>
<L N="100">At estre, we eten quyk bred.</L>
<L>In old[e] lawe, for mannys prow,</L>
<L>God &thorn;e comaundementis bed;</L>
<L>And oure newe lawe we don allow,</L>
<L N="104">And kepen bo&thorn;e by goddis red.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lete &thorn;y mercy passe ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And for&yogh;eue vs oure mysdede!</L>
<L>&THORN;y face, wi&thorn; loue to seen in sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="108">In lond of lyf, &thorn;ou vs lede.
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>Among &thorn;y seyntes in heuene on hy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>At &thorn;at feste of lif, god, vs fede!<MILESTONE N="124b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So&thorn;fast bred, god of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="112">Ihesus herde, &thorn;ou vs hede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In sy&yogh;t and in felyng, &thorn;ou semest bred,</L>
<L>In byleue, flesch, blod, and bon;</L>
<L>In sy&yogh;t and felyng, &thorn;ou semest ded,</L>
<L N="116">In byleue, lyf, to speke and gon;</L>
<L>In sy&yogh;t and felyng, no&thorn;er hond ne hed,</L>
<L>In byleue, bo&thorn;e god and man;</L>
<L>In sy&yogh;t and felyng, in litil sted,</L>
<L N="120">In byleue, grettere &thorn;yng nes nan.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whan Abraham of Ysaac his offryng made,</L>
<L>ffor a ffygure he lykned is</L>
<L>To angels bred, oure fadres hadde,</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at god fed hem in wyldernes.</L>
<L>Afterward, god hem bade,</L>
<L>"A paske lomb rosted, and ete&thorn; &thorn;es."</L>
<L>In stede of &thorn;at, oure soules to glade,</L>
<L N="128">We resceyue oure housell, god o blisse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="24" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XXIV. The Lessouns of the Dirige.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Digby</I> 102, <I>leaf</I> 124, <I>back</I>.] [52 stanzas of 8, <I>abab, abab</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="lesson">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>prima</I>: Parce mihi, domine.</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Almy&yogh;ty god, lord, me spare,</L>
<L>ffor so&thorn;e, my dayes werkys ben no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>My wittes on ny&yogh;tes wrong y ware,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;erof longe &yogh;eres mon be wro&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;enke, man, &thorn;ou ware born ful bare.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;is world what hastou bro&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world whanne &thorn;ou schalt fare,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;ou schalt bere with &thorn;e ry&yogh;t no&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="108"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What is man of gret renoun,</L>
<L>That of hym self make&thorn; aldre mest?</L>
<L>Why settyst &thorn;ou &thorn;y herte a&yogh;en resoun,</L>
<L N="12">And sodeynly repreuest hem mest?</L>
<L>In &thorn;e dawenynge &thorn;ou sou&yogh;test hem vpsodoun.</L>
<L>Contrary to godis hest</L>
<L>&THORN;ou purchasest &thorn;y saule helle prisoun;</L>
<L N="16">For fleschely lust, wormes fest.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; How longe sparest &thorn;ou me no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To swolwe my spotel, bote it me gryue?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou keper of men, alle &thorn;yng hast wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="20">What shal y do to &thorn;yn byhyue?</L>
<L>What hastou set me contrarie &thorn;y &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;y holy lawe to repryue?</L>
<L>Lord, whenne my werkis mon be so&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="24">Dyspyce me no&yogh;t in my myschyue!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ful heuy to my self y am maad withynne;</L>
<L>My werkes, on me heuye isse.</L>
<L>Why takest &thorn;ou no&yogh;t away my synne,</L>
<L N="28">And bere from me my wykednesse?</L>
<L>I slepe in dust, for we ben kynne,</L>
<L>For erthe clayme&yogh; me for hisse.</L>
<L>To seche me eerly, &yogh;if &thorn;ou begynne,</L>
<L N="32">I ne may withstonde &thorn;e y-wisse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="lesson">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>secunda</I>: Tedet animam meam.</HEAD>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My soul, of my self anoyed isse.</L>
<L>I shal leue my speche a&yogh;ens me.</L>
<L>To my soul y wole speke in bitternesse,</L>
<L N="36">And y shal saye to god so fre:</L>
<L>Wyl no&yogh;t dampne me fro blisse,</L>
<L>Shew me &thorn;e cause, &thorn;at wolde I se,</L>
<L>Why demestou me &thorn;o&yogh; y dede mysse,</L>
<L N="40">Lord, whether &thorn;e &thorn;ynke good to &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="109"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou chalenge my werk, and bere me doun,</L>
<L>Me that am werk of &thorn;y hande,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou in consayl helpe &yogh;e moun</L>
<L N="44">To wykked men here synnes withstande,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; repentaunce and sorwful<MILESTONE N="125a" UNIT="folio"> soun</L>
<L>May launce hem from &thorn;e deuelys bande:</L>
<L>To &yogh;erde of loue y moste me boun;</L>
<L N="48">Lord, me chastice wi&thorn; &thorn;at wande.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whe&thorn;er &thorn;yn ey&yogh;en ben fleschlye,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou seest as man shal see?</L>
<L>Or &thorn;y dayes so sone sy&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="52">As other mennys dayes be?</L>
<L>Or &thorn;y &yogh;erys ri&yogh;t so hye,</L>
<L>As mennys tymes in here degre?&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art god shal neuere dy&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="56">For sorwe and de&thorn; shal from the fle&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That &thorn;ou seche my wykkednesse,</L>
<L>And ransake my synne,</L>
<L>And wyte I haue no&yogh;t doun mysse,</L>
<L N="60">Bote hert and soule clene withynne.</L>
<L>So&thorn;es &thorn;er no man nesse</L>
<L>May skape &thorn;yn hond, and from the twynne,</L>
<L>Bote repentaunce and mercy kesse.</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at now ben frendis, lord, make hem kynne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="lesson">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>tertia</I>: Manus tue feceruntme.</HEAD>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thy hand made me man of resoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. &thorn;e soun]</NOTE></L>
<L>And shope me al in compas,</L>
<L>And sodeynly &thorn;ou cast me doun,</L>
<L N="68">ffor knew y no&yogh;t what &thorn;ou was.</L>
<L>Of me men sample take mowen,</L>
<L>Be ware lest &thorn;ay folwe my tras.</L>
<L>I hadde lordship in feld and toun,</L>
<L N="72">Now on a donghille is my pas.
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="110"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Haue mynde on me, lord, and take hede</L>
<L>Of fen of erthe &thorn;ou dede me make.</L>
<L>In-to dust a&yogh;en &thorn;ou shalt me lede,</L>
<L N="76">My soule from &thorn;e body take.</L>
<L>My flesch is ful sleper atte nede,</L>
<L>And solpe&thorn; my soule wi&thorn; synnes blake.</L>
<L>Lord god, &thorn;y dome y drede.</L>
<L N="80">Whanne &thorn;ou comest, y mon awake.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My hert shulde be stedefast,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast lopred as mylk, and slep in &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as chese &thorn;ou croddest me fast.</L>
<L N="84">I wyte my synnes &thorn;at y wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Lord, alle my synnes away &thorn;ou cast,</L>
<L>Bote wi&thorn; my synnes cast me no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou knowest how longe my lyf shulde last;</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;ou sette my terme, y passe it no&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou clo&thorn;edest me with flesch and skyn,</L>
<L>With bones and synewes made me to-gyder;</L>
<L>Lyf and mercy &yogh;af me withyn;</L>
<L N="92">As brotel vessel y stonde slyder.</L>
<L>&THORN;y sechyng ha&thorn; kepyd my gost with wyn.</L>
<L>A, lord, whenne &thorn;ou comest hyder</L>
<L>To deme al er&thorn;e, &thorn;y domes to twyn</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;ou&yogh; I wolde fle, I not no&yogh;t whyder.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To deme &thorn;e erthe whanne &thorn;ou wendys,</L>
<L>Fro face of &thorn;y wra&thorn;&thorn;e whyder shal I go?</L>
<L>To hyde me wi&thorn; angels aren goddis frendys?</L>
<L N="100">And god me hate, &thorn;ay ben my fo.</L>
<L>And I hyde me in helle among fendys,</L>
<L>In pyne &thorn;ay wolen tormente me so.</L>
<L>I haue synned <MILESTONE N="125b" UNIT="folio">ri&yogh;t moche, my synne me schendys.</L>
<L N="104">Me thynke &thorn;ay waxen mo and mo.
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="111"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My trespas moche arn blamed.</L>
<L>Bote repentaunce be mendement,</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e, y drede, y am aschamed.</L>
<L N="108">Whenne &thorn;ou comest to iugement,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren wylde, mon be tamed,</L>
<L>Al wopen of wra&thorn;&thorn;e mon be brent;</L>
<L>In bok of lyf &thorn;o &thorn;at be named,</L>
<L N="112">To ioye of heuene mon be sent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Almy&yogh;ty god, lord, me &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>In thy mercy &thorn;ou me lede.</L>
<L>Whenne my soule is boden out fleme,</L>
<L N="116">Helpe me, lord, atte al my nede.</L>
<L>Whenne &thorn;ou al &thorn;e world shal deme,</L>
<L>Dampne me no&yogh;t after my dede.</L>
<L>Whenne &thorn;at angels blowen here beme,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;enne alle folk may haue gret drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; From worldis worschipe y am shoue,</L>
<L>And bro&yogh;t abas from al astat.</L>
<L>My skyn is clo&thorn;ed al on roue,</L>
<L N="124">In pouerte and peyne my wyt is mat.</L>
<L>Lord, chastice me wi&thorn; &yogh;erd of loue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; y haue seruyd &thorn;e swerd of hat.</L>
<L>Wherto wyltou &thorn;y maystry proue,</L>
<L N="128">Wi&thorn; suchon as I to make debat?</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="lesson">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>quarta</I>: Quantas habeo.</HEAD>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Als many wykkednesse and trespas</L>
<L>And synnes withoute noumbre mo</L>
<L>Shew me; why hydest &thorn;y fas</L>
<L N="132">fro me, and demest me &thorn;y fo?</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;enkes &thorn;e solace</L>
<L>This turment, and do me wo?</L>
<L>A drope of thy mercie of oyle of grace,</L>
<L N="136">Lord, graunte me er y go.
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="112"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I am slyme of erthe, haue in mynde,</L>
<L>Pore of matere and dedely,</L>
<L>As a lef styrede with wynde.</L>
<L N="140">On me &thorn;ou prouest &thorn;y maystry.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou prouest &thorn;y my&yogh;t, and &thorn;at I fynde,</L>
<L>O &thorn;e stubble, &thorn;at is so drye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou pursuest me, and wylt me bynde,</L>
<L N="144">Wi&thorn; synnes in my &yogh;ou&thorn;e &thorn;ou wylt me stroye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lord, &thorn;ou pursuest me fast,</L>
<L>for so&thorn;e, a&yogh;ens me &thorn;ou doest wryte</L>
<L>Bitternesse, bote swete is past.</L>
<L N="148">I may no&yogh;t blenche whenne &thorn;ou wylt smyte.</L>
<L>I trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt me wast,</L>
<L>With synnes in my &yogh;ou&thorn;e do me endite.</L>
<L>Lord, on me &thorn;y wille &thorn;ou hast.</L>
<L N="152">My grete synne myself y wyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In synne &thorn;ou settest my fot and hede,</L>
<L>And alle my werkes hastou so&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And alle steppys y euere &yogh;ede;</L>
<L N="156">&YOGH;e haue nombred alle my wordes and &thorn;o&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ou hast taken hede,</L>
<L>Roten y schal be, wasted to no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>As clothes &thorn;at mo&thorn;&thorn;es on hem fede,</L>
<L N="160">So shal my flesch with wormes so&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wo [to] me, so mon y be,</L>
<L>For y haue don moche synne.</L>
<L>I, wreche, whyder shal y fle</L>
<L N="164">ffor wrechyd lyf y lyued ynne?</L>
<L>My lord, my god, no&yogh;t bote to the!</L>
<L>God of mercie, on me mynne!</L>
<L>Lord, haue mercie on me,</L>
<L N="168">Let no&yogh;t thy loue<MILESTONE N="126a" UNIT="folio"> fro me twynne!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="lesson"><PB REF="00000147.tif" N="113">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>quinta</I>: Homo natus.</HEAD>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, that is of woman born,</L>
<L>Lyuynge short tyme he is.</L>
<L>Er his nauel be knytte and shorn,</L>
<L N="172">ffulfilde with many wrechidnes.</L>
<L>Er he fro moder be forborn,</L>
<L>In peryl of deth, bothe partie es.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if flesch be lord, the soule is lorn;</L>
<L N="176">Bote soule be lord, he leseth his blys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man geth out as don floures,</L>
<L>Corage and strengthe, and fayre of hewe;</L>
<L>Make&thorn; moche of hymself, say&thorn;e al is oures,</L>
<L N="180">And repeth &thorn;at he neuere ne sewe.</L>
<L>He is defouled be dayes and houres,</L>
<L>And flee&thorn; as shadow, &thorn;at neuere grewe;</L>
<L>Dwelle&thorn; neuere in &thorn;e self stat of ouris,</L>
<L N="184">Encresce&thorn; mo vyces &thorn;an vertew.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou holdest worthy to open thyn ey,</L>
<L>And come to me, and clayme for rent,</L>
<L>To loke on such a wrecche as y,</L>
<L N="188">And lede hym with the to iugement,</L>
<L>&THORN;er al mankynde in company,</L>
<L>Atte thy general parlement;</L>
<L>Vertues to heuen ther schul &yogh;e try,</L>
<L N="192">The vyces in helle fyre be brent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What man may make hym clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is conceyued in vnclene sed?</L>
<L>Ywhether &thorn;ou art alone, withoute mene?</L>
<L N="196">To felowschipe &thorn;ou hast non nede.</L>
<L>Short ar mannys dayes sene,</L>
<L>And the nombre of hys monthes in thy dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast sette his terme of fat and lene,</L>
<L N="200">He passe&thorn; it no&yogh;t for no mede.
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="114"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A, go away a lytel hym fro,</L>
<L>In mendement that he mow rest</L>
<L>Tyl the day he &yogh;erned so,</L>
<L N="204">A, of harde man, come &thorn;at is best.</L>
<L>Lord, haue no mynde to do me wo,</L>
<L>fforber my synnes wolde make me lest.</L>
<L>Lord, whenne &thorn;ou comest to deme so</L>
<L N="208">Al &thorn;e world be fyre, bo&thorn;e est and west,</L>
<L>God, in &thorn;y sy&yogh;t &thorn;y way y go</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t ham; in &thorn;y fay&thorn; me fest!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lord, whenne &thorn;ou demest alle &thorn;yng in ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="212">Wher mercie shal no&yogh;t knawen be;</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t lese&thorn; no&yogh;t his my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; mercie be in companye.</L>
<L>Mercy is euere in &thorn;y sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="216">For mercie euere &thorn;yn ey&yogh;en se.</L>
<L>Wher-euere &thorn;y dome is dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t clayme&thorn; mercie for his fee.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="lesson">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>sexta</I>: Quis mihi hoc tribuat.</HEAD>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Who &yogh;eue&thorn; to me, &thorn;at y me hyde</L>
<L N="220">Tylle &thorn;y wra&thorn;&thorn;e in helle be past?</L>
<L>Withouten pyne, &thorn;y dome to byde,</L>
<L>Tyl body and soule a&yogh;en be fast?</L>
<L>With arguments no&yogh;t me chyde!</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;ou knowest how longe my lyf shal last.</L>
<L>Lord, lat mercie be my gyde,</L>
<L>And neuere fro &thorn;y face me cast!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou set me a tyme; couenant is tan.</L>
<L N="228">Haue mynde on me, what dome is di&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Trowest &thorn;ou ou&yogh;t &thorn;at y, dede man,</L>
<L>Shal haue a&yogh;eyn man of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;elde rekenyng sen y bygan</L>
<L N="232">With alle dayes &thorn;at y now fy&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Now I abyde &thorn;at I fro ran,<MILESTONE N="126b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tyl my folwyng come to myn insi&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="115"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Lord, &thorn;ou shalt clepe me,</L>
<L N="236">And I shal answere to &thorn;e, werk of &thorn;yn hande.</L>
<L>Werk of &thorn;y ri&yogh;t hand, take to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt not bynde it in helle bande.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast noumbred my steppes, how mony &thorn;ay be,</L>
<L N="240">How monye y ran, how monye I stande.</L>
<L>Bot spare &thorn;ou, lord, to &thorn;e synne of me,</L>
<L>Ne wilne no&yogh;t deme my werkes &yogh;e fande.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Deme me no&yogh;t after my dede,</L>
<L N="244">Lord, I byseche &thorn;e!</L>
<L>I haue don in &thorn;y si&yogh;t, and tok non hede;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I praye &thorn;y mageste,</L>
<L>God, my wikkednesse away &thorn;ou lede,</L>
<L N="248">Myn vnry&yogh;t away wasche &yogh;e!</L>
<L>Non more; lord, at my nede,</L>
<L>Of alle my synnes clense &yogh;e me!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="lesson">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>septima</I>: Spiritus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. sp&cmacr;]</NOTE> meus.</HEAD>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My gost, shalt &thorn;ou be made newe,</L>
<L N="252">My dayes shulle yshorted be;</L>
<L>My soule fro &thorn;e body mon remewe,</L>
<L>Alone a graue byleueth to me.</L>
<L>I haue non synne, no vices me sewe,</L>
<L N="256">Myn eyen in bitternesse dwelle y se.</L>
<L>Deliuere me, lord, and on me rewe,</L>
<L>And sette me bysydes the!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whos hande &thorn;ou wolt a&yogh;eyn me fy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="260">And &thorn;ou proue &thorn;y stronge hande?</L>
<L>My dayes ben passed to withstonde &thorn;y my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>I may no&yogh;t bere &thorn;y litel wande.</L>
<L>My thou&yogh;tes ben wasted, turned in ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="264">Turmentynge my herte inwith and ande;</L>
<L>And turnyd day to &thorn;e ny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>After derkenesse I haue bedded my bed, I fande.
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="116"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I sayde to stynke and rotenesse,</L>
<L N="268">'My fader and moder arn &yogh;e;'</L>
<L>And to wormes y sayde &thorn;ysse:</L>
<L>'My systren and my brethern both be &yogh;e.'</L>
<L>And erthe clayme&thorn; me for hysse,</L>
<L N="272">Where &thorn;en now my bydynge to me.</L>
<L>My felynge &thorn;ou art, and my god of blisse.</L>
<L>Drede of deth droueth me.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eche a day synnyng,</L>
<L N="276">And euere newe encres;</L>
<L>Neuere a day blynnyng,</L>
<L>Bote euere vertue wane les.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. waneles]</NOTE></L>
<L>To repente no bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="280">No&yogh;t bote gadre synne ay in pres.</L>
<L>In helle is no wynnyng,</L>
<L>Ne non a&yogh;eynbyynge to pes.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="lesson">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>octava</I>: Pelli mee.</HEAD>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My flesches ben wasted, don me refuse,</L>
<L N="284">My bones cleuyn vnto &thorn;e skyn;</L>
<L>My lippes arn shronken out of syse,</L>
<L>Aboute my teth arn left atwyn.</L>
<L>Haue mercye on myn werk vnwyse,</L>
<L N="288">Haue mercie on me, let mercie wyn!</L>
<L>Namly my frendes, me no&yogh;t despyse;</L>
<L>Lordis hande hath towched me more and myn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Why pursue &yogh;e me, and on me syte,</L>
<L N="292">And arn filled of my flesch and fel?</L>
<L>Who &yogh;eue&thorn; to <I>me</I>, &thorn;at wolde y wyte,</L>
<L>Wordes in boke be ered wel,</L>
<L>Or in a plate of led wryten</L>
<L N="296">With an yren poyntel,</L>
<L>Or in a flynt grauen and spyten</L>
<L>By craft of werk withoute chysel?
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="117"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I byleue <MILESTONE N="127a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at soth y say,</L>
<L N="300">Myn a&yogh;eynbyere lyuynge isse.</L>
<L>I shal rysen of &thorn;e erthe my laste day,</L>
<L>Bylapped in my flesch and skyn ywisse;</L>
<L>Byholde with myn ey&yogh;en twey,</L>
<L N="304">Se god, my sauyour, in blisse;</L>
<L>Non other ey&yogh;en bote &thorn;es, withouten nay;</L>
<L>&THORN;e hope in my bosom yput vp isse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The soule is in derkenesse from gostly sy&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="308">Lord, &yogh;yue here rest and pees!</L>
<L>Withouten ende, &yogh;yue here ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Euerlastynge ly&yogh;t, &thorn;at neuere shal sees!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at rered Lazar on hy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="312">Out of &thorn;e graue, stynkynge fro wormes pres,</L>
<L>&THORN;y pauylon of mercy be on hem py&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To reste fro pyne, make hem reles.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="lesson">
<HEAD>Lectio <I>nona</I>: Quare de uulua<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. nulla]</NOTE> eduxisti me qui, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Out of &thorn;e wombe, why hastou me bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;at wolde y hadde be fordon?</L>
<L>&THORN;anne hadde I be as no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Noon ey&yogh;e hadde sene me after son;</L>
<L>&THORN;an hadde I be as vn wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="320">No&yogh;t born from wombe to berelis doun,</L>
<L>Where my short dayes arn in my &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Where &thorn;ay shal no&yogh;t be ended moun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A, &thorn;erfore, lord, graunte me &thorn;es</L>
<L N="324">To wepe and wayle, repente my synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y torne no&yogh;t a&yogh;eyn to erthe of derkenes,</L>
<L>To stryues of de&thorn;, be curyd &thorn;erynne,</L>
<L>Lond of wrethes and &thorn;esternesse</L>
<L N="328">&THORN;er is shadew of de&thorn;, noon o&thorn;er wynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;er wone&thorn; euerlastynge for hem lyued mysse,</L>
<L>Euere gryslyhede, &thorn;at neuere schal blynne.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="lesson"><PB REF="00000152.tif" N="118">
<HEAD>Libera me, domine.</HEAD>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Delyuere me, lord, from endeles de&thorn;e</L>
<L N="332">In &thorn;at grete dredful day,</L>
<L>Where heuenys schullen be styred from er&thorn;e bre&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Whenne &thorn;ou shalt come to deme for ay.</L>
<L>To heuen, or helle, &thorn;at on he ge&thorn;;</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;e word be fyre, and grete afray.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne, woo to the synful, his soule sle&thorn;,</L>
<L>And fendys claymen hym for here pray.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That day shal be a day of drede,</L>
<L N="340">Of wra&thorn;&thorn;e and myschyf, and wrechidnesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere may no man o&thorn;ere rede,</L>
<L>Ne make amendis for his mysse.</L>
<L>ffor worldly witnesse of synful ded,</L>
<L N="344">Gostly payne in bitternesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere helpe&thorn; ne&thorn;er counseil ne med;</L>
<L>Ech man for hymself, to payne, or blysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L>&para; What shal y say for shame and drede,</L>
<L N="348">Or what to do, fool and nys,</L>
<L>Whanne y shal schewe for&thorn; no good dede</L>
<L>Byfore so gret iuge and wys?</L>
<L>Al folk on me woln take hede,</L>
<L N="352">Wayte after vertue, and fynde vys.</L>
<L>Say, "God, mercy, &thorn;y dome y drede,</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e, al mercy lys."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Now, crist, of &thorn;y mercie we craue,</L>
<L N="356">Haue mercie on vs, and leue no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>We byseche &thorn;e, &thorn;at come <MILESTONE N="127b" UNIT="folio">mankynde to saue.</L>
<L>To bye vs, &thorn;ou from heuene vs so&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Oure herytage for vs to haue.</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at wern lorn, &thorn;ou hast bo&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wyl no&yogh;t dampne in helle kaue,</L>
<L>Thy honde warke &thorn;ou hast wro&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="119"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e brennynge soule in helle hete,</L>
<L N="364">Withouten ende wepe thoo.</L>
<L>Allas, oure synnes don vs bete,</L>
<L>&THORN;ay say, 'wo, wo, wo!</L>
<L>Here is no remedie to gete.'</L>
<L N="368">&THORN;ay walke in derkenesse to and fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stynk and derkenesse is so grete,</L>
<L>Allas, in &thorn;ysternesse we go.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God, that art shapere of al,</L>
<L N="372">Of slyme of erthe &thorn;ou me wro&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;y blod principal,</L>
<L>Wonderly &thorn;ou haste vs bo&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; my body now rote smal,</L>
<L N="376">My soule to my body shal be bro&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Out of my graue, reyse me &thorn;ou schal</L>
<L>To lyues man, and fayle no&yogh;t,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Blod and boon, flesche and felle.</L>
<L N="380">Here my prayer: in parfitnesse</L>
<L>At domesday comaunde my soule to dwelle</L>
<L>In Abrahamys bosum, in thy blisse,</L>
<L>Whenne &thorn;ou shalt delyuere me fram sy&yogh;t of helle.</L>
<L N="384">&THORN;ou breke &thorn;e &yogh;ates of helle, ywisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sou&yogh;test helle in peynes felle,</L>
<L>&YOGH;af ly&yogh;t to hem in grete bry&yogh;tnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alas, y may be schamed sore,</L>
<L N="388">At domesday stonde in drede;</L>
<L>I, to come so gret a Iuge byfore,</L>
<L>And shewe for&thorn; no good dede,</L>
<L>Bote fardel of synnes gadred in store;</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;e fendes redy my rolle to rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e countretayle to shewe, &thorn;e score,</L>
<L>&THORN;e leste steppe &thorn;at euere y &yogh;ede.
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="120"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The good aungel on his ry&yogh;t syde,</L>
<L N="396">Whenne he hem ladde with merye songe,</L>
<L>And whenne he wolde no&yogh;t folwe hy[m], glyde</L>
<L>Out of the waye, he wente wronge;</L>
<L>In vertues he nolde abyde;</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;e good aungel mourned amonge.</L>
<L>"With &thorn;e soule nel y chyde;</L>
<L>Y &yogh;eue &thorn;e vp for endeles longe."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L>&para; At domesday no man shal be excusyd,</L>
<L N="404">Lord ne lady, mayde ne knaue;</L>
<L>ffor wykked counsel scholde be refusyd,</L>
<L>And after good counsayle craue.</L>
<L>After warke &thorn;at &thorn;ay vsed,</L>
<L N="408">I shal hem deme, or saue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sauyd excusyd, &thorn;e dampnyd accusyd,</L>
<L>As thay deseruyd echon haue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ech touche and mouynge with hys honde,</L>
<L N="412">&THORN;e leste twynkelynge wy&thorn; his ey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>His wronge worke sitte or stonde,</L>
<L>Ryde or go, sitte or ly&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; he spede no&yogh;t &thorn;ere he dede fonde,</L>
<L N="416">Hys conscience wole hym bewrye;</L>
<L>Benefice, auauncement, hous or londe,</L>
<L>The leste bargayn &thorn;at he dede bye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="25" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XXV. (Pety Job, or Parce mihi, Domine!)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Douce MS.</I> 322,<NOTE PLACE="foot">At the beginning, a coat of arms painted: gules, a chevron azure, between three garbs or, 2 and 1.</NOTE> <I>leaf</I> 10.] [57 stanzas of 12, <I>abab, abab</I>, and <I>baba</I> or <I>bcbc</I>, with Latin subjects.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>Here begynneth the nyne lessons of the Dirige whych Job made in hys tribulacion, lying on the Donghyll, and ben declared more opynly to lewde 
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="121"> mennes vnderstanding by a solempne, worthy, and dis|crete clerke, Rychard <I>Hampole</I>, and ys cleped pety Job, and ys full profitable to stere synners to compunccion.</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Parce michi, domine, nichil enim sunt dies mei.</HEAD>
<L>Lyef lord, my soule thow spare,</L>
<L>The sothe I sey now sykerly,</L>
<L>That my dayes nought they are;</L>
<L N="4">ffor though I be bryght of ble,</L>
<L>The fayrest man that ys oughware,</L>
<L>Yet shall my fayrenesse fade and fle,</L>
<L>And I shalbe wormes ware.</L>
<L N="8">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when my body ys all bare,</L>
<L>And on a bere brought shal be,</L>
<L>I nat what I may synge thare</L>
<L N="12">But <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quid est homo, quia magnificas eum?</HEAD>
<L>What ys a man, wete I wolde,</L>
<L>That magnifyeth hymself alway,</L>
<L>But a marke, made in molde,</L>
<L N="16">Of a clyngyng clot of clay?</L>
<L>Thow shopest vs for that we shulde</L>
<L>Haue ben in blysse for euer and ay;</L>
<L>But nowe, allas, bothe yong and olde</L>
<L N="20">fforyety&ntilde; hit bothe nyght and day.</L>
<L>A, good lord, what shall I say,</L>
<L>I that stande in thys degre?</L>
<L>I wote nothyng that helpe may</L>
<L N="24">But <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Aut quid opponis erga eum cor tuum, visitas eum diliculo, <I>et</I> subito probas illum?</HEAD>
<L N="25">Or why puttist thow thyn hert ayenst man</L>
<L>That thow hast so dere bought?</L>
<L>Thow vysyteste hym, and art full fayne</L>
<L N="28">Sodenly to preue yef he be ought.
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>To longe in synne we haue layne;</L>
<L>ffor synne hath so oure soule thorow sought,</L>
<L>To helpe oureself haue we no mayne,</L>
<L N="32">So moche woo hit hath vs wrought.</L>
<L>But to the pyt when we be brought,</L>
<L>Then men woll wepe for the and me.</L>
<L>But certes all that helpeth nought</L>
<L N="36">But <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vsquequo non parcis michi nec dimittas me vt gluciam saliuam meam? peccaui.</HEAD>
<L N="37">Or why so longe or thow wolt spare</L>
<L>Me in synne that depe dyue?</L>
<L>Thow woldest suffer neuer more</L>
<L N="40">Me to swolowe my salyue?</L>
<L>I haue the gylt, and greuyd sore,</L>
<L>ffor synne with me hathe ben to ryue.</L>
<L>But, lord, now lere me with thy lore</L>
<L N="44">That dedly synne fro me may dryue.</L>
<L>And Ihesu, for thy woundes fyue,</L>
<L>As thow becammest man for me,</L>
<L>When I shall passe oute of lyue,</L>
<L N="48">Than <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quid faciam tibi, o custos hominum? quare posuisti me contrarium tibi, <I>et</I> factus sum michimet ipsi grauis?</HEAD>
<L N="49">What shall I do vn-to the,</L>
<L>O thow kepar of all mankynde?</L>
<L>Of suche a matiere why madest thow me,</L>
<L N="52">To the contrarious me for to fynde?</L>
<L>O fader of heuen, fayre and fre,</L>
<L>As thow art bothe good and hende,</L>
<L>Yet be kynde as thow hast be,</L>
<L N="56">And spare me, lorde, that am vnkynde.</L>
<L>Thy frenshyp, fader, late me fynde,</L>
<L>As thow art god in trinite.</L>
<L>Of thy mercy make me haue mynde</L>
<L N="60">Wyth <I>Parce michi, domine.</I>
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="123"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<HEAD><MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio">Cur non tollis peccatum meum, <I>et</I> quare non aufers iniquitatem meam?</HEAD>
<L N="61">Why takest thow nat my syn away,</L>
<L>A, thow god of all goodnesse?</L>
<L>And why also, as I the say,</L>
<L N="64">Dost nat awey my wykednesse?</L>
<L>Thow madest me of a clot of clay,</L>
<L>That breketh ofte thorough brotylnesse.</L>
<L>ffull brotyll I am, hit ys no nay;</L>
<L N="68">That maketh me ofte to do amysse.</L>
<L>But good Ihesu, I pray thys</L>
<L>ffor thy grete benygnyte:</L>
<L>Thy mercy, lorde, late me nat mys,</L>
<L N="72">But <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ecce, nunc in puluere dormio; <I>et</I> si mane me quesieris, non subsistam.</HEAD>
<L N="73">Loo, in pouder I shall slepe,</L>
<L>ffor owte of poudere furst I cam,</L>
<L>And into poudere must I crepe,</L>
<L N="76">ffor of that same kynde I am.</L>
<L>That I ne am pouder I may not threpe,</L>
<L>ffor erthe I am, as was Adam;</L>
<L>And nowe my pytte ys doluen depe.</L>
<L N="80">Though men me seke, ryght nought I am.</L>
<L>O thow, fader Abraham,</L>
<L>ffor Mary loue, that mayde so fre,</L>
<L>In whos blode thy son swamme,</L>
<L N="84">So <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<HEAD>TEdet animam meam vite mee; dimittam aduer|sum me eloquium meum; loquar in amari|tudine amime mee; dicam deo, "noli me condempnare; indica michi cur me ita iudices."</HEAD>
<L N="85">Hyt forthynketh my soule y-wys,</L>
<L>The lyfe that I haue lad alway;</L>
<L>ffor now my speche ayenst me ys,</L>
<L N="88">Sothly my lyfe I shall dysplay.
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>In sorow and in bytternesse</L>
<L>Of myn oune soule, thus shall I say:</L>
<L>Now, good Ihesu, kynge of blysse,</L>
<L N="92">Dampne me nat at domesday.</L>
<L>And, good Ihesu, to the I pray,</L>
<L>Telle how thus thow demest me.</L>
<L>Nowe yeue me mercy, and say nat nay,</L>
<L N="96">Wyth <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nunquid tibi bonum videtur si calumpnieris <I>et</I> oprimas me, opus manuum tuarum, <I>et</I> consilium impiorum adiuues?</HEAD>
<L N="97">Semeth hit good, lorde, vnto the,</L>
<L>To thryste me doune, and me accuse?</L>
<L>I am thy werke, thow madest me:</L>
<L N="100">Thyne oune handwerk thow nat refuse.</L>
<L>Wythyn the close of cheryte,</L>
<L>Good god, thow me recluse,</L>
<L>And yef I gylte the in any degre,</L>
<L N="104">With thy mercy thow me excuse,</L>
<L>Ne late me neuer of maters muse</L>
<L>That fallen vnto dyshoneste.</L>
<L>Thys prayer thow nat recuse,</L>
<L N="108">But <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nunquid oculi carnei tibi sunt aut sicut videt homo <I>et</I> tu vides?</HEAD>
<L N="109">Whether thyne eyen flesshly be,</L>
<L>Or yef thow seest as seeth a man?</L>
<L>Nay, forsooth, but oonly we</L>
<L N="112">Of outeward thynges beholdyng han;</L>
<L>But inward thynges dost thow se,</L>
<L>That non other may se ne can;</L>
<L>Therfore, lorde, I pray to the,</L>
<L N="116">Warne me when I am mystan,</L>
<L>That I may flee fro foule sathan,</L>
<L>That ys aboute to perysshe me.</L>
<L>Lese nat thow ones wan,</L>
<L N="120">But <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="125"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nunquid sicut dies hominis dies tui <I>et</I> anni tui sicut humana sunt tempora?</HEAD>
<L N="121">Whether thy dayes, lord, be syke</L>
<L>As mennys dayes, that dwellen here,<MILESTONE N="11a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Or thy yeres be ought lyke</L>
<L N="124">To the tymes of mannes yere?</L>
<L>That day a man ys fresshe and fryke,</L>
<L>And sheweth forth a gladsom chere;</L>
<L>But to-morow he wexeth syke,</L>
<L N="128">And haply borne forthe on a bere.</L>
<L>Thus mannes tyme ys in a were;</L>
<L>But thy tyme stondeth in oo degre.</L>
<L>Therfore, I pray in thys manere:</L>
<L N="132">Lorde, <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vt queras iniquitatem meam, <I>et</I> peccatum meum scruteris, <I>et</I> scias quia nichil impium fecerim, cum sit nemo qui de manu tua possit eruere.</HEAD>
<L N="133">ffor to seche my wyckednesse,</L>
<L>And for suche thus all my synne,</L>
<L>Me thynketh hit commeth of grete hardnes,</L>
<L N="136">With me, lorde, so to begynne.</L>
<L>Shewe thow forth thy grete goodnes,</L>
<L>And thyne hardshyp vp thow pynne.</L>
<L>Thynke opon the brytylnesse</L>
<L N="140">That alwey worcheth me withynne.</L>
<L>And sythen I may nat fro the twyn,</L>
<L>Ne from thyne hande warysshed be,</L>
<L>Though I offende more or mynne,</L>
<L N="144">Euer <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Manus tue fecerunt me, <I>et</I> plasmauerunt me totum in circuitu, <I>et</I> sic repente precipitas me.</HEAD>
<L N="145">Thyne handes, lorde, haue made me,</L>
<L>And formed me in shape of man,</L>
<L>And me thow settest in degre</L>
<L N="148">Of grete nobley after than.
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>But whan I, thorough the sotylte,</L>
<L>Deceyued was of foule sathan,</L>
<L>Thow puttedyst me fro that dignite,</L>
<L N="152">Heldyng doune on my brayn pan.</L>
<L>Noon other cause alege I can,</L>
<L>But that synne hathe depryued me.</L>
<L>Now, for the blood that from the ranne,</L>
<L N="156">So <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Memento, queso, quod sicut lutum feceris me, <I>et</I> in puluerem reduces me.</HEAD>
<L N="157">Haue mynde, therfore, I the pray,</L>
<L>O thow god, almyghty kynge.</L>
<L>Thynke thow madest me of clay,</L>
<L N="160">And in-to clay thow shalt me brynge.</L>
<L>Suche ys thy myght, and hath be ay.</L>
<L>And sythen thow madest furst all thynge,</L>
<L>Who dare sey ayene the nay,</L>
<L N="164">To lette thy wyll or thy lykyng?</L>
<L>There ys man olde ne yonge</L>
<L>That stryue dar ayenst the.</L>
<L>Therfore, nede maketh me synge,</L>
<L N="168">Lorde, <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nonne sicut lac mulsisti me, <I>et</I> sicut caseum me coagulasti?</HEAD>
<L N="169">Mylkedest nat me, lorde, as mylke,</L>
<L>With nesshe blood whan thow me made?</L>
<L>And sythen, lord, that ylke,</L>
<L N="172">Ryght as the hardnesse of chese ys hade?</L>
<L>My bloode ys nessher than ys sylke,</L>
<L>In reyny weder that sone woll fade,</L>
<L>And thus me made do dedys swylke</L>
<L N="176">With whyche my goste ys ofte vnglade.</L>
<L>And thus in sinne full depe I wade,</L>
<L>That nygh I droune thorow freelte.</L>
<L>Although I can of synne nat sade,</L>
<L N="180">Yet <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="127"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pelle <I>et</I> carnibus vestisti me, ossibus <I>et</I> neruis compegisti me.</HEAD>
<L N="181">With flesshe and felle thow hast me cladde,</L>
<L>With bones and synewes togeder knyt.</L>
<L>Lyfe and mercy of the I hadde.</L>
<L N="184">To gouerne me thow yaue me wyt.</L>
<L>To kepe thyne hestes thow me bade,</L>
<L>And seydest that I shuld, for hit,</L>
<L>In heuen blysse be euer gladde;<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="188">And yet I woll nat fro syn flytte,</L>
<L>But freelte, lord, so me smytte,</L>
<L>Vnnethe kepte ys oone for me.</L>
<L>Nat for than I pray the yet</L>
<L N="192">ffor <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vitam <I>et</I> misericordiam tribuisti michi.</HEAD>
<L N="193">Lyfe and mercy thow yaue me ay.</L>
<L>When I wold thy mercy craue,</L>
<L>Thow seydest to me nat ones nay,</L>
<L N="196">But glad was when I wold hit haue.</L>
<L>Thow were redy nyght and day</L>
<L>With mercy, lord, me to saue;</L>
<L>But I denyed hit alwey,</L>
<L N="200">So woodly syn made me to raue.</L>
<L>I seruyd syn, and was hys knaue.</L>
<L>I dyd that was ayenst me.</L>
<L>Now, lord, when I am leyde in graue,</L>
<L N="204">Than <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Et visitacio tua custodivit spiritum meum.</HEAD>
<L N="205">Thy vysitacion, lorde, hath kepte</L>
<L>My spyryte, that ys me withyn.</L>
<L>ffor when I wolde to syn haue lepte,</L>
<L N="208">Than holy grace made me to blyn.</L>
<L>And ofte tyme I haue sore wept,</L>
<L>The more grace of the to wyn.</L>
<L>And thus with wepyng haue I wypt</L>
<L N="212">My soule, lord, from dedly synne.
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Lord, late me neuer werke begynne</L>
<L>That in any wyse may displese the;</L>
<L>And, som tyme though I fro the twyn,</L>
<L N="216">Yet, lord, <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quantas habeo iniquitates <I>et</I> peccata, scelera mea atque delicta ostende michi.</HEAD>
<L N="217">What wykednes all that I haue,</L>
<L>With my synnes all on an hepe,</L>
<L>Shewe me hem, or I go to graue,</L>
<L N="220">That I for hem may sore wepe;</L>
<L>My soule, lord, that I may saue</L>
<L>ffrom the pyt of hell so depe,</L>
<L>Where synful soules tumble and raue,</L>
<L N="224">In endeles woo ataketh good kepe.</L>
<L>Toodes of hem doth crowde and crepe,</L>
<L>In suche peynes the soules be.</L>
<L>ffrom that place I may nat kepe</L>
<L N="228">Withouten <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cur faciem tuam abscondis, <I>et</I> arbitraris me inimi|cum tuum?</HEAD>
<L N="229">Why hydest thow fro me thy face</L>
<L>That ys so full of all fayrenesse?</L>
<L>I mene thys somtyme thy grace,</L>
<L N="232">That thow withdrawest and yeuest me lace.</L>
<L>As thyne enemy thow dost me chace,</L>
<L>Demyng me in grete hardnesse.</L>
<L>Thy loue fayne wold I purchase</L>
<L N="236">Yef thow wolt me hit graunte of thy goodnes.</L>
<L>Now graunte me, lord, suche stedfastnes,</L>
<L>That I may stande in oo degre,</L>
<L>And though I fall thorow brotylnes,</L>
<L N="240">Lorde, <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Contra folium quod vento rapitur, ostendis poten|ciam tuam, <I>et</I> stipulam siccam persequeris.</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="129">
<L N="241">Ayenst a leefe, that lyght ys to blowe,</L>
<L>To me that am freel of kynde,</L>
<L>Thy myght and power dost thow showe,</L>
<L N="244">As though I myght beres bynde.</L>
<L>With wyndes ofte I ouerthrowe,</L>
<L>Suche fondyng of the I fynde.</L>
<L>I renne forthe fro rowe to rowe,</L>
<L N="248">Som-tyme before, somtyme behynde.</L>
<L>I grope as a man that ys full blynde;</L>
<L>But though I stomble, thow folowest me.</L>
<L>A, lord, though I to the be vnkynde,</L>
<L N="252">Yet <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scribis enim contra me amaritudines, <I>et</I> consumere me vis peccatis adolescencie mee.</HEAD>
<L N="253">Thow wrytest, lord, ayenst me<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bytternesse, that I shall rede,</L>
<L>At domesday, in syght of the,</L>
<L N="256">And all the worlde in length and brede.</L>
<L>That I dyd in pryuyte,</L>
<L>There opynly hit owte shall sprede;</L>
<L>And thys thow wylt full well y-se,</L>
<L N="260">And distroy me for my wyked dede.</L>
<L>But, lorde, to the I clepe and grede,</L>
<L>As thow art lorde of all pyte,</L>
<L>That day when I shall drope and drede,</L>
<L N="264">Than <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Posuisti in neruo pedem meum, <I>et</I> obseruasti omnes semitas meas, <I>et</I> vestigia pedum meorum con|siderasti.</HEAD>
<L N="265">In a synew thow hast my feet sette,</L>
<L>With the whyche that I go shall,</L>
<L>And all the pathes thow hast mette</L>
<L N="268">That euer I yede in wey or walle.</L>
<L>There ys nothyng that the may lette</L>
<L>To knowe my steppes grete and smalle,</L>
<L>Wycked and worse, good and bette,</L>
<L N="272">I wote well thow considerest alle.
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>But, lorde, to the I clepe and calle;</L>
<L>When I slyde, supporte thow me;</L>
<L>And though somtyme I take a falle,</L>
<L N="276">Yet <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui quasi putredo consumendus sum, <I>et</I> quasi vestimentum, quod commeditur a tinea.</HEAD>
<L N="277">The whyche as rotyng shall consume,</L>
<L>And fare as mowthe eten cloth;</L>
<L>And as from the fyre departeth fume,</L>
<L N="280">So body and soule asundre goth.</L>
<L>I am made of a lothly hume;</L>
<L>Hit ys a thyng to man most loth.</L>
<L>Wherof than shulde I presume</L>
<L N="284">To be hygh-herted or lyghtly wroth?</L>
<L>Though I be he that ofte mys doth,</L>
<L>Of mercy art thow large and fre.</L>
<L>As I leue that thys ys soth,</L>
<L N="288">So <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOmo natus de muliere, breui viuens tempore, repletur multis miserijs,</HEAD>
<L N="289">A man that ys of a woman bore,</L>
<L>But lytell whyle he lyueth here,</L>
<L>And euery day more and more</L>
<L N="292">Replenysshed ys with synnes sere;</L>
<L>With hote and colde, and hungor sore,</L>
<L>Turmented ys from yere to yere,</L>
<L>And ofte hym wanteth goddys lore,</L>
<L N="296">That gostly wey, he shuld lere.</L>
<L>And thus he wandreth in a were,</L>
<L>As a man blynde, and may nat se.</L>
<L>Therfore I pray the, with louely chere,</L>
<L N="300">ffor <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui quasi flos egreditur <I>et</I> conteritur, <I>et</I> fugit velud vmbra, <I>et</I> nunquam in eodem statu permanet.</HEAD>
<L N="301">The whyche spryngeth oute as a floure,</L>
<L>That groweth fresshe, all men to glade;
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>But when he with a sharpe shoure</L>
<L N="304">Ys smyten, begynneth sone to fade.</L>
<L>So lese I the fayre coloure</L>
<L>That god almyghty furst in me made,</L>
<L>And thus I chaunge in euery shoure,</L>
<L N="308">And fle away ryght as a shade.</L>
<L>And herewith I am full lade</L>
<L>With synnes of diuerse degre.</L>
<L>Of heuen blysse me nought degrade,</L>
<L N="312">But <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Et dignum ducis super huiuscemodi aperire oculos tuos, <I>et</I> adducere eum tecum in iudicium.</HEAD>
<L N="313">And, lord, thow lettest that hit be dygne</L>
<L>Thyne eyen to opene vppon suche on,</L>
<L>And hym thow shewest, by that sygne,</L>
<L N="316">That he, with the, to dome shall gone.</L>
<L>Haue mercy on me, Ihesu benygne!</L>
<L>Me thynketh myn hert ys harder than a ston,<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And besyed with a spiryte maligne.</L>
<L N="320">My flesshe, the worlde, then ben my fone.</L>
<L>These ben myn enemyes, lord, echone,</L>
<L>Euer aboute to perysshe me.</L>
<L>Lorde, for the loue of Mary and Iohn</L>
<L N="324">Euer <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quis potest mundum de immundo conceptum semine? nonne tu, qui solus es?</HEAD>
<L N="325">But, lord, who may clene make</L>
<L>Conceyued thyng of seede vnclene?</L>
<L>Nat thow? A, yes, I vnderstande,</L>
<L N="328">Yef the lyste to make hit clene.</L>
<L>Allas, I walke in a lake</L>
<L>Of dedly synne that doth me tene.</L>
<L>But, lorde, for the loue of Maryes sake,</L>
<L N="332">Amende the harme that I of mene.</L>
<L>Y-wys I am nat worthe a bene,</L>
<L>Of my sylfe, to commendyd be.</L>
<L>Yet helpe me, lorde, with thy grace shene,</L>
<L N="336">And euer <I>Parce michi, domine!</I>
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="132"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Breues dies hominis sunt, numerus mensium eius apud te est.</HEAD>
<L N="337">Mennes dayes ben shorte, beware,</L>
<L>And therto take good entente;</L>
<L>ffor in respyte of tyme euermare</L>
<L N="340">They beth nothyng equipolent.</L>
<L>The nombre of hys monthes are</L>
<L>Alwey at the, lorde, verament.</L>
<L>Oure lyfe ys nought but sorow and care</L>
<L N="344">Tyll we be passed iugement.</L>
<L>My wyttes, lorde, I haue myspent,</L>
<L>That thow me yaue to rewle with me.</L>
<L>But that I may ryse vp, and here repent,</L>
<L N="348">Lorde, <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Constituisti terminos eius, qui preteriri non pote|runt.</HEAD>
<L N="349">Hys termes, lord, thow hast ordeyned,</L>
<L>How longe he shall now lyue here;</L>
<L>That may he nat passe, ne be refreyned,</L>
<L N="352">But by thyne absolute power.</L>
<L>Thys sentence may be well susteyned</L>
<L>By a story, as we may here,</L>
<L>Howe Ezechye to deth-ward peyned,</L>
<L N="356">And yet god addyd ouer xv yere.</L>
<L>Hys kyndly tyme was comen full nere,</L>
<L>But for hys synnes tho wepte he.</L>
<L>Lorde, yeue me grace, that I may here</L>
<L N="360">Haue <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Recede ergo paululum ab eo, vt quiescat, donec optata veniat, <I>et</I> sicut mercenarij dies eius.</HEAD>
<L N="361">Therfore, lord, a lytell go awey.</L>
<L>Withdrawe thyn hande, that man may rest</L>
<L>Tyll he desyre hys dethe day,</L>
<L N="364">And wylne to be shut vp in hys cheste,</L>
<L>And late hym lyue, yef hym lust ay.</L>
<L>Thys holde I, lorde, for the beste.
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>All disease from hym delay</L>
<L N="368">Tyll the careyn in erthe be keste.</L>
<L>Allas, all thys world now ys myswrest,</L>
<L>To carpe thys, lorde, ayenst the.</L>
<L>Make me to thy mercy trest,</L>
<L N="372">ffor <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quis michi hoc tribuat, vt in inferno protegas me, donec pertranseat furor tuus?</HEAD>
<L N="373">Who to me may yeue or graunte,</L>
<L>ffor loue or any affeccioun,</L>
<L>ffro thy wrathe that ys duraunte,</L>
<L N="376">I may haue my proteccioun?</L>
<L>In helle yef I be concurraunte,</L>
<L>There am I in subieccioun.</L>
<L>In heuen though thow woldest me haunte,</L>
<L N="380">Yet there am I at thy correccioun.</L>
<L>I may nat from thy respeccioun</L>
<L>By no way, lorde, hyde now me.</L>
<L>Therfore seye I thys lessoun</L>
<L N="384">Of <I>Parce michi, domine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Et constituas michi in quo recorderis mei.</HEAD>
<L N="385">And thow woldest a tyme ordeyne<MILESTONE N="13a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In whyche thow woldest of me haue mynde,</L>
<L>With som solace me to susteyne,</L>
<L N="388">That of thy blysse am so fere behynde.</L>
<L>My woo from the can I nat leyne,</L>
<L>But telle hit the, for thow art kynde.</L>
<L>I am fast bounde here with a cheyne</L>
<L N="392">Of dedly synne, full wele I fynde.</L>
<L>But woldest thow, lorde, me vnbynde</L>
<L>Thorough the vertew of thy pyte,</L>
<L>Than were I glad, and lyght as lynde,</L>
<L N="396">To haue <I>Parce michi, domine</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Putasne mortuus homo rursum viuat?</HEAD>
<L N="397">Trowest thow nat that man shal ryse</L>
<L>Ayene to lyfe, that dyed onys?</L>
<L>Yes, and that in a wonderful wyse,
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="134"></L>
<L N="400">With flesshe and felle, bloode and bones.</L>
<L>Than shal god hys dome deuyse,</L>
<L>And to hym take the good att ones;</L>
<L>But dampned soules shullen sore gryse,</L>
<L N="404">And yeue a shoute with hydous grones.</L>
<L>Thys make they shull wofull mones;</L>
<L>All that shullen dampned be,</L>
<L>That I may dwelle withyn the wones</L>
<L N="408">Of <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cunctis diebus quibus nunc milito, expecto donec veniat immutacio mea.</HEAD>
<L N="409">All the dayes that I lyue here</L>
<L>In thys wofull wepyng dale,</L>
<L>I byde alwey, from yere to yere,</L>
<L N="412">Tyll I chaunge, as men do fall.</L>
<L>Change I shall withouten were,</L>
<L>Nat ay be dwellyng in thys vale;</L>
<L>But, lorde, whan I am leyde on bere,</L>
<L N="416">Hye vp to heuen my soule hale,&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor there commyn neyther grete ne smale</L>
<L>But thow drawe hem, lorde, to the,&mdash;</L>
<L>That my soule be not in bale,</L>
<L N="420">But <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vocabis me, <I>et</I> ego respondebo tibi; operi manu|um tuarum porriges dexteram.</HEAD>
<L N="421">Thow shalt me call at domesday,</L>
<L>When thow art set on iugement,</L>
<L>And I to the, wythouten delay,</L>
<L N="424">Shall yeue my answere verament.</L>
<L>But, good Ihesu, to the I pray,</L>
<L>Thynke alwey with full entent</L>
<L>Thow madest me of a clot of clay;</L>
<L N="428">Thyne handwerke helpe, as thow furst ment;</L>
<L>And with my thought I haue myspent,</L>
<L>Thorough malyce, here, of frealte:</L>
<L>Here, leof lorde, late me repente,</L>
<L N="432">But <I>Parce michi, domine!</I>
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tu quidem gressus meos dinumerasti, sed parce peccatis meis.</HEAD>
<L N="433">fforsothe, my steppys euerychone</L>
<L>Thow nombred hast, and tolde hem all.</L>
<L>But, lorde, to the I make my mone,</L>
<L N="436">As thow art lord of heuen and hell.</L>
<L>Vertues, lorde, though I haue none,</L>
<L>Late thy grace in me now welle;</L>
<L>ffor woo ys hym that stante alone,</L>
<L N="440">And hathe noon helpe yef that he fall.</L>
<L>My syn ys bytter than eysell or gall,</L>
<L>And stynketh, lorde, in syght of the.</L>
<L>But nought for than to the I call</L>
<L N="444">ffor <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Spiritus meus attenuabitur, dies mei breuiabun|tur, <I>et</I> solum michi superest sepulcrum.</HEAD>
<L N="445">My spyryt shal be feble and feynt</L>
<L>When I am fallen in any age,</L>
<L>My dayes, make I neuer so queynt,</L>
<L N="448">Shullen abrege and somwhat swage,</L>
<L>And I ful sone shal be atteynt</L>
<L>Whan I haue loste myn hote corage;</L>
<L>And though I dyed than as doth a seynt,</L>
<L N="452">A pyt shal be myne herytage;</L>
<L>In erthe gete I non other wage<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Off all rychesse that man may se.</L>
<L>Whan I am closed in that cage,</L>
<L N="456">Than <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non peccaui, <I>et</I> in amaritudinibus moratur oculus meus.</HEAD>
<L N="457">I haue nat synned wylfully</L>
<L>Thorow my feynt, feble nature,</L>
<L>Ne greued the so greuosly,</L>
<L N="460">Wherfore I shulde thys wo endure.</L>
<L>Thow punysshest me, and I not why,</L>
<L>Passing resoun and good mesure.
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>Hit ys my flessh, lorde, and nat I,</L>
<L N="464">That grocheth ayenst thyn hard reddure.</L>
<L>But, lorde, as I am thy creature,</L>
<L>And that ylke god that boughtest me,</L>
<L>So my care recouere and cure</L>
<L N="468">With <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dies mei transierunt, cogitaciones mee dissipate sunt, torquentes cor meum.</HEAD>
<L N="469">My dayes, lorde, passed are,</L>
<L>And olde I am, I am no faunt.</L>
<L>My thoughtes wandre wyde whare,</L>
<L N="472">ffor they ben, lorde, full variaunte.</L>
<L>Myne herte they greuyn wonder sare,</L>
<L>ffor euer aboute hym they haunte.</L>
<L>Thys maketh me to drowpe and dare</L>
<L N="476">That I am lyke a pore penaunte.</L>
<L>Though I be, lorde, vnsuffisaunte,</L>
<L>Any helpe to gete of the,</L>
<L>Yet, for I am thy creaunte,</L>
<L N="480">Lorde, <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Noctem verterunt in diem, <I>et</I> rursum post tenebras spero lucem.</HEAD>
<L N="481">The nyght they turned in-to the day,</L>
<L>ffor they maden me to wake all nyght.</L>
<L>I myght nat slepe by no way,</L>
<L N="484">Suche thoughtes were in myn hert plyght.</L>
<L>In derkenesse dymme as I so lay,</L>
<L>Yet hoped I after the clere day lyght;</L>
<L>But thoughtys me so trobled ay,</L>
<L N="488">That I was than a wofull wyght.</L>
<L>But, lorde, as thow art mekyl of myght,</L>
<L>All euyll thoughtes put fro me,</L>
<L>And that I of the may haue a syght,</L>
<L N="492">Lorde, <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Si sustinuero, infernus domus mea est; in tenebris straui lectulum meum.</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="137">
<L N="493">Lorde, yef I shall suffre thys grete disese,</L>
<L>Hit woll me brynge vnto my graue.</L>
<L>And yet ywys I may nat chese,</L>
<L N="496">Whether I be kyng, knyght or knaue.</L>
<L>In derkenesse dymme, all oute of ese,</L>
<L>My lytell bed spred I haue;</L>
<L>That bed shall I neuer lese,</L>
<L N="500">Though I wolde for angor raue,</L>
<L>Tyll the day of dome, that of my graue</L>
<L>I shall aryse, and mo with me.</L>
<L>My soule, lorde, I pray, thow saue</L>
<L N="504">With <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Putredini dixi, pater meus es; mater mea <I>et</I> soror mea, vermibus.</HEAD>
<L N="505">To roten erthe, ryght thus sayde I,</L>
<L>"Thow art my fader of whom I cam,"</L>
<L>And vnto wormes sekurly,</L>
<L N="508">"Thow art my moder, thy son I am;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. am I]</NOTE></L>
<L>My systren all ye bene, for why,</L>
<L>None other then ye, forsoth I am."</L>
<L>I shall call hem sustres, lo, for thy,</L>
<L N="512">ffor I shall roote amonge hem.</L>
<L>Of the lowest erthe god made Adam,</L>
<L>Of whyche my kynde I had, as he.</L>
<L>Now, lorde, that art lykened to a lambe,</L>
<L N="516">So <I>Parce michi</I>, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vbi est ergo nunc prestolacio <MILESTONE N="14a" UNIT="folio">mea <I>et</I> paciencia mea? tu es, domine, deus meus.</HEAD>
<L N="517">Where ys myn abydyng nowe,</L>
<L>And all my pacience therto?</L>
<L>They ben away, I wote neuer howe,</L>
<L N="520">ffor sothe me wanteth bothe two</L>
<L>Yef myn hert be styf and towe,</L>
<L>To thanke the in wele and woo,</L>
<L>Hit ys nat I, but only thow,</L>
<L N="524">Thow art my lord and god also.
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="138"></L>
<L>O thow grete lord, alpha and oo,</L>
<L>Helpe me, for thy grete pyte!</L>
<L>I haue y-nowgh, I pray the, hoo,</L>
<L N="528">And <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<HEAD>PElli mee consumptis carnibus adhesit os meum, <I>et</I> derelicta sunt tantummodo labia circa dentes meos.</HEAD>
<L N="529">TO my skyn my mouth ys, lo,</L>
<L>And cleued fast, as ye se may;</L>
<L>And wasted ys my flesshe also,</L>
<L N="532">And bothe my lyppes ben away.</L>
<L>My whyte tethe, they ben full bloo.</L>
<L>Ye wolde be agaste, yef ye me say.</L>
<L>Myne heryng ys full clene ago,</L>
<L N="536">Myne eyen ben dymme, &thorn;at weren ful gray;</L>
<L>And I that was full stoute and gay,</L>
<L>ffull horyble am now opon to se.</L>
<L>Tyme ys that men now for me pray,</L>
<L N="540">ffor <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Miseremini, miseremini mei, saltem vos, amici mei, quia manus domini tetigit me.</HEAD>
<L N="541">. Reweth on me, reweth on me!</L>
<L>My frendes namly, now helpe&thorn; at nede!</L>
<L>ffor I am there I may nat fle.</L>
<L N="544">The hande of god ful sore I drede.</L>
<L>And frendes, seeth that I am he,</L>
<L>Thys other day that on the erth yede.</L>
<L>Now helpe, yef that youre wyll be,</L>
<L N="548">With prayer, fastyng, and almes-dede.</L>
<L>ffor these mowen best gete me mede</L>
<L>With Placebo And Dirige.</L>
<L>Herewith my soule I pray yow fede,</L>
<L N="552">With <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quare persequimini me sicut deus, <I>et</I> carnibus meis saturamini?</HEAD>
<L N="553">Why, as god, do ye pursewe</L>
<L>Me that suffre these sharpe shoures?
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="139"></L>
<L>Ye lat me peyne here in a peynfull pewe,</L>
<L N="556">That ys a place of grete doloures.</L>
<L>Yow I chese for frendes trewe,</L>
<L>And made yow myne executoures.</L>
<L>But tyme shall come that ye shall rewe</L>
<L N="560">That euer ye were to me so false treytoures.</L>
<L>My good ye spent, as hit were youres,</L>
<L>But nat a peny yeuyn ye me.</L>
<L>Nowe for all suche faytoures,</L>
<L N="564">Lorde, <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quis michi tribuat, vt scribantur sermones mei?</HEAD>
<L N="565">Who may graunte me thys boone,</L>
<L>That my wordes wreten were</L>
<L>In ensample of euerychon</L>
<L N="568">That hap may to ben in care?</L>
<L>ffor yef they wolden make moone,</L>
<L>Eyther groche with hert sare</L>
<L>Ayenst god, that sytteth in troone,</L>
<L N="572">Because, yef they wolden spare,</L>
<L>And make nat so ferly fare,</L>
<L>But take ensample wolden of me.</L>
<L>Now, lorde, as I am but wormes ware,</L>
<L N="576">So <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quis michi det vt exarentur in libro stilo ferreo, aut plumbi lamina vel celte sculpantur in silice?</HEAD>
<L N="577">Who shall graunt me, or I be dede,</L>
<L>To wryte hem by oon and oone,</L>
<L>My booke with ynke blak or rede,</L>
<L N="580">Made with gumme and vermylone?</L>
<L>Or ellys yet in plate of lede,</L>
<L>Or grauen in harde flynte of stone,<MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That all men, where euer they yede,</L>
<L N="584">Myght otherwhyle loke theropon?</L>
<L>I wolde my frendys and my foon</L>
<L>Ensample take myght by me.</L>
<L>As thow art thre, and god aloon,</L>
<L N="588">Now <I>Parce michi, domine!</I>
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="140"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scio enim quod redemptor meus viuit, <I>et</I> in nouis|simo die de terra surrecturus sum, et rursum circumdabor pelle mea, et in carne mea videbo deum, saluatorem meum.</HEAD>
<L N="589">I wote ryght well that myn redemptour</L>
<L>Lyueth yet, and lyue shall aye,</L>
<L>And I shall ryse, I not what oure,</L>
<L N="592">Oute of the erthe on domysdaye,</L>
<L>And take to me my furst coloure,</L>
<L>In flesshe and felle, clad on clay.</L>
<L>And so shall I see my sauyour</L>
<L N="596">Deme the worlde in wondre aray.</L>
<L>The wikked than, withouten delay,</L>
<L>As arowes, to helle they shullen fle.</L>
<L>Lorde, that I go nat that way,</L>
<L N="600">So <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quem visurus sum ego ipse, <I>et</I> oculi mei conspec|turi sunt, <I>et</I> non alius.</HEAD>
<L N="601">Whan I mysylfe shall see in syght</L>
<L>With eyen clere, and hert[e] stable,</L>
<L>And knowe hym as god almyght,</L>
<L N="604">That was for me man disparitable,</L>
<L>Shall ther fore me noon other wyght</L>
<L>Se my god that ys durable,</L>
<L>But I mysylfe, with eyen bryght,</L>
<L N="608">Shall hym beholde most honorable.</L>
<L>O lord, that charyte that ys so amyable,</L>
<L>And bryght shynyng in thy mageste,</L>
<L>That syght to se, lord, make me able,</L>
<L N="612">Thorow <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reposita est hec spes mea in sinu meo.</HEAD>
<L N="613">Thys hope ys in myn hert[e] sette,</L>
<L>That neuer from me shall dysseuere.</L>
<L>Thereyn my truste also ys knette,</L>
<L N="616">The whyche to haue now ys me leuere.</L>
<L>I hope to god that I shall gete
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>Of all diseases yet rekeuere,</L>
<L>And se my lorde in hys turete,</L>
<L N="620">With whom I hope to dwelle euer.</L>
<L>Though I be synfull, lorde, take me neuer</L>
<L>In any thyng that may displese the.</L>
<L>Thy blysse, late me haue for euer,</L>
<L N="624">Thorough <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quare de vulua eduxisti me, qui vtinam con|sumptus essem, ne oculus me videret?</HEAD>
<L N="625">lord, why leddest thow so me</L>
<L><B>A</B>, Oute of the wombe that I was in?</L>
<L>Wold god I had consumed be</L>
<L N="628">With-in myn oune moders skynne,</L>
<L>That the eye, with whyche I se,</L>
<L>Had nat seyn nomore ne mynne,</L>
<L>That I myght in that degre</L>
<L N="632">Neuer haue wyste what had be synne,</L>
<L>ffor syn maketh me from the to twynne,</L>
<L>That of nought madest thow me.</L>
<L>Thy mercy, lord, make me to wynne</L>
<L N="636">With <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<HEAD>ffuissem quasi non essem, de vtero translatus ad tumulum.</HEAD>
<L N="637">And, wold god, that I be hadde</L>
<L>As a thyng that neuer was;</L>
<L>ffor all with synne I am be-stadde,</L>
<L N="640">And euery day I do trespas.</L>
<L>No wonder though I be vngladde,</L>
<L>And though I synge often allas;</L>
<L>ffor pure woo I wexed madde,</L>
<L N="644">Nere goddys mercy my solas.</L>
<L>Lo, lorde, lo, I am ryght as</L>
<L>A wytles man withouten the;</L>
<L>But as thow of plente mercy has,<MILESTONE N="15a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="648">So <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nunquid non paucitas dierum meorum finietur breui?</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="142">
<L N="649">Whether the fewnes of my dayes</L>
<L>Shull nat hastyly haue an ende?</L>
<L>Sythen I can se by no worldly wayes,</L>
<L N="652">But oute of the world sone shal I wende,</L>
<L>The worldes wyles ryght nat me payes,</L>
<L>ffor they ben false and full vn-thende.</L>
<L>My flesshly lust my soule affrayes,</L>
<L N="656">And I am tempted with the fende.</L>
<L>Thys maketh me to bowe and bende</L>
<L>Alwey to syn, that woo ys me.</L>
<L>Lord, that art curteys and hende,</L>
<L N="660">So <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dimitte ergo me, domine, vt plangam paululum dolorem meum, antequam vadam, et non reuertar ad terram tenebrosam <I>et</I> opertam mortis caligine,</HEAD>
<L N="661">Therfore, lord, suffer thow me</L>
<L>A lytell what, that, whyl I may,</L>
<L>The tyme that euer I greved the</L>
<L N="664">In ded or thought, by nyght or day,</L>
<L>And graunt me, yef thy wyl be,</L>
<L>That here in erthe wepe I may,</L>
<L>The derke lande that I neuer se,</L>
<L N="668">That keuered ys with black alway.</L>
<L>Now, good Ihesu, to the I pray,</L>
<L>As thow art god in trinite,</L>
<L>ffrom that londe thow kepe me ay,</L>
<L N="672">Thorow <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<HEAD>Terram miserie <I>et</I> tenebrarum, vbi vmbra mortis <I>et</I> nullus ordo, sed sempiternus horror inhabitans.</HEAD>
<L N="673">The londe of myschyef and of derknes,</L>
<L>Where as dampned soules dwell,</L>
<L>The londe of woo and of wrechednesse,</L>
<L N="676">Where ben mo peynes than tonge may telle,</L>
<L>The londe of dethe and of duresse,</L>
<L>In whyche noon order may dwelle,</L>
<L>The londe of wepyng and of drerynesse,</L>
<L N="680">And stynkyng sorow on to smelle:
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>Now from that londe that cleped ys helle,</L>
<L>Worthy lord, rescue now thow me,</L>
<L>So that I maye euer with the dwelle</L>
<L N="684">Thorough <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
<L>Here endeth the ix lessons of the Dirige, which</L>
<L>Yob made in his tribulacion.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="26" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>XXVI. Here begynneth a tretyse of Parce michi, domine.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Douce</I> 322, <I>leaf</I> 15.] [19 stanzas of 8, 12 or 16, in alternates.] [A picture comes here of a man lying in a field under a tree. A dejected-looking bird stands near, with a scroll coming from its mouth, on which are the words "Parce michi."&mdash;A. F. P.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>By a forest syde, walkyng as I went,</L>
<L>Disporte to take, in o mornyng,</L>
<L>A place I fonde shadyd with bowes I-bent,</L>
<L N="4">Y-set aboute with floures so swete smellyng.</L>
<L>I leyde me doune apon that grene,</L>
<L>And caste myn eyen me aboute;</L>
<L>I fonde there byrdys with feders shene,</L>
<L N="8">Many oon sittyng apon a rowte.</L>
<L>Oon byrde there-by sate on a brere:</L>
<L>Here federes were pulled, she myght nat fle.</L>
<L>She sate and sange with mornyng chere,</L>
<L N="12">"<I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Spare me, lorde, kyng of pyte,"</L>
<L>Thus seyng thys byrde in pore aray;</L>
<L>"My myrthe ys go, and my iolyte,</L>
<L N="16">I may nat fle as other may.</L>
<L>My federes shene bene pulled me fro,</L>
<L>My youth, my streyngthe, and my beawte.</L>
<L>Wher-thorough I take thys songe me to:<MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="20"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>When I herde thys mornyng song,</L>
<L>I drewe to thys byrde nere and nere,
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>And asked who had don thys wrong,</L>
<L N="24">And brought her in so drowpyng chere,</L>
<L>And who had pulled her feders awey,</L>
<L>That shuld her bere from tre to tre,</L>
<L>And why she sange in her lay</L>
<L N="28"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>The byrde answered, and seyde me tyll,</L>
<L>"Man, be in pese, for crystes sake.</L>
<L>Yef I shewe the myn hertys wyll,</L>
<L N="32">Peynes me sore woll awake.</L>
<L>Yef thow wolt take my worde in mynde,</L>
<L>There shall no sorow be my lettyng,</L>
<L>That I nyll holy myne herte vnbynde,</L>
<L N="36">And sothely telle the thyne askyng,</L>
<L>Whyche were my feders that were so clere,</L>
<L>And who hath pulled hem all fro me,</L>
<L>And why I syt singyng on brere</L>
<L N="40"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>ffeders iiij I had y-wys,</L>
<L>The two were set on euery wynge.</L>
<L>They bare me breme to my blys,</L>
<L N="44">Where me lust be at my lykyng.</L>
<L>The furst was 'youth,' the ij<SUP>de</SUP> 'beawte,'</L>
<L>'Streyngth' and 'ryches' the other two.</L>
<L>And now they been, as thow mayst se,</L>
<L N="48">All iiij federes fallen me fro.</L>
<L>My principall federe, youthe hit was.</L>
<L>He bare me ofte to nysete;</L>
<L>Wherefore my songe ys now, allas,</L>
<L N="52"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>In youthe I wrought folyes fele,</L>
<L>My hert was set so hygh in pryde,</L>
<L>To synne I yaue me euerydele,</L>
<L N="56">Spared I neyther tyme ne tyde.</L>
<L>I was redy to make debate.</L>
<L>My lyfe stode ofte in mechyll drede;
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>And my lykyng, to walke late,</L>
<L N="60">And haue my luste of sinfull dede.</L>
<L>I was now here, I was now there,</L>
<L>Vnstable I was in all degre.</L>
<L>To hym I crye, that Mary bare,</L>
<L N="64"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>ffor Salamon seyth in his poyse,</L>
<L>Thre weyes there beth full harde to knowe:</L>
<L>Oon ys a shyp that sayleth in the see,</L>
<L N="68">An egle an hygh, a worme in lowe.</L>
<L>And of the fourth, telle he ne can:</L>
<L>Hit ys so wonderfull in hys heryng,</L>
<L>The weyes of a yonge man,</L>
<L N="72">Whyche that ben here at theyre lykyng.</L>
<L>And now hathe age y-smete me fro</L>
<L>My pryncipall feder of Iolyte.</L>
<L>ffor all that euer I haue mys-do,</L>
<L N="76"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>My ij<SUP>de</SUP> feder hyght 'bewte.'</L>
<L>I helde my selfe so clere of shappe,</L>
<L>That all the peple shuld loke on me,</L>
<L N="80">And worshyp me with hood and cappe.</L>
<L>My rudde was rede, my colour clere,</L>
<L>Me thought neuer none so fayre as I,</L>
<L>In all a contre, ferre ne nerre,</L>
<L N="84">In fetewres and shap so comly.</L>
<L>My forhede large, my browes bent;</L>
<L>My eyen clere, and corage bolde.</L>
<L>My shappe ne myght no man amende,</L>
<L N="88">Me thought my self so fayre to beholde.</L>
<L>And yet I was begyled in syght.</L>
<L>The myrrour, lorde, disceued me.</L>
<L>Wherfore I aske, lorde, of thy myght,</L>
<L N="92"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>Thys feder me bare full ofte to synne,</L>
<L>And pryncipally to lechery.
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="146"></L>
<L>Clyppyng and kyssyng cowde I nat blynne,</L>
<L N="96">Me thought hit crafte of curtesy.</L>
<L>A cusse, hit ys the deuylles gynne;</L>
<L>Ofte of hit aryseth woo and wrake.</L>
<L>The deuyll with cusse many doth wynne.</L>
<L N="100">I counseyle the, thow syn forsake.</L>
<L>Sampson loste hys streyngth therfore,<MILESTONE N="16a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Dauid hys grace, for bersabee,</L>
<L>Tyll he cryed with wordes sore</L>
<L N="104"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Salamon, that worthy kyng,</L>
<L>ffull fayre he was from top to toe,</L>
<L>Wherfore in hys age yong</L>
<L N="108">He was <I>amabilis domino;</I></L>
<L>That after he felle foule and sore</L>
<L>ffor luste of wemen that was hym nygh.</L>
<L>They fonned hym in hys age hore,</L>
<L N="112">That he forsoke hys god on hygh.</L>
<L>Nat oonly these, but many mo</L>
<L>Bewte hath begyled, ywys.</L>
<L>I wote well I am oon of tho;</L>
<L N="116">I can the better telle thys.</L>
<L>Nowe hathe age y-smyte me fro</L>
<L>My secund feder, that hyght beawte.</L>
<L>ffor all that euer I haue mysdo,</L>
<L N="120"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>My thryd feder, 'streynght' hyght.</L>
<L>My name was knowe on euery syde,</L>
<L>ffor I was man of mochell myght,</L>
<L N="124">And meny oon spake of me full wyde.</L>
<L>To pryke and praunce I was full prest,</L>
<L>My streyngthe to kepe in euery place;</L>
<L>And euermore I had the best:</L>
<L N="128">Suche was my hap, suche was my grace.</L>
<L>My streyngth full ofte me drowe amys,</L>
<L>And torned me, lorde, clene fro the.</L>
<L>Now, kyng crouned in heuen blys,</L>
<L N="132"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I>
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="147"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Thys feder bare me beyonde the see,</L>
<L>To gete me name in vncouth lande.</L>
<L>To robbe and slee, had I deynte,</L>
<L N="136">Ne spared I neyther for no bande.</L>
<L>Of holy churche toke I no yeme,</L>
<L>Bokes to take, ne vestement.</L>
<L>There myght nothyng so moche me queme</L>
<L N="140">As robbe, or se an abbey brente.</L>
<L>With streyngth I gate me grete aray,</L>
<L>Precious clothes, golde, and fee.</L>
<L>I thought full lytell on that day,</L>
<L N="144"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>When Nabugodonozor, ferse in fyght,</L>
<L>Ierusalem had thought to wynne,</L>
<L>And so he dyd with mayne and myght,</L>
<L N="148">And brent the temples that were theryn,</L>
<L>And all the golde that he there founde,</L>
<L>He toke with hym, and home gan ryde,</L>
<L>Hym thought there shuld nothyng withstonde;</L>
<L N="152">Hys hert was sette so hygh in pryde,</L>
<L>Tyll the kyng of myghtes moste</L>
<L>Brought hym there that lowest was,</L>
<L>And caught hym from hys ryall hoste,</L>
<L N="156">And drofe hym to a wyldernesse.</L>
<L>And there he lyuyd with herbe and rote,</L>
<L>Walkyng euer on foot and on honde,</L>
<L>Tyll cryste of mercy dede hym bote,</L>
<L N="160">And hys pryson oute of bonde.</L>
<L>Than sayde thys kyng these wordys y-wys:</L>
<L>'All thyng be, lorde, at thy pouste;</L>
<L>Mercy I crye, I haue do mys;</L>
<L N="164"><I>Parce michi, domine!'</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>Whyle I had my streyngth at wyll,</L>
<L>ffull many a man I dyd vnreste.</L>
<L>They that wold nat myne heste fulfyll,</L>
<L N="168">My knyfe was redy to hys breste.
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>And nowe I syt here blynde and lame,</L>
<L>And croked ben my lymes all.</L>
<L>I was full wylde, I am now tame.</L>
<L N="172">Thys feder of streyngth ys fro me fall.</L>
<L>And now hathe age smetyn me fro</L>
<L>My thryd feder of iolyte.</L>
<L>ffor all that euer I haue mysdo,</L>
<L N="176"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>My fourth feder, 'Ryches' was.</L>
<L>To make hit shyne, I trauayled sore.</L>
<L>I wente in many a perylous place,</L>
<L N="180">Well ofte my lyfe was nygh for-lore.<MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By dale, by doune, by wodes syde,</L>
<L>I boode many a bytter shoure;</L>
<L>In salt see I sayled well wyde</L>
<L N="184">ffor to multiply my tresoure.</L>
<L>With false sleyghtes I gate my good,</L>
<L>In Couetyse I grounded me.</L>
<L>Ihesu, for thy precious blood,</L>
<L N="188"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>When I was seker of golde y-nowgh,</L>
<L>I gan to ryde abowte well faste.</L>
<L>I purchased moche, and god wote howgh.</L>
<L N="192">I wende thys lyfe wolde euer haue laste.</L>
<L>I lete me bylde castelles and toures,</L>
<L>Withoute y-warded with stronge dyches,</L>
<L>Withyn y-bylde halles and bowres;</L>
<L N="196">There was no toure my castell lyche.</L>
<L>In thys was set all my lykyng,</L>
<L>And torned me, lorde, holy from the.</L>
<L>To the I crye now, heuen kyng,</L>
<L N="200"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>When I was most in all my flowres,</L>
<L>And had aboute me wyfe and chylde,</L>
<L>I lost my catell and my toures.</L>
<L N="204">Then wexed myn hert in party mylde.
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>Catell felle fro me sodeynly;</L>
<L>Ryght as hit came, hit went awey.</L>
<L>Men seyen 'good geten vntrewly,</L>
<L N="208">The iij<SUP>de</SUP> eyre browke hit ne may.'</L>
<L>I was full wylde, I am now tame.</L>
<L>ffortune hath pulled ryches fro me.</L>
<L>Your wreche, lorde, I cannat blame.</L>
<L N="212"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>Iob was rycher then euer was I,</L>
<L>Of golde, syluer, and o&thorn;er good;</L>
<L>Hit felle hym fro, and that sharply,</L>
<L N="216">As dyd the water out of the flood.</L>
<L>Hym was nat lefte so mekyll a clothe</L>
<L>Hys naked body for to hele.</L>
<L>Hym lacked crostys of a lofe,</L>
<L N="220">When hym lyste ete in tyme of mele.</L>
<L>And yet he helde vp then hys hande,</L>
<L>And seyde, 'hygh god in mageste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Line 222 is repeated after line 223.</NOTE></L>
<L>I thanke the of thy swete sande.</L>
<L N="224"><I>Parce michi, domine!</I>'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>Now <I>Parce michi, domine!</I></L>
<L>My ioy, my myrthe, ys all agone.</L>
<L>Youthe, streyngth, and my beawte,</L>
<L N="228">My federes fayre, be fall me fro.</L>
<L>Wherto ys a man more lyke,</L>
<L>Then to a floure that spryngeth in may?</L>
<L>All that lyuen, bothe pore and ryche,</L>
<L N="232">Shall dye, vnknowyng of her day."</L>
<L>I set me doune apon my kne,</L>
<L>And thanked thys byrde of here good lore.</L>
<L>I bethought me well, of thys worde <I>parce</I>,</L>
<L N="236">Was bale and bote of gostly sore.</L>
<L>Now <I>parce</I>, lorde, and spare thow me,</L>
<L>Thys ys a worde that sone geteth grace.</L>
<L>And <I>parce</I> geteth goddys pyte,</L>
<L N="240">And sheweth to vs hys blessed face.</L>
<TRAILER>Amen.</TRAILER>
</LG>
